<FIRST>r a PM-LightsOut     01-26 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lights Out,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Motorist Drives by Flashlight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some people dine by candlelight or enjoy
walking in the moonlight, but Barbara and Tibor Bathony never
expected to drive by flashlight.
   When the headlights on their truck failed in ice fog at nearly 60
degrees below zero eight miles from the tiny town of Tok, the couple
drove the rest of the way with the guiding light of a household
flashlight shining through the windshield.
   ``It was like a whiteout and you try to wave the fog away,'' Mrs.
Bathony said. ``We were trying to see a little better and we turned
the high beam on and all the lights went bad.''
   Mrs. Bathony moved to Juneau in September and was in Fairbanks
last weekend to get the last of her household belongings. She and
her husband left Fairbanks on Sunday in their truck, towing a rented
flatbed and carrying three dogs for the 600-mile trip to Juneau.
   It was minus 53 degrees when they left Fairbanks, minus 57 when
they stopped in the town of North Pole and by the time they reached
Tok about 175 miles southeast, ``none of the thermometers could be
read any more,'' she said.
   There was little traffic, which made it easier to drive by
flashlight when the truck's headlight fuse blew, she said.
   ``Nobody was as dumb as we were to leave at that temperature.''
</TEXT>
