<FIRST>r i PM-NukePanic     01-26 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuke Panic,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazilian Town Panics After Lightning Sets Off Alarm at Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A thunderstorm set off an alarm
near Brazil's only nuclear power plant, causing thousands of people
to flee a nearby town in panic, civil defense officials said.
   A hilltop siren went off Monday night in the town of Frade, 115
miles southwest of Rio and four miles from the plant.
   Civil Defense Coordinator Elio Serafim said the siren sounded for
about 40 minutes during a thunderstorm and caused ``total
pandemonium'' in the town of 5,000 people.
   ``People thought it was a real emergency and ran to the gas
station, which is the agreed-on meeting point in the evacuation
plan. But when help didn't come, they panicked and tried to escape
any way they could,'' Serafim said by telephone from Angra dos Reis,
a seaside resort city near Frade.
   ``There were 3,000 or 4,000 people running through the streets,
trying to break into cars and trucks to escape. It was complete
chaos,'' Serafim said. The nuclear power plant, meanwhile, had been
shut down for maintenance, he said.
   Civil defense officials tried to call Frade but the town's only
telephone wasn't working and a fuse had burned out in the community
radio post, said Serafim.
   ``We got there about an hour later and were almost lynched.
People were shouting and trying to overturn our car. They were
really upset _ and with good reason,'' he said.
</TEXT>
