<FIRST>r a AM-Julius-Execution     01-26 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Julius-Execution,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Halts Julius Execution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Wednesday stayed the
scheduled execution of death row inmate Arthur James Julius, saying
the courts need more time to address last-minute claims raised by
his attorneys.
   Assistant Attorney General Ed Carnes said the ruling by U.S.
District Judge Truman Hobbs meant Julius' execution, set for Friday,
would be delayed at least a month, possibly much longer.
   Hobbs' decision came after Gov. Guy Hunt refused to grant
clemency for Julius, whose mother and other relatives met with Hunt
earlier in the day.
   Julius was scheduled to be electrocuted at 12:01 a.m. Friday for
the 1978 murder of his cousin, Susie Bell Sanders.
   Ms. Sanders was strangled and sexually assaulted at her
Montgomery home while Julius was free on an eight-hour pass from a
prison work-release center. At the time of the killing, he was
serving a life sentence for a 1972 slaying.
   At issue before Hobbs were defense attorneys' claims that
prosecutors failed to turn over all the materials they had
concerning the 1978 slaying.
   A Montgomery County judge had refused Monday to halt Julius'
execution, and both the Alabama Court of Criminal Appeals and the
Alabama Supreme Court issued similar rulings Tuesday.
   Alabama's last execution was Aug. 28, 1987, when Wayne Eugene
Ritter was electrocuted for his non-triggerman role in the slaying
of a Mobile pawn shop owner.
</TEXT>
