<FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0836 01-26 0879</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0836,0907</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS Collins and Norris; Separates moved for AMs as a0702 on
Basnett and as a0405 on Collins. Basnett also moved on the business wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Lord Basnett</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lord Basnett, a former trade union leader often
blamed by his fellow Laborites for helping to put Conservative
Margaret Thatcher in power, died Wednesday. He was 64.
   Basnett, who flew Sunderland flying boats in World War II, was
leader of Britain's third-largest union, the 800,000-member General
and Municipal Workers, until he retired in 1986.
   As one of the most powerful union leaders, Basnett forced Edward
Heath, then Conservative prime minister, to abandon a ban on pay
negotiations during an official wage freeze policy in 1973.
   But his union's militancy against pay restraint under a Labor
government in 1978 led to the ``winter of discontent'' when
hospitals were strikebound and the dead went unburied.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>J. Floyd Andrews</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J. Floyd Andrews, 69, a former World War II
pilot who later helped start one of the nation's most successful
commuter airlines, died Wednesday.
   A pilot in the Royal Air Force during World War II, Andrews
helped to start PSA in 1949. In the airline's early days, he
sometimes would take over the controls of one of the carrier's DC-3s
to fly passengers between San Diego and San Francisco.
   Named PSA president in 1962, Andrews tried to instill a family
spirit among the workers and he insisted no one address him as Mr.
Andrews. He also helped institute one of first frequent-flier
programs, offering discounted fares or free trips for the airline's
regular customers.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Gilbert Voss</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marine biologist Gilbert Voss, a champion of
Florida's coral reefs who recently raised public concern about
damage to the marine treasure, died Monday of cancer at age 70.
   Voss was a professor of biological oceanography at the University
of Miami's Rosentiel School of Marine and Atmospheric Sciences since
1951 and editor of Sea Frontiers magazine, published by the
International Oceanographic Foundation.
   Voss suggested in the 1950s that South Florida's reefs be
preserved and enlisted Miami Herald editor John Pennekamp in the
campaign. Pennekamp's name now graces a state park that protects
miles of threatened reefs.
   Voss also was recognized as an expert on octopus and squid
fisheries.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Bruce Penny</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bruce Penny, 68, former Sunday editor of the
Seattle Post-Intelligencer, a founder of the state's American Legion
newspaper and a decorated World War II bomber pilot died Monday
following a brief illness.
   Penny began a 32-year career at the P-I in May 1949, starting out
as copy editor before becoming telegraph editor, then picture
editor. In 1956 he was named Sunday editor.
   During World War II Penny flew 30 B-17 bombing missions over
France, Holland and Germany. He was awarded the Silver Star and
Distinguished Flying Cross. He retired from the Air Force reserve
with the rank of colonel.
   Penny who edited the Washington State Legionnaire from 1968 to
1984, won at least six national awards for his editiorials.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Nathan Jacobs</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nathan Jacobs, a former New Jersey Supreme
Court Justice died Wednesday. He was 83.
   Jacobs was a Rutgers University professor and a Superior Court
appellate judge before his appointment to the Supreme Court by Gov.
Alfred Driscoll.
   After reorganization of the state judiciary sent him back to the
appeals court briefly, Jacobs returned to the high court in 1952 and
served until his retirement in 1975.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>James Collins</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Francis Collins, a retired Army general
and a former president of the American Red Cross, died Sunday of
cancer at age 83.
   During World War II, Collins served in the Pacific and was
transferred to the Washington area in 1946. He joined the faculty at
the Army War College in 1950 and later was an executive assistant
and special assistant to the assistant secretary of defense for
manpower and personnel.
   From 1954 to 1957, Collins commanded two infantry divisions and
was commanding general of Army forces in Alaska. For the next four
years, he was assistant deputy and chief of staff for army personnel.
   Collins was appointed to the rank of four-star general in 1961
and was named commander-in-chief of Army forces in the Pacific. He
retired in 1964 and became president of the Red Cross and retired in
1970.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Clarence Norris</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clarence Norris, the last survivor of the
``Scottsboro Boys'' rape case which became a symbol of racial
injustice in the Deep South in the 1930s, died Monday. He was 76.
   The ``Scottsboro Boys'' case involved nine black teen-agers who
were accused of raping two white women in Alabama in 1931. Following
one of a series of trials, which went on until 1937, one of the
women withdrew her accusation.
   Norris was sentenced to death three times and spent 15 years in
prison. He was then a fugitive from justice for 30 years after he
violated his parole and fled Alabama. He came to New York City,
where he worked as a warehouseman.
   In 1976, when Norris was 64 years old, the Alabama Pardon and
Parole Board unanimously found that Norris was innocent of rape
charges. Then-Gov. George C. Wallace signed the pardon order.
</TEXT>
