<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 0213EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Housing-Congress     01-26 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Housing-Congress,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Optimistic About Prospects for Housing Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressmen say they believe the Bush
administration will pay more attention to housing problems than
Reagan did, and several bills are in the works to outline the
programs and find ways to pay for them.
   Being counted among the reasons for optimism is Bush's selection
of a former member of the House, Jack Kemp, for secretary of Housing
and Urban Development.
   ``I'm delighted he has been chosen,'' Sen. Alan Cranston,
D-Calif., chairman of the housing subcommittee of the Senate
Committee on Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs, said Wednesday. ``I
think he's very bright and knows how the legislative process works.''
   Cranston said he and other members of the committee have met with
Kemp and feel he is interested in housing problems and receptive to
their ideas despite differences they have with some of Kemp's past
proposals.
   Kemp has supported the transfer and sale of public housing to
tenants, housing vouchers as a way of giving low-income tenants
expanded choices in the private market and urban enterprise zones to
encourage economic development in the inner cities.
   Cranston and New York Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, the ranking
Republican on the housing panel, plan to co-sponsor a comprehensive
housing bill designed to help the homeless, the first-time
homembuyer, low-and moderate-income people and the elderly and
handicapped.
   The proposal would cost $3.1 billion in the first year, Cranston
said, but ``you can't do anything without funds.''
   Many on Capitol Hill say they're encouraged that Bush and Kemp
seem amenable to restoring some federal funds that had been cut
under Reagan.
   Federal funds for low-income housing have been cut 75 percent
since 1981, and Reagan's 1990 budget request includes only half the
funding authorized by Congress under the Stewart B. McKinney
Homeless Assistance Act.
   Bush pledged full funding of the McKinney Act during the
presidential campaign, and Kemp has said he believes the 1986 tax
reform may have gone too far in reducing incentives for the
construction and rehabilitation of affordable housing.
   Legislation being developed by Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell, D-Maine, and Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., would begin to
address Kemp's concern by making permanent the tax credits which
were set to expire at the end of this year for investors in
low-income housing.
   Bills introduced in the House would duplicate some of the efforts
in the Senate by establishing a national housing trust to provide
assistance to first-time homebuyers, make grants to local
governments to convert closed school building to shelters for the
homeless and expand current programs to provide federal asssitance
for the homeless.
</TEXT>
