<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--ReaganLawsuit     01-26 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Reagan Lawsuit,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suit Settled over Barring Of Protesters from 1984 Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Reagan's re-election committee
agreed to pay $25,000 to settle a free-speech lawsuit by 17
protesters who were barred from a 1984 campaign rally, attorneys say.
   Under the out-of-court settlement reached Tuesday, the
demonstrators will receive $800 apiece after legal fees and costs,
plaintiffs' attorney Robert Newman said Wednesday.
   The Reagan-Bush '84 Committee admitted no wrongdoing in the
settlement of the U.S. District Court lawsuit, said committee
attorney W. Stuart Dornette.
   Police and Secret Service agents, saying they were acting at the
request of rally organizers, barred the 17 from the Aug. 20, 1984,
event at the public Fountain Square Plaza because they were carrying
anti-Reagan signs, the plaintiffs said.
   Those permitted inside metal barriers set up to restrict access
to the square were given pro-Reagan signs, the lawsuit said.
</TEXT>
