<FIRST>r a PM-Bundy-TapeBurner     01-26 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bundy-Tape Burner,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Burns X-Rated Tapes After Seeing Bundy Interview</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bundy, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEDFORD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convenience store owner says he set fire to
hundreds of X-rated videotapes after seeing a television interview
in which serial killer Ted Bundy said he was ``guided and shaped''
by pornography.
   ``They're rotten filth,'' Kenneth Patterson said Wednesday before
igniting a barrel filled with the tapes. ``I don't want to send them
back. I want to burn them. I just want to pour a can of gasoline on
them. I don't want anyone to see them.''
   Bundy, who confessed to murdering 23 women, was executed in
Florida on Tuesday for the 1978 rape and murder of a 12-year-old
girl.
   In an interview with religious broadcaster James C. Dobson
shortly before his death, the 42-year-old Bundy said he was
influenced by an addiction to hard-core pornography. Pornography, he
warned, ``can reach out and snatch a kid out of any house today.''
   ``He said there's people like him who watch these movies and a
part of their brain snaps,'' said Patterson, a father of two. ``You
think of your kids, other people's kids. We just discontinued
renting them and any kind of pornography completely.''
   ``I don't need it. Society doesn't need it. We're going to stick
with the family type.''
   Patterson, who has been renting X-rated movies at his Bedford
Minute Market for about five years, said he doesn't care if he loses
customers.
   ``I don't want any part of this type of garbage,'' he said.
   ``Those kids are more important than money. I might lose some
business but I think I'll gain in the long run. Money is not the
question,'' said Patterson, who didn't specify how much the tapes
had cost him.
</TEXT>
