<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     01-26 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veteran Democrat and a newly elected Republican
have a name recognition problem: Voters are having trouble keeping
Richard Kraus and Robert Kraus apart.
   The Republican, state Rep. Robert Kraus of Kingston, said he's
received mail from constituents miffed by political stands taken by
the Democrat, state Sen. Richard Kraus of Arlington. Arlington, a
suburb of Boston, is about 40 miles northwest of Kingston.
   Robert Kraus wrote a letter to the editor of The Patriot Ledger
in Quincy to explain who he is _ and to assure them that he's not
the Kraus who's working on a proposal to replace local property
taxes with income taxes.
   ``Let there be no mistake _ Sen. Richard Kraus and Rep. Robert
Kraus are not related by blood or by agreement on this matter,''
Robert Kraus wrote.
   Richard Kraus said he expected trouble after the election.
   ``I knew when a Robert Kraus appeared on the scene there was
likely to be a lot of confusion,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VICKSBURG, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vicksburg's leaders know a bargain when
they see one, and they aren't afraid to do things a little
differently.
   So it was that Mayor Robert Walker and two city aldermen managed
to grab a new police precinct station for just $1 this week before
it rolled out of town.
   The station is a caboose.
   The officials bought it from the Mid-South Rail Corp. and plan to
use it to increase the police presence in a southern section of the
historic river city.
   ``It will be a little different, but I think it will complement
other things in the area,'' Walker said.
   Police Chief Lamar Davidson said one person, a
receptionist-dispatcher, will occupy the caboose full time and
patrol officers will use it as a base.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SOUTH HADLEY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Head librarians at Mount Holyoke
College tend to have long tenures, but Anne Edmonds is retiring
after only a quarter century on the job, a little short of the
average.
   Edmonds, 64, is only the fourth head librarian at the women's
college since Mary Olivia Nutting took the job 119 years ago. She
said she plans to retire when the library's addition is complete, in
about two years.
   The average tenure of Edmond's three predecessors was 31.3 years.
   Nutting, who kept the job for 31 years, was followed by Bertha E.
Blakely, who served 35 years. Even after her retirement, Blakely
came in every day for 25 years to build the college's extensive
archives, Edmonds said.
   Next came Flora Belle Ludington, who held the post 28 years
before Edmonds took over in 1964.
   Edmonds attributed the long terms of her predecessors to the fact
that library administration was a man's field until recently and was
hard for a woman to move around in. That trend has since reversed.
</TEXT>
