<FIRST>r w PM-Sullivan-Abortion     01-26 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sullivan-Abortion,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservatives Say They're Satisfied with Sullivan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's embattled nominee as health
secretary won support from a cadre of conservative anti-abortion
senators after telling them he backs the president's position to
reverse the Supreme Court decision legalizing abortion.
   Louis W. Sullivan's meeting Wednesday with the conservative
senators followed reports by others on Capitol Hill that he had
voiced support for the 1973 Roe. Vs. Wade decision.
   Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., said Sullivan convinced him
otherwise. Humphrey said that ``on the basis of this meeting'' he
had no reservations about Sullivan to head the Department of Health
and Human Services.
   Sullivan also received a renewed vote of support from the
president.
   ``He has supported my position 100 percent,'' Bush said Wednesday
in an interview with newspaper reporters, adding the chances were
``none'' that he would withdraw the nomination.
   ``I've not heard anyone suggesting that he will not be
confirmed,'' Bush said.
   The dispute underscored the dilemma of Senate Republicans who do
not want anyone at HHS with views other than their own on the
abortion issue but who hesitate to oppose confirmation of Bush's
only black Cabinet nominee.
   ``It would be an embarrassment to the president, an embarrassment
to the Republican Party, if the nomination encountered any trouble
and we don't want that,'' Humphrey had said on Tuesday.
   In a bid to placate the anti-abortionists, White House chief of
staff John Sununu said Wednesday that Sullivan had suggested
Constance Horner, a former Regan administration personnel director
whose anti-abortion views are well known, as his chief deputy at HHS.
   Humphrey said he was satisfied that the new secretary be
surrounded by aides ``who would actively support the president on
abortion.''
   The issue of Sullivan's abortion views resurfaced earlier this
week after Sen. Bob Packwood of Oregon, a pro-choice Republican,
said that in a recent meeting Sullivan had expressed his personal
support for Roe vs. Wade.
   As recently as Monday, when thousands of anti-abortion protestors
marched to mark the 16th anniversary of the high court's decision,
Bush reaffirmed his opposition to abortion and called for the
decision's reversal.
   Sullivan himself has said little publicly.
   ``Once the hearings go forward, everything will be cleared,'' he
said Wednesday after meeting with senators including abortion
opponents Jesse Helms of North Carolina, Orrin Hatch of Utah, James
McClure of Idaho and William Armstrong of Colorado.
   Also attending was a conservative who has taken a pro-choice
position for many years _ Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo. _ who agreed
with the others that Sullivan had expressed opposition to Roe vs.
Wade.
   He said the nominee ``not only feels that as a designee of George
Bush but as a person.''
   Simpson said Sullivan would spell out his position in a written
statement that would be made public.
   ``He never quite knew what was waiting for him here,'' said
Simpson. ``He was trying to, maybe like a doctor would, explain his
diagnosis.''
</TEXT>
