<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 0317EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceRecruiting     01-26 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Recruiting,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlanta Police Come To Mississippi Seeking Recruits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX DOMINGUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlanta police recruiters are beating the
bushes in the Deep South, offering pay hikes of up to $8,000 just to
keep officers on the streets of one of the nation's fastest growing
cities.
   The department has tried to hire 200 officers for each of the
last two years. Last year, it was able to come up with only 119
candidates and the recruiters are blaming competition with
neighboring counties, which are growing along with Atlanta.
   ``You've got to realize we've got 17 counties to compete
against,'' recruiter R.E. Gordon said during a week-long stop here.
``A lot of the growth is in the suburbs and they need employees,
too.''
   A new precinct planned to open this year and an annual attrition
rate of about 140 officers has the Atlanta police department
scrambling to find recruits. Last February, five recruiters from the
1,400-officer department began making out-of-state trips to find new
officers.
   ``We pick our destination cities based on population, schools and
the economy. There's no sense going to Coral Gables, Florida, where
they pay officers $35,000 a year and we're offering $22,000,''
recruiter M.H. Gray said. ``A lot of people in cities like Jackson
start at minimum wage or $4.50 and it's hard to make a living or
have anything.''
   The Jackson police department pays just over $14,000 a year to
first-year police officers, who must have at least two years of
college, compared with $21,392 for first-year Atlanta officers, who
do not need a degree. Officers with two years of college receive
$22,237 to start in Atlanta, recruiters said.
   The recruiters said they do not actively seek out local police
officers, but will test any applicant interested.
   Gordon said the majority of Atlanta recruits do not come from
police departments in the cities they visit.
   Last year, recruiters visited 19 cities, including Fayetteville,
N.C., Columbia, S.C., Louisville, Ky. and Nashville, Tenn., Gordon
said. Nine trips are planned this year, the recruiters said.
   Gordon said 141 people had picked up applications by Wednesday
morning. About 75 were expected to be tested today with 30
eventually hired from Jackson, Gordon said.
   One applicant said Wednesday he has been trying to find a job
with various law enforcement agencies in Mississippi for the past
eight months.
   ``Mississippi just doesn't have the funds available,'' said Kevin
Iosty, 21, an electrician who traveled about 85 miles from Laurel to
apply. ``This is a career I've been wanting to pursue for a long
time and Mississippi just doesn't have the opportunities.''
</TEXT>
