<FIRST>r i PM-Argentina     01-26 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Argentina,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alfonsin Gives Military Voice In Internal Security</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Raul Alfonsin has
created a national security council that includes the three military
chiefs of staff, giving the rightist armed forces a voice in
Argentine internal security.
   The action late Wednesday came in response to a guerrilla assault
on a suburban army base that left 36 people dead, most of them
leftist extremists, authorities said. In his decree, Alfonsin said
he formed the council to advise him on ``anti-subversive action.''
   In addition to the army, air force and navy chiefs, it includes
the defense, interior and foreign relations ministers, the state
intelligence chief, a secretary to be designated by the president
and Alfonsin.
   The president may add other members to the council at his
discretion.
   The rightist military has long pressed for a role in determining
internal security policy, but Alfonsin had refused under pressure
from human rights groups and the political left, which fears a
resurgence of anti-leftist repression.
   The government says at least 8,900 suspected subversives vanished
without a trace in the 1970s during the military's ``dirty war''
campaign to rid the country of leftists. Human rights groups say up
to 30,000 people actually were abducted and are presumed to have
been killed by security forces.
   Since Alfonsin was elected president 5{ years ago, military
tensions have been on the rise, especially since April 1987.
   Alfonsin has faced three uprisings in the last 21 months by
right-wing elements in the army infuriated by the human rights
trials of military officials accused of atrocities during the armed
forces' 1976-83 rule.
   The decree said Monday's attack on the 3rd Infantry Regiment's
base, the first leftist guerrilla action in more than a decade, made
necessary ``the taking of decisions conducive to efficiently
preventing, controlling and stifling a repetition of these events.''
   A heavily armed group assaulted the infantry base in suburban La
Tablada and it was retaken after a 27-hour siege by army and police
forces backed by tanks, helicopter gunships and artillery.
   Seven soldiers, one policeman and 28 guerrillas were killed.
Another 68 people were wounded, and 19 guerrillas were captured,
authorities said.
   Also Wednesday, Attorney General Andres D'Alessio said
investigations revealed the dead included Jorge Caldu, a member of
the defunct People's Revolutionary Army, known by its Spanish
initials ERP.
   The ERP, a Marxist guerrilla group active in the 1970s, was
virtually wiped out in a harsh anti-subversion campaign after the
military seized power in 1976.
   Another victim was Manuel Banos, a leader of the Movement
Everyone for the Country, a small leftist organization known to
include former ERP militants. Another leader of the movement, Juan
Burgos, was among those captured.
   The guerrillas were believed to be seeking to attract popular
support by staging a raid on the regiment, thus showing their
militant opposition to right-wing elements in the armed forces.
   The group called itself the Popular Resistance Front.
</TEXT>
