<FIRST>r w PM-CongressRdp Bjt   01-26 0841</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress Rdp, Bjt,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitchell Agenda Democratic at Home, Bipartisan Abroad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. George Mitchell used his inaugural address
as Senate majority leader to offer President Bush ``true
bipartisanship'' on foreign policy while pushing a distinctly
Democratic agenda on domestic issues.
   The Maine Democrat's proposals include boosting the minimum wage,
improving the lot of the homeless, assuring day care for the
children of workers and investing in education, housing and
improving the environment.
   Mitchell said that while Bush recognized many of these needs in
his presidential inaugural address last Friday, ``he has yet to tell
us how he proposes to meet them.''
   On the Senate's first working day of the 101st Congress,
Mitchell, Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas and other
senators jammed the legislative hopper with some 300 bills, some
retreads from the past, some representing new initiatives.
   The Senate also unanimously confirmed the first of President
Bush's Cabinet choices, all by identical 99-0 roll call votes. Only
Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., was not present to vote.
   The first three confirmed members of the Bush Cabinet are
Secretary of State James A. Baker III, Secretary of Labor Elizabeth
Hanford Dole and budget director Richard Darman.
   Mitchell presented a Democratic view of the nation's problems in
a carefully tailored response to Bush's inaugural address, strongly
endorsing its appeal to end bickering and restore bipartisanship in
foreign policy.
   ``In his inaugural address the president put his hand out to me
and to the speaker of the House,'' Mitchell said. ``I now extend
mine to him.''
   ``We are here to make a new start,'' Mitchell said. ``A central
aim of that new start for me is to pledge to President Bush that I
will do my utmost to foster true bipartisanship.''
   But promises and good intentions will not make bipartisanship a
fact, Mitchell said.
   ``It requires deeds to match words, action to carry out
intention,'' he said. ``Bipartisanship grows from shared
responsibility.''
   Mitchell added, however, that serious consultation between the
White House and Capitol Hill ``will not prevent differences between
the Congress and the president.''
   ``There have always been such differences,'' he said. ``There
always will be.''
   He made clear that for the two parties to come together in a
cooperative foreign policy, ways must be found to end the festering
feud over the War Powers Act. The act is intended to compel a
president to withdraw U.S. forces from potentially hostile
situations if Congress objects to their presence.
   Congressional supporters of the act defend it as protecting the
constitutional right of Congress to declare war. But former
President Reagan and other chief executives have called for its
repeal as an unconstitutional encroachment on a president's power as
commander in chief of the armed forces.
   ``I believe a constitutionally sound compromise is possible and I
shall work for it,'' Mitchell said.
   Dole also pledged bipartisanship. But at the same time he said it
is the aim of Senate Republicans to ``support and further the cause
of our new Republican president.''
   The confirmation process got into full gear with the Senate votes
confirming Baker, Darman and Mrs. Dole and the opening of
confirmation hearings for Defense Secretary-designate John Tower and
several other Cabinet nominees.
   One nominee apparently defused controversy over his views.
   Louis Sullivan, named by President Bush's to head the Department
of Health and Human Services, met privately with anti-abortion
senators and apparently convinced them his views are close enough to
theirs to merit their support.
   ``Dr. Sullivan believes in his heart that the Roe vs. Wade
decision should be overturned,'' said Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H.,
referring to the 1973 Supreme Court ruling that legalized abortion.
Sullivan, head of the Morehouse College medical school, had upset
many conservative legislators when he was quoted by a senator as
saying he did not favor overturning the ruling.
   The speeches by Dole and Mitchell were followed by a rush to
introduce the first legislation of the year.
   The hundreds of bills ranged from a measure to block or repeal
the proposed $45,000 pay raise for lawmakers to Dole's proposal for
a balanced budget amendment to the Constitution.
   The very first bill _ S.1, the Integrity In Post Employment Act _
would restrict members of Congress and congressional staff as well
as members of the executive branch from lobbying for specified
periods after leaving government service.
   Mitchell told reporters he favors a pay raise as part of the
ethics package, as long as senators no longer are permitted to
accept fees for giving speeches and making personal appearances.
   The proposed pay raise has become the most controversial issue of
the new Congress.
   The goal of opponents is to block attempts by House Speaker Jim
Wright to permit the pay raise to take effect automatically in two
weeks by preventing a vote to forbid it.
   Lawmakers' salaries are scheduled to rise on Feb. 8 from just
over $89,500 to $135,000, an increase of 50 percent. Federal judges
and some political appointees would also see their salaries boosted.
</TEXT>
