<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Personnel     01-26 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Personnel,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Fills No. 2 Jobs at Pentagon, Energy and Budget</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors executive Donald J. Moore was
named second in command at the Pentagon, and former Rep. W. Henson
Moore of Louisiana was tapped for the No. 2 spot at the Energy
Department, as President Bush filled vacancies in his administration.
   Bush on Wednesday also filled the No. 2 position in the Office of
Management and Budget, naming attorney William M. Diefenderfer III.
   Atwood, Moore and Diefenderfer all must be confirmed by the
Senate.
   Atwood, who is expected to bring management expertise to the
Pentagon, has been vice chairman of the board of General Motors
since 1987. He will work under former Sen. John Tower of Texas, who
is Bush's nominee as secretary of defense.
   Moore, who served in the House from Louisiana from 1975 until
1987 and is considered knowledgeable about the oil and gas industry,
had been under consideration for the top job at the Energy
Department.
   However, Bush decided to name an energy secretary who was an
expert in nuclear energy, and chose former chief of naval operations
James D. Watkins for the post.
   Since leaving Congress, Moore has been a partner in a law firm
based in Atlanta and Washington.
   Diefenderfer served as chief of staff and counsel to Sen. Bob
Packwood, R-Ore., when he was chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee.
   Filling out other senior positions at the budget office, Bush
named Robert E. Grady, a campaign adviser and speechwriter, as
associate director for natural resources, energy and science; Janet
Hale, who was an assistant secretary in the Transportation
Department, to be associate director for economics and government;
Edwin L. Dale Jr., a former newspaper reporter who worked at the
budget office and Commerce Department for the last eight years, as
counselor and director of external affairs; and Thomas A. Scully, an
attorney, to be associate director for congressional affairs.
   Also Paul D. Wolfowitz, the U.S. ambassador to Indonesia, is
expected to be named undersecretary of defense for policy. The job
has been vacant since Fred C. Ikle resigned a year ago.
   Wolfowitz was assistant secretary of state for East Asian affairs
for more than three years before his appointment to the Jakarta post.
   Bush also announced he was nominating Fred Zeder II to be
president of the Overseas Private Investment Corporation, succeeding
Craig Nalen.
   Zeder had been a senior adviser to the Bush transition team. He
also played a prominent role in Bush's presidential campaign. Zeder
previously had served as President Ronald Reagan's special
representative on negotiations with on the status of Micronesia.
   Another appointment announced was the nomination of Susan
Engeleiter to be administrator of the Small Business Administration,
succeeding James Abdnor.
   Mrs. Engeleiter served as state Senate minority leader in the
Wisconsin legislature since 1984, but lost a bid for the U.S. Senate
to Democrat Herbert Kohl, owner of the Milwaukee Bucks of the
National Basketball Association.
   Bush also nominated Paul D. Coverdell, formerly a member of the
Georgia Legislature, to become Peace Corps director succeeding Loret
M. Ruppe.
   Coverdell now is president and chief executive officer of
Coverdell &amp; Co., Inc., in Atlanta and was formerly chairman of the
Republican Party in Georgia.
   Bruce S. Gelb, vice chairman of the board of Bristol-Myers
Company, will be nominated as director of the United States
Information Agency, succeeding Charles Z. Wick, the president
announced.
   Bush also said he would nominate Constance Berry Newman, who
worked in his campaign, as director of the Office of Personnel
Management.
</TEXT>
