<FIRST>r i PM-Peru-Mine     01-26 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peru-Mine,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire, Poisonous Fumes Impede Rescue Efforts In Peruvian Gold Mine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire and poisonous fumes in a collapsed
Peruvian gold mine slowed efforts by rescuers to find amateur miners
trapped hundreds of feet underground for more than five days,
officials said.
   Energy Minister Jose Carrasco said ``authorities have almost no
hope of finding more survivors'' in the Sol de Oro gold mine, 230
miles south of Lima near Nazca.
   Three miners have been rescued, and six found dead in the mine,
which was being worked on a part-time basis by area residents after
it had been abandoned last year by its owners, official sources said.
   Nazca police Lt. Juan Robles said the trapped miners have been
inside the mine since Saturday, when a fire prevented their escape.
   The mine caved in Monday after the blaze, which was set during a
dispute by rival mining factions, collapsed wooden tunnel supports,
officials said.
   Carrasco said the dispute was over a newly discovered vein that
was yielding 4.5 pounds of gold daily. He said the exact number of
trapped miners was not known.
   Official sources have given conflicting figures of 15 to 200
miners.
   Police said toxic gas and smoke from a smoldering fire were the
greatest impediments to rescuers, six of whom were hospitalized for
inhalation of the poisoned air.
   Hopes were buoyed for finding survivors Tuesday when Carrasco
reported rescuers heard faint tapping from caved-in tunnels. But
those hopes dimmed Wednesday.
   ``There cannot be any life inside the mine because they have been
trapped for five days counting today,'' Juan Taipe, a Nazca
councilman who heads the city rescue effort, said Wednesday.
   The fire started in the five-level mine after gas lamps used for
lighting set ablaze wooden tunnel supports on the second.
   Officials said miners were believed located on the second, third
and fourth levels of the mine, which extends about 1,000 feet into a
half-mile high hill on Nazca's outskirts.
</TEXT>
