<FIRST>r a PM-Bundy-Confession     01-26 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bundy-Confession,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Killer Describes How He Coerced, Killed College Victim</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bundy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On a warm spring night in 1974, Ted Bundy waited
for his next victim in an alley behind a row of sorority and
fraternity houses, clutching a briefcase and with crutches tucked
under his arms.
   University of Washington's Greek Row was his stage, and his props
were in place. The crutches to signify a disabled leg. The briefcase
that was hard to carry. A few blocks away, his brown Volkswagen bug
waited in a parking lot. Behind its rear wheels were handcuffs and a
crowbar.
   Bundy, who could be a poised and charming man, was all
anticipation as 18-year-old Georgann Hawkins happened along. She was
just completing her first college year that June 11, and was headed
down the well-lit alley for her sorority house.
   ``I was moving up the alley, using a briefcase and some crutches,
and the young woman walked down,'' Bundy said on the tape played
Wednesday by Robert Keppel, a state attorney general's investigator.
   The tape was made Friday, the day Bundy confessed to the eight
1974 ``Ted'' killings in western Washington. Bundy, 42, was executed
Tuesday morning in Florida for the 1978 rape and murder of a
12-year-old girl.
   Five ``Ted'' victims had been slain by the time Bundy encountered
Ms. Hawkins.
   On the tape, Bundy said Ms. Hawkins paused for a moment, then
``kept on walking down the alley toward me.''
   At mid-block the two came together and the handsome Bundy must
have known what to say. ``I ... asked her to help me carry the
briefcase. Which she did and we walked back up the alley'' toward
his car, he said in a matter-of-fact manner, whispering in spots.
   ``When we reached the car ... I knocked her unconscious with the
crowbar. ... There were some handcuffs there, along with the
crowbar. ... I handcuffed her and put her in the passenger's side of
the car and drove away.
   ``She was unconscious but she was very much alive.''
   Bundy said he drove to Issaquah, 15 miles east of Seattle.
   In the tape, filled with pauses and sighs, Bundy quickly
summarized the rest of the trip: ``past Issaquah and up the hill,
down the road to a grassy area.
   ``I ... took her out of the (car) and took the handcuffs off her
and ...''
   The easy-talking Bundy, who Keppel said had a habit of talking
fast when he was slipping away from the truth, had a hard time
getting the words out on what then happened to Ms. Hawkins.
   ``Gee, this is probably the hardest part, I don't know. (Pause).
I don't know, it's all getting sort of abs..., um, not abstract
would be poor, but um, well we're getting into some, we're getting
right down to it and uh well we'll talk about it, it's just you
know, you understand, it's not something that I find easy to talk
about and after all this time. (Pause, deep sigh).''
   At this point in the news conference, Keppel stopped the tape,
out of respect, he said, for the victim's family.
   ``It's bad. That's about all I can say,'' he said of Bundy's
continuing description of Ms. Hawkins' murder.
   Keppel has offered to describe to the families of victims the
treatment to which they were subjected. So far, he said, he has had
no takers.
   Keppel said Bundy did say later in the tape, intertwined with
``gruesome details,'' that he had returned to near the University of
Washington the day after Ms. Hawkins' abduction to recover her shoe
and shattered earrings.
   He rode over on his bicycle and found them near where he had
parked his Volkswagen, even while police were inspecting the alley a
few blocks away.
</TEXT>
