<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 0431EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Economy     01-26 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Economy,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economist Says Soviet Deficit Three Times Higher Than October Projection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's budget deficit is three times
what the Kremlin projected three months ago and must be quickly
lowered if chronic shortages of consumer goods are to end, a senior
economist says.
   Leonid Abalkin, director of the Economics Institute of the
Academy of Sciences, told a news conference Wednesday that the
deficit ``ruins the national economy.''
   He said the $162 billion budget shortfall could be eliminated in
two to three years if the state stops funding more money-losing
enterprises and the military devotes more of its resources to the
civilian sector.
   ``Without a solution to this problem, we won't be able to solve
the problem of consumer goods shortages,'' Abalkin said.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has called improving supplies of
food and consumer goods for the country's 285 million people a top
priority in his program of perestroika, or restructuring the economy.
   In October, Soviet officials said the budget had been running in
the red for years and projected a deficit of $55 billion on a budget
of $795 billion.
   This month, economist O.T. Bogomolov wrote that the deficit
actually could reach $162 billion this year, and Abalkin agreed with
that estimate.
   He said the April 1986 explosion and fire at the Chernobyl
nuclear power plant and earthquakes in Armenia last month and in
Tadzhikistan this month had contributed to the deficit.
   He said world economic conditions, such as the falling price of
oil _ the Soviet Union's main export _ were also to blame.
   The Soviet Union itself could be criticized because its ``unwise
export structure'' is ``very vulnerable'' to fluctuations in the
price of oil, Abalkin said.
   He said some production targets in the Five-Year Plan that runs
through 1990 should be scrapped, and $32 billion could be saved by
closing bad businesses and calling off expensive construction
projects and other huge outlays.
   The state should stop financing businesses that won't turn a
profit for years and instead focus on enterprises that can make
quick profits, he said. The government reported last week that one
in 10 enterprises lost money in 1988.
   Other help could come from the military. Instead of building new
factories, plants producing goods for the military could turn their
ready-made resources and skilled workforce to civilian use, he said.
   Gorbachev said this month that the military budget will be
trimmed by 14.2 percent and the production of arms and military
supplies by 19.5 percent.
   The state traditionally has all but ignored the market forces of
supply and demand, wasting money on unprofitable factories that
produce goods no one wants and giving short shrift to some highly
sought items. It also set prices artificially low on basics such as
housing, meat, bread and cabbage.
   Last year, the Soviet Union began an effort to change that by
ordering businesses that cannot pay their own way to close. But
Abalkin said no businesses have gone bankrupt.
   In some cases, when closing was imminent, workers formed a
private business to run the operation as a cooperative, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
