<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 0445EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Soviet     01-26 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Soviet,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Announces Visit by Soviet Foreign Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China announced today that Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard Shevardnadze will visit Beijing next week, setting the stage
for the first Sino-Soviet summit in 30 years.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing said Shevardnadze will be
in Beijing for three days beginning Feb. 2, renewing talks with his
Chinese counterpart on normalizing relations marred by three decades
of hostility and mistrust.
   Qian Qichen held talks with Kremlin leaders in Moscow in
December, the first Chinese foreign minister to do so in 32 years.
   If next month's talks go well, the two foreign ministers may set
a date for the first Sino-Soviet summit since Nikita Khrushschev met
Mao Tse-tung in Beijing in 1959.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has repeatedly expressed
his eagerness to improve ties with China and is widely expected to
travel to Beijing in April or May.
   Gorbachev's meeting with 84-year-old senior Chinese leader Deng
Xiaoping would formally normalize ties strained since the two
countries split over ideological differences in 1960 and fought a
short border war in 1969.
   Li said Shevardnadze and Qian will ``prepare for a summit meeting
between top leaders of China and the Soviet Union. The two sides
will also exchange opinions on other matters of common interest.
Chinese leaders will meet with Shevardnadze.''
   He said the Qian-Shevardnadze talks will take up what China says
is the main obstacle to better Sino-Soviet ties _ the conflict in
Cambodia.
   China backs the anti-Vietnamese resistance in Cambodia; the
Soviet Union backs Vietnam's 10-year occupation of the war-torn
country.
   Both powers agree that a withdrawal of Vietnamese troops is the
key to a political settlement.
   However, differences remain on the composition of a coalition
government to be formed by the Hanoi-backed forces in Phnom Penh,
the Cambodian capital, and the three-party resistance including the
Khmer Rouge.
   China has welcomed a recent Vietnamese proposal to remove all its
troops in Cambodia by September and says it will reduce military aid
to the resistance in conjunction with the pullout.
   Marked progress also has been made in resolving the other two
issues China sees as obstacles to normal relations with Moscow _
Afghanistan and border tensions.
   Soviet troops are reportedly leaving Afghanistan in the final
stage of a military pullout to be completed by Feb. 15. Gorbachev
also announced last week that Soviet troop strength in Asia will be
reduced by 200,000.
   Most Soviet troops in Asia are located near the Sino-Chinese
border or in Soviet ally Mongolia, and are regarded by China as a
direct threat to its security.
   Normalization of political ties will not bring dramatic changes
to overall ties, which have been steadily improving during the 1980s.
   Trade between the powers in 1988 has been estimated at about $2.8
billion, up 30 percent from the previous year, and barter along the
highly militarized 5,000-mile border is booming.
   Cultural and academic exchanges are increasing. The official
Xinhua News Agency said today that 600 Chinese scholars will go to
the Soviet Union this year and 320 Soviets will study at Chinese
universities. In 1983, when academic contacts were renewed, only 10
scholars were exchanged.
   The two sides also are discussing joint ventures and Soviet
technological help to modernize factories set up by the Soviets in
the 1950s and then abandoned when relations deteriorated.
   China has emphasized it will never return to the political
relationship of the 1950s, when the fledgling Chinese Communist
state followed the Soviet lead in setting international policy.
</TEXT>
