<FIRST>r a PM-Bundy-Will     01-26 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bundy-Will,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bundy Wanted Cremation, Ashes Spread Over Cascades</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bundy, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ted Bundy requested in his will that
his body be cremated and the ashes scattered over Washington state's
Cascade Mountains, where the remains of at least four of his victims
were found, a newspaper reported.
   The will signed the night before his execution also gives the
serial killer's civil attorney, Diana Weiner of Sarasota, control
over his remains, personal property and assets, including $709.66 in
cash, the Florida Times-Union reported today.
   Sandy Williams, co-owner of the Williams-Thomas Funeral Home in
Gainesville, where Bundy's body was sent following Tuesday's
execution at the Florida State Prison, said no public funeral was
planned.
   But Williams would not give details about the final disposition
of the body because of an agreement with Ms. Weiner.
   The will did not give a specific location for the scattering of
the ashes, and attempts by The Associated Press to reach Ms. Weiner
on Wednesday night were unsuccessful.
   Bundy, a 42-year-old former law school dropout, was executed
Tuesday for the February 1978 murder of 12-year-old Kimberly Leach
of Lake City. He also was convicted of two other Florida deaths. He
confessed to 23 other slayings in the days before his execution.
   Bob Keppel, a Washington state attorney general's investigator
who has tracked Bundy for 15 years, said Wednesday he thinks Bundy
could be responsible for more than 100 slayings dating back to 1969.
   Bundy admitted late last week he was responsible for eight
murders in 1974 in western Washington. The remains of four victims
were found on Taylor Mountain in the foothills of the Cascades.
   Prison records show Bundy's personal property included a radio
with a headphone, a gold-colored chain with a cross, a religious
book, stationery, a gold-colored wedding band, and a bottle of
suntan lotion.
   The $709.66 in cash was money donated by family and friends for
snacks and other items from the prison canteen.
   The items were inventoried Tuesday and picked up at the prison by
Ms. Weiner, said Department of Corrections spokesman Bob Macmaster.
</TEXT>
