<HEAD>Mayflower Replica Gets Major Overhaul</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Plimoth is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a month of refurbishing by
shipworkers with Pilgrims' pride, the Mayflower II is ship-shape and
back in its berth.
   ``It came back yesterday and it looks absolutely gorgeous,''
Plimoth Plantation spokeswoman Troy Creane said Wednesday.
   The ship, visited by about 300,000 people a year, undergoes major
repairs about every two years, and minor maintenance is nearly
continuous.
   ``It's one of the prime attractions in Plymouth, and it's very
important to keep her in as good a shape as possible,'' Creane said.
   The repairs at the Gloucester Marine Railway cost about $25,000,
Plantation spokesman Jeff Scotland said. He said the ship was
repainted with nontoxic paint to help prevent water contamination.
   Built in England, the 106{-foot-long ship sailed to Plymouth in
1957 as a symbol of friendship to America.
   The original ship sailed to North America in 1620 with 102
passengers and was dismantled in 1622.
