<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador     01-26 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Duarte Rejects Guerrilla Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte
has rejected leftist rebels' conditional proposal to participate in
national elections, calling it unconstitutional and a ``proposal for
war.''
   The guerrillas, who have been battling the U.S.-backed government
for nine years, offered to participate in this year's presidential
balloting if it were postponed from March 19 to September and other
conditions were met.
   The rebels have rejected as ``farce'' all five elections held
this decade, claiming they were part of a ``U.S.-imposed
counterinsurgency project.''
   The proposal, announced Tuesday by guerrilla leaders at a Mexico
City news conference, was virtually rejected that afternoon by Fidel
Chavez Mena, presidential candidate of Duarte's Christian Democratic
Party.
   The United States has not responded.
   ``This is not a proposal for peace. It is a proposal for war,''
Duarte told reporters on Wednesday. ``There are the threats. They're
talking about attacks, escalating the war'' if the proposal is not
accepted.
   He said that according to the constitution, presidential
elections must be held no later than two months before the end of
the 5-year presidential term.
   Duarte's term ends June 1.
   In its proposal, the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front
said it would accept the extension of Duarte's administration until
the new election date. Duarte, who is dying of liver cancer, said:
``I don't accept the idea of remaining in the presidency even one
minute after the end of my term.''
   The rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, or Arena, also
rejected the guerrilla proposal as unconstitutional. Arena candidate
Alfredo Cristiani is leading Chavez Mena in recent polls.
   Guerrilla sources have indicated they would step up attacks if
the proposal is rejected.
   The war has killed an estimated 65,000 people, mostly civilians.
Three rounds of government-guerrilla dialogue between 1984 and 1987
ended in stalemate.
   Duarte said he was not closing the door on the guerrillas.
   ``I have said I would talks with any and all who declare publicly
without conditions that violence is not the way to resolve the
country's problems and that they are ready to incorporate themselves
into the democratic process,'' he said.
</TEXT>
