<FIRST>r i PM-India     01-26 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>India Displays Its Military Might As Sikhs Try To Blow Up Train</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India today displayed its military might
at a parade marking the republic's founding 39 years ago, and Sikh
militants in Punjab killed at least three people and tried to blow
up a passenger train.
   The Press Trust of India news agency said explosives placed by
Sikh separatists went off minutes after a Pakistan-bound train
passed the track today at Khasa, four miles north of the Sikh holy
city of Amritsar.
   The explosion damaged the track, and Indian railways later
suspended train service in the area. The news agency quoted police
as saying Sikh separatists were responsible for the blast, but did
not elaborate.
   Security was tight in New Delhi for the Republic Day anniversary,
reflecting fears that Sikh extremists would try to disrupt the
celebrations. Sikh militants are campaigning for an independent
homeland in Punjab, claiming they are discriminated against by the
country's Hindu majority.
   The 1.1 million-man Indian army displayed a new bridge-laying
tank and marine helicopter in the capital amid a host of festive
floats, camel-mounted riflemen and high-stepping military bands.
   President Ramaswamy Venklataraman presided over the procession
from a reviewing stand. Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, the bulky shape
of a bullet-proof vest apparent beneath his high-collared gry suit,
was also present amid tight security.
   Police estimated 1 million people watched the parade.
   In the Punjab city of Amritsar, seat of the Golden Temple, the
holiest shrine of the Sikh faith, police reported calm today. But
the news agency said at least three people were killed by Sikh
radicals elsewhere in the state.
   Sikh separatists killed more than 2,400 people in Punjab last
year and so far this year have taken at least 156 lives in the rich
farm state where Sikhs comprise a slight majority.
   Fears of an attack in New Delhi were heightened by the Jan. 6
executions of two Sikhs convicted in the 1984 assassination of Prime
Minister Indira Gandhi, mother of the current Indian leader.
   Rajiv Gandhi and his wife Sonia watched the military parade from
a reviewing stand along The Way of Kings. The chief guest at the
Republic Day celebrations was Nguyen Van Linh, secretary general of
Vietnam's Communist Party.
   The annual celebration marks India's declaration of a republic in
1950, three years after independence from Britain was achieved.
   One of the first new military items displayed was the Kartik
tank, developed in India. It is designed to lay bridges over dry
spans in as little as three minutes to facilitate rapid movement of
armored columns.
   Another was the Sea King helicopter, designed to carry commandos
and land on water.
   Previously seen hardware included Soviet-designed T-72 tanks and
a MiG-27 warplane. Moscow is India's chief supplier of weaponry.
   After the armor and weapons passed, the parade turned into a
procession of floats from various Indian states, school children in
starched uniforms carrying flags, and dancers twirling to the music
of high-pitched flutes and resonant drum beats.
   One drill team, cripsly attired in black and white, high-stepped
by on stilts brandishing rifles over their heads.
   Two helicopters showered 440 pounds of rose and marigold petals
on the parade route.
</TEXT>
