<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 0516EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AncientTomb     01-26 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ancient Tomb,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Irish Tomb Was Earliest Structure Built With Astronomical Use, Study
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study of an Irish tomb built about three
centuries before Stonehenge provides new evidence that it is the
oldest known structure with an astronomical function, says a study
published today.
   The 5,000-year-old tomb was apparently designed to create a
dramatic light show that began at sunrise on the shortest day of the
year, probably for religious purposes, the study said.
   Previous research also suggested an astronomical connection.
   But this study is the first to investigate implications of the
fact that the sun rose in a different spot on the horizon when the
tomb was built than it does today, said astronomer Tom Ray of the
Dublin Institute for Advanced Studies in Ireland, whose results are
published in the British journal Nature.
   The Newgrange tomb, north of Dublin, was built around 5,100 years
ago; the first stage of Stonehenge, located on Salisbury Plains,
England, dates back about 4,800 years.
   The tomb is among the oldest of massive stone monuments found in
northwestern Europe and the British Isles, said archaeologist Curtis
Runnels of Boston University. Ray's study gives the strongest
evidence to date that even the early monuments were designed with
astronomical influence, Runnels said.
   Edwin Krupp, director of the Griffith Observatory in Los Angeles
and a researcher in ancient astronomy, said he believed previous
studies already had established an astronomical role in the tomb's
design. But the new work improves the case, he said.
   Krupp agreed that the Irish tomb is the oldest known monument
with firm evidence for astronomical design, but Runnels said that
because of uncertainties in dating, some Egyptian buildings may be
as old.
   The Newgrange tomb lies within a mound of loose stones about 90
yards wide and 35 feet tall. A corridor snakes about 60 feet into
the mound, leading to a chamber with a dome-shaped roof.
   Ray said the light show began with sunrise on the winter solstice.
   The first rays of light shot down the center of the corridor and
struck the floor in the chamber, creating a lighted spot a few feet
long and a couple inches wide, Ray said. The reflection lit a
carving that features a trio of spirals.
   The sunlight entered above the tomb's entrance through a gap
measuring about 8 inches tall and 3 feet wide, Ray said. As seen
from the chamber, the sun would appear in the lower left hand corner
of the gap, continue rising until it was framed by the gap, and then
exit at the upper right corner, he said.
   The gap was created such that when it framed the sun, it matched
the sun's width vertically within an accuracy of one-fifth or
one-sixth of the sun's radius, which is ``not bad for 5,000 years
ago,'' Ray said.
   Scientists can only gather circumstantial evidence to determine
the intentions of the Newgrange builders, Krupp said, because ``you
don't have the owner's manual.''
   The calculation that the first rays of the sun reached the back
chamber by going down the middle of the corridor gives ``a certain
kind of symmetric satisfaction ... although really we don't know if
that was the target or what the detailed meaning of that event might
have been,'' Krupp said.
   ``But to our eyes, that looks like a very satisfying place to put
a beam of light if you're into dramatic light and shadow effects.''
   Runnels said archaeologists suspect the tomb was a burial
chamber, built by an agricultural society that had not yet
discovered metal for tools.
   The society was apparently complex enough to plan and build the
elaborate tomb, with a specialist leisure class to make astronomical
observations and direct the engineering, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
