<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Norris     01-26 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Norris,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Last Survivor Of ``Scottsboro Boys'' Rape Case Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clarence Norris, the last survivor of the
``Scottsboro Boys'' rape case, which came to symbolize racial
injustice in the Deep South in the 1930s, has died. He was 76.
   He died Monday at Bronx Community Hospital after a long illness.
   The ``Scottsboro Boys'' case involved nine black teen-agers who
were accused of raping two white women in Alabama in 1931. A series
of trials dragged on until 1937, when one of the women withdrew her
accusation.
   Norris was sentenced to death three times and spent 15 years in
prison.
   He came to New York City, where he worked as a warehouseman. In
1976, when he was 64, the Alabama Pardon and Parole Board
unanimously found that he was innocent of rape charges and then-Gov.
George C. Wallace signed his pardon.
   All but the youngest defendant in the case were sentenced to
death. Although none was executed, all went to prison.
   The case began on March 25, 1931, when the youths, who had caught
a freight train as they headed north to seek jobs, were taken off
the train at Paint Rock, Ala., jailed in nearby Scottsboro on rape
charges.
   In ``The Last of the Scottsboro Boys,'' his 1979 autobiography
written with Sybil D. Washington, Norris contended that he and the
other youths were scapegoats, caught at the wrong place at the wrong
time with two white women who were afraid they would be accused of
fraternizing with blacks.
   Norris, who was born in Warm Springs, Ga., is survived by his
wife, Melba, two daughters, Deborah N. Webster and Adele Norris, all
of New York and three sisters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
