<DOCNO> AP890126-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 0532EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ToothSurvey     01-26 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tooth Survey,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Says Americans Place High Monetary Value on Teeth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's now an eye for an eye and a tooth for
$309,000, according to a survey taken for root-canal specialists who
wanted to know how much monetary value Americans place on their
front teeth.
   The survey taken last month for the American Association of
Endodontists asked 1,023 men and women to name the smallest amount
of money they would accept for one of their healthy front teeth.
   Dr. Joseph D. Maggio, president of the association, said almost a
quarter of those surveyed refused to specify how much, saying they
would not sell such a tooth for any amount of money.
   The average amount cited by respondents who said they would take
money was $309,000, Maggio said Wednesday night.
   ``This survey tells us that people understand the importance of a
tooth to their health and quality of life,'' said Maggio, an
endodonist from Oak Brook. ``A tooth is like a computer chip. It's
small and the materials that make it up are worth only pennies, but
that's far exceeded by its functional value.''
   Maggio estimated the chemical value of an average-sized front
tooth at about 12 cents.
   Maggio said the survey specified healthy front teeth because
those are the ones most people would be least willing to part with.
   ``Obviously, we wouldn't have gotten the same results if we had
asked about wisdom teeth,'' he said.
   Maggio noted that the survey, conducted by the Opinion Research
Corp. of Princeton, N.J., found that older respondents were much
less willing to sell a tooth.
   Among respondents at least 65 years old, 42 percent said they
would accept no amount of money for a front tooth. A similar
response came from only 13 percent of those between ages 18 and 34.
   ``It could be that older people already have suffered some tooth
loss and know first hand that nothing can really replace a natural
tooth,'' Maggio suggested.
   As an endodontist, Maggio believes that everything possible
should be done to save an existing tooth, rather than pulling it and
replacing it.
   He estimates that more than 22 million root canal procedures, in
which the tooth is saved by removing the nerve, were performed in
the United States last year, compared with some 40 million tooth
extractions.
   ``In most parts of the country, a root canal can save an existing
tooth for between $275 and $700, depending on the type of tooth and
the severity of decay,'' he said. ``An extraction, if the missing
tooth is replaced with a bridge or a partial, usually winds up being
more expensive.''
   Maggio said there are 2,900 endodontists in the nation, and their
work was only recognized as a speciality by the American Dental
Association in the 1960s, even though root canal work had been
performed for many years before that.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
