<FIRST>r a PM-SchoolBusCrash     01-26 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-School Bus Crash,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Driver, Pupil Killed When Bus Rolls Into Creek</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old student started grabbing
children and ``throwing them out the door'' as their school bus
skidded off a muddy road and into a creek, but he couldn't reach an
8-year-old who sank before his eyes.
   The child and the driver, who rejected the teen-ager's offers of
help, died Wednesday after being trapped underwater for more than an
hour, authorities said. Eleven other students escaped after the
accident 40 miles southeast of Kansas City.
   ``I saw the other little boy in the water, and I tried to grab
for him underneath the water,'' said 16-year-old Bill Raley, one of
12 students on the bus. ``I didn't even get to touch him. I tried.
He went under and I never saw him again.''
   Killed were Dale R. Thomasson, 46, a teacher, counselor and
school bus driver, and Loren Newkirk II, 8, both of Wellsville in
rural east-central Kansas.
   The two were trapped beneath the front axle of the bus until
wreckers pulled it from the creek, Franklin County Deputy Sheriff
Craig Davis said. Loren was freed and survived more than four hours
before being pronounced dead at a hospital. The cause of death was
listed as drowning.
   A preliminary autopsy showed Thomasson died from massive,
crushing injuries, Davis said.
   The bus was en route to Wellsville's school complex, about 10
miles northeast of Ottawa, when it slowed for a curve on a gravel
road made muddy by early-morning rains. The bus ran off the road
after the turn, Davis said.
   It slid onto the bridge rail over Walnut Creek, then tipped to
its side and landed upside down on the top of a 9-foot embankment,
Davis said. The bus then began sliding into the creek, which was as
deep as 6 feet.
   Raley said another student opened the back emergency exit and the
two helped students jump out onto a muddy embankment as water poured
in the front door.
   ``I just started grabbing them and throwing them out the door,''
he said.
   Raley said he fell down and slid to the front of the bus, where
the water was deeper.
   He tried to reach for Loren, who disappeared into the water.
   ``I yelled to Mr. T, `Do you need my help?' He just said, `Get
the heck out!'' Raley said.
   The youth said he jumped out the back and swam to the bank, then
ran up the road to a house and called an ambulance.
   Davis said Thomasson apparently grabbed Loren and jumped into the
water just as the bus rolled over onto them.
</TEXT>
