<FIRST>r a PM-SardinesSentence     01-26 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sardines Sentence,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Says Sardine Shoplifting Not Worth Life Sentence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clyde Ashley Jr. shoplifted two cans of
sardines, ate them in the store and then tried to steal money to pay
for them. For that, the ex-convict was sentenced to life in prison
as a habitual offender.
   On Wednesday, the Mississippi Supreme Court ruled that the
sentence, handed down in 1986, was overly harsh. Ashley was properly
convicted for his ``great sardine caper,'' the court said in
ordering the trial judge to reconsider the sentence.
   As evidence of the ``seemingly undue harshness'' of the sentence,
Justice James Robertson noted that prosecutors had said they
wouldn't oppose a lighter sentence in the case.
   According to the court records, Ashley, now 44, was paroled on
Dec. 13, 1985, after spending 23 years in prison on a series of
burglaries and one attempted robbery _ each time under the influence
of alcohol.
   On Jan. 15, 1986, Ashley, after being rebuffed in attempts to get
money from 85-year-old Eva Washington, entered a small grocery store
in Osyka in Pike County and was seen opening and eating two cans of
sardines.
   ``Once more while drinking Ashley rather pathetically and
pitifully again ran afoul of the law,'' said Robertson, writing for
the high court.
   According to court records, when the owner of the store cornered
Ashley and asked for payment for the sardines, Ashely said he would
go to his aunt's house to get some money.
   The owner went with Ashley to see Washington, who was not
actually his aunt. The store owner waited outside and called police
when Ashley did not return. Police found Ashley hiding in a closet
inside the house.
   Ashley was convicted of burglary for breaking into the house. The
judge, reviewing his criminal record, determined that Ashley was a
habitual offender and issued the sentence of life without parole.
</TEXT>
