<FIRST>r a PM-ChemicalLeak     01-26 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chemical Leak,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Leak In Week Reported At Superfund Site In Nitro</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NITRO, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moisture and waste acid reacted together to
blow the lid off a 55-gallon drum, causing the second leak at an
abandoned chemical plant in a week, a federal Environmental
Protection Agency official said.
   A small vapor cloud dispersed before EPA officials could
determine how wide an area it covered. There were no reports of
injury to anyone in or near the former Artel Chemical Co. plant.
   EPA on-site coordinator Jerry Saseen said officials wouldn't know
until later today what chemical was stored in the drum that blew up
Wednesday at the Superfund site. EPA officials said the drum was
located in the same area of the plant where a Jan. 19 leak occurred.
   Last week's accident was also caused by moisture reacting with a
chemical stored in a 55-gallon drum. There was a similar leak last
fall.
   Both Saseen and Nitro Mayor Don Karnes blamed unusually warm
weather for causing condensation inside the drums. Temperatures have
been fluctuating from the 20s and 30s to the 50s and 60s during a
January warm spell.
   ``Until we get more even temperatures, we could have situations
like this,'' Saseen said. ``The situation is ripe that this can
happen, many, many, many times. ... I believe we will be
experiencing these things over and over until the warm weather is
over.''
   Saseen said the leak was neutralized with lime and soda ash. He
said an EPA crew would remain at the scene overnight.
   ``We have literally thousands of drums here. It's a very, very
fragile situation,'' Saseen said.
   Cleanup crews could begin moving more than 5,000 drums of toxic
and hazardous chemicals from the abandoned plant as early as
mid-February, said EPA official Doug Fox. The plant was closed and
turned over to the EPA in June after the federal government declared
it a public health hazard.
   Last week's leak involved thionyl chloride, a potentially
poisonous chemical used in the manufacture of pesticides. There were
no injuries, but a 19-block area of Nitro was sealed off and about
2,500 of the town's 8,000 residents were confined to their homes for
more than an hour.
   Karnes said he did not give an order confining residents to
shelter in the latest incident. The mayor, who had expressed
displeasure over a lengthy delay between last week's leak and the
time the EPA notified Nitro officials, said the reaction to
Wednesday's leak was much faster.
   Nitro, built in World War I to manufacture explosives, lies along
the Kanawha River in an area known as Chemical Valley that is the
site of more than two dozen chemical plants.
   There have been several chemical leaks in the area during the
past decade. In 1985, 135 people were hospitalized after methyl
isocyanate leaked from a Union Carbide plant in Institute. The plant
was similar to one in Bhopal, India, that leaked the year before,
killing more than 2,000 people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
