<FIRST>r a PM-AirportFire     01-26 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airport Fire,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Breaks Out In Kennedy International Arrivals Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A smoky fire that erupted in a snack bar
storeroom at Kennedy International Airport injured 34 people, forced
the evacuation of 600 passengers and delayed four flights,
authorities say.
   The west wing of the International Arrivals Building was shut
down through the night but most of it, except for at least three
aircraft gates damaged in the fire, was expected to reopen this
morning, said Armando Arrastia, a Port Authority spokesman.
   The cause of the blaze was under investigation but there was no
reason to believe it was suspicious, said Efrain Parrilla, a Fire
Department spokesman.
   The fire broke out Wednesday night on the second floor in a
storage area containing paper and metal goods for an adjacent snack
bar-souvenir store and other restaurants in the building, he said.
   ``The flames did not spread quickly but the smoke did,'' Parrilla
said.
   Damage to the building was light, Parrilla said.
   More than 150 firefighters fought the blaze, which was declared
under control within 1{ hours.
   Air France, El Al Israel Airlines, Air Afrique and Royal Air
Maroc flights, which were using gates near the snack bar, were
delayed about three hours because of the fire, said Arrastia. The
flights left from the east wing of the building, he said.
   Twenty-six people injured were taken to hospitals, the others
were treated at the scene, said Capt. Mark Rothstein of the
Emergency Medical Services. Most suffered smoke inhalation, and none
of the injuries were life threatening, authorities said.
</TEXT>
