<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 0616EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     01-26 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former President Chun Refuses To Testify On 1980 Uprising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Chun Doo-hwan refused
today to accept a writ to testify before a National Assembly
committee on the suppression of a 1980 uprising that left at least
200 people dead.
   Chun, in voluntary exile at an isolated Buddhist temple, said in
a statement he takes responsibility for putting down the Kwangju
uprising, but does not intend to appear before the panel
investigating the matter.
   ``I think I was in a position to take moral and political
responsibility , so I have no intention to avoid responsibility,''
Chun said.
   Former President Choi Kyu-ha, who briefly held office before Chun
took power with military backing in 1980, also refused today to
accept a writ to testify.
   Both former presidents said previously that as former heads of
state they could not be compelled to testify. President Roh Tae-woo
has backed Chun's refusal to testify despite widespread criticism.
   About 500 radical students from several Seoul colleges clashed
with riot police at Dongguk University today to demand the arrest of
Roh and Chun. They hurled hundreds of firebombs and rocks at police
surrounding the school.
   ``Arrest Chun Doo-hwan!'' and ``Overthrow Roh Tae-woo!'' students
yelled.
   No serious injuries or arrests were reported in the fighting.
   The opposition is trying to use the Kwangju incident and other
legacies of the authoritarian Chun regime to weaken its successor,
the nearly year-old Roh government. Roh, a former general and close
ally of Chun, is still identified with the ex-president in the eyes
of many Koreans.
   Writs were issued to the two ex-presidents as the special
committee resumed its hearing today into the 1980 uprising in the
southern city of Kwangju. The opposition-controlled National
Assembly has been investigating allegations of human rights abuses
and corruption under Chun.
   By official count, about 200 people were killed and more than
1,000 injured in the army's suppressiong of the uprising. Opposition
groups claim the casualty toll was much higher and the uprising
remains a highly charged issue.
   Chun was in control of the armed forces at the time and became
president a few months later. Choi, a former prime minister, briefly
served as a figurehead president.
   In his statement, Chun said he would testify ``indirectly''
instead of appearing before the committee, but gave no details. Chun
had indicated he would answer questions in writing.
   ``I spend time here looking back on the past with regrets and
repentance and I wish I could have healed the scars of the Kwangju
incident while in office,'' he said in his message from the temple
on the west coast.
   Under Korean law, the parliamentary committee has the power to
refer the case to the prosecution for legal action, but the
prosecution must decide whether to act.
   If the former presidents are charged and convicted of contempt of
parliament, they could be sentenced to up to five years in prison.
   Chun is also being pressed to testify before another
parliamentary committee investigating corruption and other misdeeds.
   The former president has denied any personal wrongdoing, but he
surrendered $24 million and went into rural exile after apologizing
to the nation in November. About a dozen members of the
ex-president's family have been arrested or convicted on corruption
charges.
</TEXT>
