<FIRST>r a PM-FemaleBishop     01-26 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Female Bishop,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Formal Consecration Set For First Female Bishop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first woman to be elected a bishop of the
Episcopal Church says she hopes her precedent-setting position will
encourage other women, but she plans to devote herself to religious,
not political, duties.
   ``I do not intend to be an international Anglican gadfly, moving
around to promote ordination of women, but I will be as supportive
as possible,'' the Rev. Barbara C. Harris said Wednesday.
   Her election in September as suffragan, or assisting bishop,
touched off a spirited debate among Episcopalians over her
background and qualifications as well as her gender. The election
was formally approved Tuesday by a majority of the 118 U.S. bishops.
   In her first public comments since her election, Harris said she
was glad the approval process was over.
   ``While it has not all been sweetness and light, it has certainly
been bearable because of the support, affirmation and love and
prayerful support I have had,'' she said.
   Harris was joined at a news conference by presiding Bishop David
E. Johnson of Boston, who said a full and formal consecration would
be held Feb. 11. He said it could be one of the largest affairs of
its kind.
   Harris, a former public relations executive who is black, said
she believed racism may have played a part in some of the criticisms
of her background and qualifications.
   ``Given that racism is so prevalent in our society and so woven
into the fabric of our lives, ... I am certain that there was some
element of racism present in some of the objections,'' she said.
   Harris was criticized for being too liberal, for being divorced
and for lacking a college or seminary degree. She acknowledged that
she still had to overcome some opposition.
   ``We recognize that this presents a problem for some people,
theologically and emotionally,'' she said, ``and we must always be
about helping or attempting to help them to understand what this
means in the life of the church and to move toward some
reconciliation with them as far as is possible.''
</TEXT>
