<FIRST>r i PM-Malaysia-Detainees     01-26 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Malaysia-Detainees,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Politicians Released from Detention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today released two
leading opposition lawmakers and three other politicians it had held
without trial for 15 months, but parliament's opposition leader
remained in custody.
   The five were released because the government felt they no longer
post a threat to the country's security, police sources said on
condition of anonymity.
   They were among 106 people rounded up in October 1987 and held
without trial under the Internal Security Act in a move Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamed said was necessary to prevent
Malay-Chinese racial clashes.
   Only two of the original 106 remained in detention after today's
releases _ the Democratic Action Party's secretary-general and the
leader of the opposition in Parliament, Lim Kit Siang, and his son,
Lim Guan Eng.
   Reduan Aslie, public relations officer at federal police
headquarters, said those released today included parliament members
Karpal Singh, the party's vice chairman when he was arrested, and
Perumal Patto, its deputy secretary general.
   Also released from the Kemunting detention camp near Ipoh, 125
miles north of Kuala Lumpur, were opposition People's Socialist
Party member Mohamad Nasir Hashim, opposition Pan Malaysian Islamic
Party Baling branch secretary Mohamed Yusof Hussein and party member
Kamarulzaman Che Ismail, Reduan said.
   Under Malaysian law, anyone detained under the Internal Security
Act must give up his party posts, although he can remain a member of
the party and of parliament.
   At the time of the arrests, Mahathir also banned three
newspapers, citing similar reasons. They were allowed to resume
publishing four months later.
   Currently, about 65 people are being held under the Internal
Security Act.
   When Mahathir became prime minister in July 1981, 550 people were
detained under the act. He called for a review and released most of
them.
</TEXT>
