<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 0725EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Balloonist     01-26 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Balloonist,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Balloonist Says He'll Fly Non-Stop Around the Globe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the competition heating up to conquer one of
ballooning's final frontiers, a British adventurer is racing to meet
a spring liftoff date in an attempt to be the first to circle the
globe by balloon.
   ``We feel it's the ultimate challenge for balloonists at the
moment,'' said Julian Nott, leader of the attempt and an experienced
balloonist who has set 79 records.
   At a news conference Wednesday at the Explorers Club, Nott, 44,
said he and 33-year-old copilot Buddy Squires would take off in
their 10-story high, helium-filled balloon at the end of March from
a World War II blimp hangar near Los Angeles.
   ``The race is on,'' Nott said. ``There have been five attempts,
other people are talking about making attempts. There are a lot of
people who've announced they are going to make flights, but there's
no one who's actually shown any hardware.''
   Nott predicted he and Squires would succeed where others have
failed because a pressurized crew cabin would allow his balloon to
sail in the relative calm of the jet stream, well above the stormy
weather of lower altitudes.
   The balloonists intend to soar to 35,000 feet, head east over the
southern United States, the Atlantic Ocean, North Africa, Saudi
Arabia, India, Southeast Asia and China, and set down in California
some 25,000 miles and 18 days later.
   Nott said he had permission from about 35 foreign countries to
float over their territory. He said the voyage has cost about $1.5
million so far.
   The announcement was not the first time the British balloonist
had said he would try to fly non-stop around the world. At a 1986
news conference, Nott told reporters he would lift off in March 1987
from western Australia and head east over New Zealand and the South
Pacific. That plan was scrapped a few months later.
   Nott admitted Wednesday he had been overly optimistic and
underestimated the complexity of his ambitions.
   ``It's just taken longer than we thought,'' he said. ``Everybody
involved has been a little bit overwhelmed. It's simply a bigger
effort than we thought.''
</TEXT>
