<FIRST>r a PM-Burt-License     01-26 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burt-License,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Controversial Gynecologist Surrenders License</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gynecologist James C. Burt has surrendered
his license to practice medicine, but remains unbowed before
challenges to his self-described ``love surgery.''
   The State Medical Board announced Wednesday that it had accepted
Burt's offer to surrender his Ohio medical license, and said the
``surrender-revocation'' also includes a requirement that Burt, 67,
not practice medicine anywhere in the country.
   But in a statement accompanying the announcement, Burt again
denied that he had ever performed the surgery _ a physical
alteration of female genitalia aimed at enhancing sexual
responsiveness _ without patient consent.
   ``Every patient I have ever delivered or operated upon has had at
least one informed consent,'' said Burt, who practiced in Dayton.
   Last month, the State Medical Board charged Burt with ``gross
immorality'' for 41 alleged violations ranging from overprescribing
drugs to performing unnecessary surgeries. The board charged that
the surgery caused sexual dysfunction, emotional distress,
infection, chronic pain, incontinence and the need for corrective
surgery in many patients.
   At least three malpractice lawsuits are pending against Burt,
each asking $3 million in damages. The women say Burt performed the
surgery without their consent. Burt has denied the charges.
   Burt had faced a Jan. 30 hearing before the medical board, but
the panel said its acceptance of the ``surrender-revocation''
eliminates the necessity for formal disciplinary hearings, since
license revocation is the maximum penalty the board can impose on a
licensee.
   Burt's attorney, Earl Moore, said the doctor had been considering
retirement for some time and did not believe the board would treat
him fairly.
   ``He will write and lecture and give seminars,'' Moore said.
``The saga of Doctor Burt is far from over. He's more concerned now
about helping his patients and friends and other doctors.''
   Moore said Burt might continue to promote his surgical technique.
   The matter was brought to public attention when the CBS-TV news
show ``West 57th'' aired a report on Burt's so-called ``female
circumcision'' technique.
   The procedure involved the reconstruction and relocation of the
vagina and the removal of flesh covering the clitoris, an external
tissue that responds to sexual stimulation. Burt described the
technique in his 1975 book, ``Surgery of Love.''
   Burt performed 170 of the operations at St. Elizabeth Medical
Center in Dayton, the last one in February 1987. He agreed to stop
performing the surgery at the hospital last November at the request
of hospital officials.
   Hospital officials said Tuesday that an internal investigation
concluded that all 170 operations were done with patient consent and
that the hospital plans no further action against Burt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
