<FIRST>r i PM-France-Auschwitz     01-26 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Auschwitz,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nuns To Move Out Of Concentration Camp, Archbishop Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Carmelite nuns who were criticized for
setting up a convent inside Auschwitz will move to a site outside
the former Nazi death camp where millions died, the Archibishop of
Lyon said today.
   In a written statement, the archbishop, Cardinal Albert
Decourtray, said he was informed by Cardinal Francicus Macharski of
Krakow that the nuns would be installed in a new convent to be built
outside the center of the Polish camp.
   The monastery was established by a dozen nuns in 1984 in a former
theater in the middle of Auschwitz, setting off a storm of protest
by European Jews who believe the camp should be left as an
undisturbed memorial to its victims.
   Jewish leaders met Dec. 20 in Paris with four Roman Catholic
cardinals to disucss progress toward moving the convent to another
location by February 1989, a deadline set in earlier meetings.
   Today's statement said the nuns will ``live in their new convent
which will be constructed on separate land.'' Decourtray did not
provide details on where the new building would be constructed.
   ``We can wait now for the imminent execution of the convent's
construction that will permit the Carmelites to leave the old
theater,'' the statement said.
   It said the sisters would continue to provide a center for
information, education and prayer at the new location.
   Theo Klein, president of the Council of French Jewish
Institutions, said in a statement today the accord with the
Carmelite sisters was important but that Jewish leaders regretted it
took 30 months for the Polish church to act.
   Klein said he was waiting for details on ``the measures that will
be taken ... by our Catholic partners.''
</TEXT>
