<FIRST>r a PM-FatalFire     01-26 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fatal Fire,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Die In Apartment Fire After Drug Raid By Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A diversionary ``flash-bang'' grenade used by
police in a drug raid may have started the fire that killed an
elderly couple, officials said.
   The police high-risk entry team used a battering ram to break a
window at an apartment Wednesday night, then tossed in the grenade
to divert the occupants' attention and entered the place, said
Police Chief John Laux.
   The apartment was filled with smoke, and officers tried to put
out the fire, but it spread too quickly, the chief said.
   Police and three people inside the apartment fled the building.
The fire, which was confined to the apartment in the 10-unit
complex, was extinguished 15 minutes later.
   The victims, whose names were not immediately released, were
found in a rear bedroom, said Fire Capt. Clarence Matson. Two other
people who had been in the unit, a mother and her child, were
treated at a hospital and released.
   Laux said it was uncertain whether the grenade _ which produces a
blinding light and a popping noise _ caused the fire, but he said
officials would investigate.
   Such devices have been used before and had not caused fires, he
said. ``This was a very routine operation and entry,'' Laux said.
   Two people were arrested in the raid, he said.
