<FIRST>r a PM-EscapeeCrutches     01-26 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Escapee Crutches,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prisoner Drops Crutches, Escapes on Foot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A murder suspect who had been taken to a
hospital dropped his crutches and took off ``like a jackrabbit,''
escaping from a sheriff's deputy, authorities said.
   ``Evidently, his leg was not as bad as believed,'' said Tim
Killian, assistant administrator at the St. Louis County Jail.
   Dennis John Hannuksela, 29, formerly of Gilbert, fled Wednesday
outside the Northland Medical Center, Killian said. He had been in
for a routine visit and was being taken back to the car, said Sgt.
Tom Person, a supervisor at the jail.
   ``The deputy didn't have him in handcuffs, because you don't
handcuff a man on crutches,'' Person said. ``He was unlocking the
car when he heard the crutches drop and looked up to see Hannuksela
running like a jackrabbit.''
   The deputy, who was not identified, chased the suspect but lost
him, authorities said.
   Person said that Hannuksela's injury wasn't faked and speculated
that the prisoner, ``anticipating his escape, punched up his
adrenaline to the point that he could run like crazy.''
