<FIRST>u i PM-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru   01-26 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0512,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Envoy in West Beirut After Report Hostages May be Freed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to CORRECT spelling of British ambassador's name,
ADD quotes from Ramsay, details on British hostages. ADDS byline. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Ambassador Allan Ramsay, escorted
by heavily armed bodyguards, crossed Beirut's dividing Green Line
into the city's Moslem sector today to investigate reports British
hostages might soon be freed.
   Patrick McCabe, Ireland's ambassador to Lebanon, said he also
would head for Beirut from his office in Iraq to investigate the
reports.
   One of the British hostages is Brian Keenan, a Belfast teacher
with dual British and Irish nationality whose release is also sought
by the Ireland.
   A British Embassy spokesman confirmed Ramsay was in west Beirut
and indicated he was trying to check reports that Keenan and
possibly British journalist John McCarthy would be released.
   The other Briton missing in Lebanon is Anglican Church envoy
Terry Waite.
   Ramsay denied his visit had a special significance.
   ``I often come to west Beirut, and there's nothing significant in
my current visit,'' he told The Associated Press by telephone when
asked if it was in connection with the reports.
   He said none of the reports ``can be verified ... I'm anxious to
avoid speculation on that subject.''
   The envoy spoke from the British consular section in west Beirut.
   No faction has claimed to hold Waite, Keenan or McCarthy.
   They are among the 15 foreigners, including nine Americans, held
hostage in Lebanon. The hostage held longest is Terry Anderson,
chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press, who was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   There was no immediate word on where Ramsay went in west Beirut
or whom he planned to meet. ``We have heard a report and we're
making inquiries,'' said the embassy spokesman, on condition of
anonymity.
   Earlier, Christian-run Voice of Lebanon radio said prospects that
British hostages would soon be freed were growing.
   Most hostage releases in the past have been preceded by
statements from the kidnappers. No such statements about Keenan or
McCarthy have been reported.
   McCarthy, 31, a producer for the London-based Worldwide
Television News agency, was kidnapped April 17, 1986, as he drove to
Beirut airport to fly to London. Keenan, 38, an English teacher at
the American University of Beirut, was kidnapped in west Beirut six
days earlier.
   Waite was kidnapped Jan. 20, 1987 while on a mission to negotiate
the release of hostages.
   McCabe told The Associated Press in the Iraqi capital: ``I'll go
to Beirut on the first available flight to investigate rumors there
about the Irish hostage. But as you know there are many rumors in
Beirut.''
   He said he had not received any specific information regarding
any other hostage and noted he was not in a position to say whether
he would negotiate with anyone about the hostages.
   Sources in Belfast said the Foreign Ministry told Keenan's family
it hoped to have ``good news'' on the hostage soon. Keenan's two
sisters were reported to be planning to fly to Beirut.
   In Dublin, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said: ``At the moment,
all we have are rumors from Beirut, but obviously we hope something
will come from these rumors.''
   Hana Naja, a Lebanese assistant at the Irish consular section in
west Beirut, told The AP: ``We have no solid information yet'' about
Keenan being released.
   There has been a flurry of activity by Irish officials over
Middle East issues in recent days.
   Irish Foreign Minister Brian Lenihan met Foreign Minister Ali
Akbar Velayati of Iran in Paris two weeks ago during an
international conference on chemical weapons.
   Ireland's Ambassador to Saudi Arabia, Declan Connolly, flew to
Damascus, the Syrian capital, after the Paris meeting and held talks
with Syrian government officials on undisclosed topics.
   Officials in Damascus said Connolly also met Foreign Minister
Farouk al-Sharaa of Syria on Wednesday night in Damascus.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains 40,000 troops
in eastern and northern provinces as well as Beirut's Moslem sectors.
   The Syrians, Iran's main Arab allies, have been instrumental in
negotiating the release of several foreign hostages in recent years.
   The reports of a possible release came amid a thaw in relations
between Britain and Tehran. They reestablished full diplomatic
relations in November after a 17-month rift.
   A 23-year-old Briton, Nicholas Nicola, who had been held in Iran
for two years after a shooting incident, was freed earlier this
month, raising hopes Britons held in Lebanon might also be freed.
</TEXT>
