<FIRST>u i PM-Israel     01-26 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Prevent Funeral March, Kill One Palestinian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and killed one Palestinian
and wounded three in a clash that occurred after the soldiers
prevented a West Bank village from holding a funeral march, the army
said today.
   The soldiers fired Wednesday night as the villagers fled after
they were told to stop, said an army spokeswoman who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   In violence today, Arab hospital officials said at least 10
Palestinians were shot and wounded by soldiers in the Gaza Strip.
   Also today, troops bulldozed four houses in the West Bank village
of Aqraba, blew up one in the town of Tulkarem, and sealed one in
each of the two sites, the army said. The houses belonged to
families of Palestinians suspected of throwing firebombs at Israeli
troops and cars, an army spokeswoman said.
   The United States and human rights groups have criticized
demolitions as a violation of international law because no legal
hearing is held first.
   The clash outside the West Bank village of Hable began Wednesday
evening after the army lifted a curfew, Arab reporters said.
   Villagers immediately tried to organize a funeral march for a
youth killed in a clash Tuesday, but troops looking for suspects in
previous violence met the residents in an olive grove, the army
spokeswoman said.
   Soldiers shot at the legs of the villagers after they ignored a
call to disperse and warning shots fired in the air, she said.
   She said one Palestinian was killed and three were wounded. Arab
reporters said one of the wounded was in critical condition with
head and chest wounds.
   The death brought to 369 the number of Palestinians killed in the
13-month uprising against Israeli rule in the occupied territories,
which Israel seized from Egypt and Jordan in the 1967 Middle East
War. Fifteen Israelis have died.
   The Cabinet on Wednesday discussed the army's new orders on the
freer use of plastic bullets. Several legislators called for a ban
on plastic and rubber bullets. The new regulations allow officers
and specially trained soldiers to fire plastic bullets to stop
fleeing stone-throwers and to disperse Palestinians erecting
roadblocks.
   Also today, the Defense Ministry confirmed that Faisal Husseini,
one of the most prominent Palestine Liberation Organization
activists in the occupied lands, will soon be released from
detention. Husseini's wife, Najat, said the detention order expires
Sunday.
   Husseini has been held without trial or specific charges for most
of the past 21 months. He was last arrested in July and ordered held
in what is called ``administrative detention'' for six months.
</TEXT>
