<HEAD>Talks With Opposition Expected Soon in Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long-delayed talks between the government
and opposition groups, including Solidarity, will probably begin in
early February, a government spokesman said today.
   Also today, Solidarity leader Lech Walesa met in Warsaw with
aides to prepare for talks with the government on legalizing the
union, according to Jacek Ambroziak, a Walesa aide and lawyer for
the Roman Catholic Episcopate.
   Walesa's advisers did not say who would attend their meeting with
the government, but Tadeusz Mazowiecki, one of Walesa's closest
advisers, said a meeting with government officials was likely to
take place Friday.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Stefan Staniszewski said broader talks
between the government and opposition groups on economic and
political freedom ``should begin in the nearest days,'' probably
Feb. 5 or 6.
   The government first proposed the broad-based talks during labor
unrest in August, but Walesa said authorities must first agree to
legalize his union, which they banned in 1982. Last week, in a
dramatic reversal, the Communist Party's Central Committee said it
would allow more than one legal trade union and opposition
participation in government bodies.
   Solidarity agreed Sunday to hold talks with the government on
legalizing the banned union. This week's talks will be a kind of
preparatory meeting, said a Walesa adviser, the Rev. Henryk
Jankowski of St. Brygida's church in Gdansk.
