<FIRST>r a PM-VirginMary     01-26 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Virgin Mary,0358</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Police Captain's Madonna Statue Sparks ^By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LYNN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two police commanders feuding over a 9-inch
statuette of the Virgin Mary on their shared desk have been put on
different shifts, but their dispute continues before a state
arbitrator.
   The antagonism has spiraled into a full-blown debate over freedom
of religion and separation of church and state.
   ``People kind of think it's silly to be arguing over such a
thing. There are a lot more important things in the world to worry
about,'' said a lieutenant on the 180-member police force who asked
not to be identified.
   The dispute between Capt. Bruce Hogan and Lt. Eugene V. Begley
started when Hogan insisted on placing the pale yellow Madonna on
the desk they shared as the Nos. 1 and 2 in command of department's
night shift in this factory town.
   The veteran officers began trading insults and jibes as the
argument escalated last fall. Hogan accused Begley of shrouding the
religious icon in newspaper whenever the commander stepped out for
lunch.
   Begley reportedly further incurred the captain's wrath when he
skirted Hogan's order not to touch the statuette under any
circumstances.
   ``I never touched it,'' Begley said Wednesday. ``I just put the
cup over it.''
   In November, Chief John F. Hollow transferred Begley to dayside
detective duties.
   On Tuesday, a state arbitrator heard Begley's claim that the
transfer has cost him $45,000 in annual pay because by working days
he can no longer accept extra assignments for traffic control on
road construction projects.
   Three more grievance hearings are scheduled through March.
   ``That statue has no place on a police captain's desk. We have
Catholics, Protestants, Jews and I'm sure a few Muslims in this
department,'' Begley said. ``Hogan has no right to push his religion
on other people. He should not be flaunting it.''
   The chief has declined to comment on the case.
   ``It should never have left the in-house stage,'' spokesman Lt.
Joseph Rowe said. ``The department certainly didn't plan to go
public with it.''
</TEXT>
