<FIRST>r i PM-Arafat-US     01-26 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arafat-US,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aide Says Arafat Won't Seek U.S. Visa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aide to Yasser Arafat said today the PLO
leader has decided not to ask the United States for a visa to let
him address an Arab-American group.
   The president of the American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee,
Abdeen Jabara, said this month the group had invited Arafat to speak
at its April meeting and that he had accepted.
   Nabil Shaath, one of Arafat's top political advisers, did not
explain Arafat's apparent change of heart except to say Arafat
``said he will not go on an invitation from an unofficial group.''
   The only invitation Arafat would accept to visit the United
States would be from officials in Washington, Shaath said.
   Until December, the United States refused to even talk to the
Palestine Liberation Organization. In November, Washington refused
Arafat's request for a visa, saying he endorsed terrorism. Arafat
had requested the visa so he could address the U.N. General
Assembly, and the assembly session was moved to Geneva to
accommodate Arafat.
   Last month, Arafat renounced terrorism and endorsed U.N.
resolutions recognizing Israel's right to exist, leading the United
States to open talks with PLO officials in Tunisia.
   The problem for President Bush's administration is that denying
Arafat a visa now could anger Arab leaders, but granting him one
would draw fire from Israel and groups prominent in U.S. politics
who support the Jewish state.
   Israel still refuses to deal with the PLO, which it considers a
terrorist organization, and it has bitterly criticized the U.S.
decision to talk with it.
</TEXT>
