<SECOND>PM-Assault Rifles,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Semiautomatic Weapons Turned in Under Post-Massacre Buy-Back
Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mayoral candidate's offer to buy back
assault weapons in the aftermath of the Stockton school massacre
yielded two AK-47s and an Uzi.
   Councilman Nate Holden on Tuesday offered to pay up to $300 for
such weapons from a $50,000 campaign fund, a plan derided as
``spitballs at battleships'' by a spokeswoman for Mayor Tom
Bradley's re-election campaign.
   Meanwhile, Police Chief Daryl Gates appeared on ABC's
``Nightline'' Wednesday night to renew his call to outlaw assault
rifles. Today, he was expected to announce plans to form a committee
to explore a 1990 gubernatorial run.
   Assault rifles became a political issue after an AK-47 was used
last week by drifter Patrick Purdy to fire more than 100 bullets
into a schoolyard. Purdy killed five students and wounded 29 others
and a teacher before killing himself.
   Holden said Wednesday the buy-back plan might stem gang slayings.
``Any Uzi or AK-47 that we can get out of the hands of our citizens
and into the hands of law enforcement, where they belong, and
destroyed, would be a step forward,'' he said.
   Bradley spokeswoman Dee Dee Myers said the mayor opposes the sale
of semiautomatic rifles altogether and favors comprehensive laws
rather than a buy-back.
   Holden on Wednesday said a woman who kept the Uzi under her bed
for several years turned it in to ``get it out of her life.''
   A 16-year-old and a 23-year-old man brought unloaded AK-47s to
two police stations, police said. The teen-ager said he received the
rifle as a gift and ``just wanted to be rid of it,'' said spokesman
Lt. Fred Nixon.
