<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 0956EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--PolystyreneBan     01-26 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Polystyrene Ban,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>Council Bans Fast-Food Packaging</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Council has banned polystyrene foam,
joining a growing number of communities where the substance commonly
used in fast-food packaging is unwelcome.
   The ordinance, approved 4-1 Wednesday, was opposed by business
groups and generally favored by environmentalists. It takes effect
in 1990.
   City commissioners said the ban was needed to reduce the amount
of non-biodegradable waste littering streets and choking local
landfills. In addition, the substance has been identified by some as
a hazard to wildlife.
   The measure applies to coffee cups, ``clamshell'' food containers
and other polystyrene items. Non-profit food providers are exempt.
   The ban means hamburgers and other fast-food fare will come
wrapped in foil, paper or cardboard.
   Polystyrene foam food containers have been banned in Suffolk
County, N.Y., and Florida. Berkeley, Calif., has adopted a ban on
all polystyrene foam containers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
