<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--Recycling-China     01-26 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Recycling-China,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>World's Longest Paper Trail?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city plans to move mountains of leftover
office memos, feasibility reports and other paper and put them on a
slow boat to China.
   The plan to put 1,000 tons of reusable scrap paper each day on
container ships bound for China is intended to relieve pressure on
Southern California's landfills, which are rapidly nearing capacity,
officials said Wednesday.
   China Paper Partners will buy the wastepaper from disposal
companies serving office buildings, where workers will be asked to
place discarded food and drink in separate containers. A pilot
program is scheduled to begin Feb. 1.
   Chinese officials said the paper will be recycled at mills China
is planning to build.
   ``There is a great demand for paper material in China,'' said He
Xin Hao, the commercial consul at the Chinese Consulate in Los
Angeles.
