<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1002EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Pope     01-26 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Pope,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Theology Professors Criticize Pope, Church, for Stand on Birth Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 170 Roman Catholic
theology professors today released a declaration strongly
criticizing Pope John Paul II and the church's ban on artificial
birth control.
   The professors took aim primarily at the pontiff's exercise of
power in three areas: choosing new bishops, granting approval to
teach theology, and the pope's teachings.
   All three areas have been subjects of controversy, exemplified by
the dispute over last month's selection of Cardinal Joachim Meisner
to head the archdiocese of Cologne, West Germany, one of the most
influential church posts in Europe. Meisner was reportedly long
backed by the pope but opposed by some clerics in Cologne, who
considered him too conservative.
   ``When the pope does that which isn't part of his office, he
cannot demand obedience in the name of Catholicism,'' the
German-language statement said. ``He must expect dissent.''
   The professors who signed the declaration are based in Austria,
Switzerland, the Netherlands and West Germany. They include
well-known figures such as Hans Kueng of Tuebingen University and
Belgian theologian Edward Schillebeeckx, as well as many other
prominent teachers.
   Another signer was feminist theologian Catharina Halke of
Nijmegen's Catholic University in the Netherlands.
   ``There are professors ranging from the left to the right,'' said
Dietmar Mieth of Tuebingen University, a spokesman for the group.
``They represent a cross section of theology professors in the four
countries.''
   Both priests and lay teachers signed the seven-page document,
Mieth told The Associated Press in a telephone interview.
   At the Vatican, spokesman Joaquin Navarro said: ``I think we are
talking of a local matter and I know that today the German bishops
will make known their thoughts on this point of view.''
   ``I can also say that some people who signed have withdrawn their
support of the document,'' Navarro added, without providing any
names.
   The theologians' declaration complained that the pope recently
has linked the church's teachings on birth control too closely to
fundamental articles of faith, such as the holiness of God.
   It said the link was made so strong that those who criticize the
church's ban on artificial birth control are confronted with
accusations they are ``attacking the fundamental pillars of
Christian teaching.''
   ``The concept of New Testament truth and Jesus' teaching about
salvation are enlisted by the pope to represent a specific teaching
that cannot be justified either in Holy Scripture or in the
traditions of the church,'' the theology teachers said.
   The statement, which the group called the Cologne Declaration,
complained about a rejection of ``theological argumentation'' and
``a neglect of the laity in the church.'' It complained of an
``antagonism from above, which heightens the conflicts in the church
by means of rigid discipline.''
   The Rev. Friedhelm Hengsbach, a professor at the St. Georgen
theology seminary in Frankfurt, said: ``I don't think the Vatican
will be very pleased.''
   Hengsbach, one of the authors of the Cologne Declaration, told
The Associated Press, ``The pope can't expect that people will just
keep saying `yes, yes.''' A spokesman for West Germany's bishops
said they would respond to the declaration after studying it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
