<FIRST>u i PM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru   01-26 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0494,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Militants Blamed for 37 Slayings; Government Puts Troops on Alert</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with new casualty figures. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese militants killed at least 37
people in central and southern Sri Lanka over the past 24 hours,
including an opposition candidate in next month's national
elections, police said today.
   Seven more people were found shot to death, but authorities said
they didn't know if the slayings were politically motivated. Police
shot to death another man believed to be a militant.
   The government placed troops on alert across the nation, and the
Defense Ministry warned militants against further attempts to
disrupt the Feb. 15 elections.
   Police blamed most of the killings on the radical Sinhalese
People's Liberation Front, which has vowed to disrupt the elections
and opposes past government efforts to make peace with Tamil rebels.
   Victims included Nissanka Dharmatilleke, the 10th opposition
candidate to be killed since nominations for the national elections
closed 20 days ago.
   Military officials who spoke on condition of anonymity declined
to say who might have killed the 42-year-old Dharmatilleke.
   He belonged to the United Socialist Alliance, a leftist coalition
whose candidate, Ossie Abeyegoonesekera, finished a distant third in
last month's presidential election.
   Six of the 10 slain candidates belonged to the alliance. The
others belonged to the opposition Sri Lanka Freedom Party led by
Sirimavo Bandaranaike.
   Dharmatilleke's father, two brothers and two political supporters
also were killed in the attack late Wednesday at Katugastotta, 60
miles northeast of Colombo, the capital.
   All the victims were Sinhalese, Sri Lanka's majority ethnic group.
   In another attack Wednesday night, seven Sinhalese were shot to
death at Kadugannawa, five miles southeast of Katugastotta, but
military officials said they did not know if the killings were
politically motivated.
   Police said 31 people, all Sinhalese, were killed by militants in
18 separate incidents in southern and eastern cities. They did not
give details.
   A man killed in police firing in southern Sri Lanka late
Wednesday was identified as J.L. Siripala, a suspected militant,
officials said.
   Opposition parties have blamed the candidates' killings on
supporters of the United National Party headed by Ranasinghe
Premadasa, Sri Lanka's new president. Members of the governing party
have denied the charge and blamed the People's Liberation Front.
   The front has denied responsibility for the latest killings.
   Sinhalese comprise 75 percent of Sri Lanka's population of 16
million people and dominate the political and military
establishments. Tamils make up 18 percent of the population.
   A Tamil separatist war in northern and eastern Sri Lanka has
prompted a Sinhalese backlash. The People's Liberation Front
initially targeted the United National Party, saying Premadasa's
predecessor, President Junius R. Jayewardene, had gone too far in
his peacemaking efforts with the Tamils.
</TEXT>
