<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-LiberalBlueprint 1stLd-Writethru a0455 01-26 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Liberal Blueprint, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0455,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Liberal Group Pushes Agenda</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 4 grafs new with news conference; picks up at pvs 4th graf,
In an</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of liberals in and out of Congress
today denounced former President Reagan for a legacy of ``neglected
needs'' and said it will press President Bush to do better.
   ``We don't need to play on their turf. If we play on their turf,
we lose,'' Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, said at a news conference at
which the Democracy Project, a New York-based think tank, released a
600-page blueprint for liberal action.
   ``We are going to be more than kind and gentle; we are going to
be bold and imaginative,'' said Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore.
   In the 38-chapter broadside it issued, the Democracy Project
said, ``We now see the difference between good acts and good acting
and how popularity is not the same as problem solving.''
   In an introduction to the volume, Mark Green, president of the
project, said both ``opportunity and peril'' confront the 41st
president and the 101st Congress.
   ``But diverting America from responding well are the multiple
crises Ronald Reagan has bequeathed us,'' he said. ``It's hard to
ignore his accumulation of neglected needs.''
   The document also criticized Bush for failing to deal in his
campaign with issues ranging from the need for public housing to the
plight of nuclear weapons production plants.
   ``Stressing flags and furloughs may have been a winning political
formula, but it will now take a microscope to detect Bush's mandate
for change,'' Green wrote.
   The critique did not spare the Democrats and their presidential
nominee either.
   ``Clearly Reagan and Bush have a very few understandable themes,
involving less taxes and government, while Democrats seem to flit
from one framework and slogan to another,'' it said. ``Michael
Dukakis tried to define himself as the sum of his position papers,
but it still didn't add up to a coherent whole.'
   The group said Bush's call for a ``kinder, gentler nation'' along
with his pronouncements on education, ethics and the environment
``do obligate him to pursue more compassionate solutions. Even
`liberal' solutions.''
   Among specific recommendations were public financing of Senate
and House races, requiring large employers to provide health
coverage for their workers, giving up Reagan's Star Wars plan of a
space-based missile defense as a bargaining chip to obtain
reductions in nuclear weaponry, and avoiding any ``precipitous''
balancing of the budget for fear of triggering a recession.
   The document contrasts sharply with a blueprint issued Dec. 8 by
the conservative Heritage Foundation, which called for greater
reliance on private-sector health insurance, withdrawing from the
1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty to permit faster movement on Star
Wars, and increasing the personal income tax exemption for children
to $6,500.
   Members of Congress listed as attending today's press briefing
were Sens. Wyche Fowler of Georgia and Tom Harkin of Iowa and Reps.
Byron Dorgan of North Dakota, Edward Markey of Massachusetts and
Henry Waxman of California. All are Democrats.
   ``Reaganites concluded that the best way to produce sustained
growth was to concentrate on stimulating well-off investors to save,
invest and produce more,'' the group's analysis said. ``This
emphasis, however, conveniently led to a flood of corporate
giveaways and upscale tax breaks. The results? Savings and
investment fell after enactment of Reagan's tax budget program in
1981, and the distribution of wealth predictably worsened.''
   It also said that ``Reagan administration family policies have
been pro-life, pre-birth; but once the fetus became an infant, the
government ran away from home.''
   ``It's an odd priority to think that large corporations need tax
incentives to be productive but that you ruin a child if you give
him or her a hot lunch,'' the critique said.
   In U.S.-Soviet relations, the document said, Reagan ``deserves
praise for finally appreciating the need to trade proposals rather
than insults,'' but failed to formulate a plan for responding to new
Soviet initiatives.
   In the field of government ethics, it said, the former president
``never once publicly reproached his dozens of derelict appointees.''
</TEXT>
