<FIRST>u p PM-VaGovernor     01-26 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Va Governor,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wilder Formally Enters Governor's Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Gov. L. Douglas Wilder, who confounded
political experts in 1985 by winning statewide office in the
conservative South, opened a bid today to become the nation's first
elected black governor.
   ``Forty years ago, working my way through college and law school
as a waiter and busboy, I never dreamed I would have the opportunity
to run for governor of Virginia,'' the 58-year-old Democrat told
hundreds of cheering supporters.
   Wilder announced a ``three for Virginia'' plan _ permanent tax
relief, a fight against drugs and drug-related crime, and creation
of jobs and housing for rural Virginians.
   Wilder has no opposition for the Democratic nomination, which
will be decided at the party convention in June. State Sen. Daniel
W. Bird Jr. pulled out of the race two days ago, citing low
fund-raising.
   On the Republican side, former Sen. Paul Trible has announced for
governor and is expected to face former Virginia Attorney General
Marshall Coleman for the nomination.
   Louisiana had a black governor during Reconstruction, but he was
not elected; Lt. Gov. Pinckney Pinchback became acting governor in
1872-73 after Gov. Henry Warmoth was removed from office.
   In 1985, Wilder's nomination for lieutenant governor drew
predictions of doom for the party ticket in Virginia, which is 82
percent white.
   But Wilder and his running mate, Gerald L. Baliles, won, thanks
in part to the popularity of outgoing Gov. Charles S. Robb, now a
U.S. senator. Wilder received 44 percent of the white vote and 97
percent of the black vote.
   Baliles is barred by the state constitution from seeking a second
consecutive term.
   As a state senator from Richmond in the 1970s, Wilder was seen as
a left-of-center oddity in a body dominated by conservative whites.
   Wilder's views and his rhetoric have moderated, however. He
refused to use race as an issue in the 1985 campaign and has been a
generally loyal, if sometimes fretful, team player as lieutenant
governor.
   In his biggest rift with Baliles, he complained about a
half-penny sales tax increase passed in 1986. But Wilder's criticism
came after the session and angered the governor, who wanted to know
why Wilder did not speak up sooner.
</TEXT>
