<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Italy-Calvi     01-26 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Italy-Calvi,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian Court Reportedly Concludes Banker Was Murdered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Milan court has concluded that banker Roberto
Calvi, whose body was found hanging from a London bridge in 1982
after his Banco Ambrosiano collapsed, was murdered, newspapers
reported today.
   A coroner's jury in London in June 1983 left unresolved the
question of whether Calvi hanged himself, perhaps driven to suicide
by his inability to account for $1.4 billion in loans and interest,
or whether he was murdered to stop him from talking about a
financial scandal reaching into the Vatican.
   Calvi was popularly known as ``God's banker'' because of his
close ties with the Vatican.
   The action in the Milan civil court was brought by Calvi's widow,
Clara, who is trying to collect on a $3 million life insurance
policy.
   Calvi was insured by Assicurazioni Generali, Italy's largest
insurance company. A spokesman, Armando Zimolo, said the policy
ruled out payment in case of suicide. The company may appeal today's
decision.
   According to the newspaper accounts, the court reached its
conclusion on the basis of an autopsy and a reconstruction of what
the court believed happened the night of June 17, 1982, at
Blackfriars Bridge in London.
   Court officials could not be reached for comment.
   Calvi was found twisting in the wind from scaffolding under the
bridge. His suit pockets were loaded with 11 pounds of bricks and a
brick was stuffed down the front of his pants.
   The Vatican bank was the largest shareholder of Banco Ambrosiano.
   Banco Ambrosiano collapsed following its failure to collect $1.4
billion in Vatican bank-assured loans made to 10 dummy companies in
Latin America.
</TEXT>
