<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-OPEC 1stLd-Writethru a0522 01-26 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-OPEC, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0522,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>OPEC, Independent Oil-Producing Nations Meet</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 11th graf, `The spot ...,' to UPDATE with today's prices.
Picks up in 12th graf, `The non-OPEC ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts from OPEC and independent oil-producing
nations met today in a second attempt to reach a cooperative
agreement to support crude oil prices.
   Both sides gathered at a hall this morning in the City, London's
financial district, for a second joint session. A first _ and
unsuccessful _ meeting took place last April.
   The secretary-general of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, Subroto, told reporters Wednesday that the two sides
``will exchange information'' today and plan to issue a joint
statement afterward.
   The non-OPEC group issued a communique Wednesday saying: ``The
(non-OPEC) delegates unanimously share the desire to see the oil
market stabilize, an issue they consider of importance to both
consumers and producers of oil.''
   A senior OPEC source said he was hopeful an agreement could be
reached for independent producers to cut their production, although
he said that wasn't likely soon.
   ``Our unity is stronger now. Prices have strengthened and we are
ready'' for a cooperative agreement, said the OPEC source, who
requested anonymity.
   ``This is the first step in a step-by-step move'' to push up oil
prices, the source added.
   In April, six non-OPEC producers met with representatives from
six of OPEC's 13 members and suggested they jointly cut their
exports by 5 percent. OPEC, then more divided, rejected that
proposal.
   This time, some of the seven attending non-OPEC producers might
offer to cut their collective production by 5 percent, without
asking for reciprocal cuts from OPEC, non-OPEC sources said this
week.
   They likely would want reassurances from OPEC that in that event,
the cartel would not increase its own production.
   The spot price of North Sea Brent Blend, the most widely traded
international crude oil, was $16.76 a barrel in afternoon trading
today, up 16 cents from late Wednesday. West Texas Intermediate, the
U.S. benchmark crude oil, rose 25 cents to $18.37 a barrel today in
late-morning trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   The non-OPEC communique said representatives of Angola, China,
Colombia, Egypt, Malaysia, Mexico, and Oman met with observers from
the Soviet Union, Norway, the Yemen Arab Republic and the Canadian
province of Alberta and the states of Alaska and Texas.
   OPEC participants feel that if all goes well this week, the next
step would be to call a meeting of the ministers of the six members
of the OPEC contact group with ministers from the participating
non-OPEC countries, the source said.
   That is likely to take place in late March to coincide with an
OPEC committee meeting scheduled for March 29 in Vienna, the source
said.
   Holding such a meeting might be useful to help support oil prices
during the second quarter, when demand traditionally slackens and
prices weaken.
   OPEC members agreed in November to limit their production to 18.5
million barrels a day in an effort to boost prices to a targeted $18
a barrel. The agreement was effective Jan. 1.
   OPEC members are producing an estimated 19.5 million barrels a
day, down as much as 3.5 million barrels a day from the fourth
quarter. That has helped oil prices recover from about $12 a barrel
in December.
   In their previous accord, OPEC members agreed to limit production
to 15.06 million barrels a day.
   The next full OPEC ministerial meeting is scheduled for June.
   The other OPEC members are Ecuador, Gabon, Libya, Qatar, Iran,
Iraq and the United Arab Emirates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890126-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-NerveGas-Arrest     01-26 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nerve Gas-Arrest,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Prosecutor: Businessman Charged In Nerve Gas Plot Had Military Contacts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Korean-American businessman charged in a
plot to export nerve gas had contacts at U.S. military bases and
possessed Army ``fact sheets'' available only to authorized defense
contractors, a prosecutor said today.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Anne Singer raised the issues after an
attorney for the Short Hills businessman, Juwhan Yun, asked a judge
to release his client on bail.
   Yun, 48, had also asked Bendix Technologies about buying a
chemical agent that could be used to mask the presence of sarin, the
deadly nerve gas that the government accuses him of trying to
acquire, said Ms. Singer.
   Correspondence found in his possession ``does show that he has
contacts with persons at U.S. military bases,'' she told U.S.
District Judge H. Lee Sarokin. After the hearing, Ms. Singer
declined to elaborate on her statement.
   She also told the judge Yun was not an authorized defense
contractor but had fact sheets provided by the Army only to
contractors on an approved distribution list.
   Last week, Ms. Singer disclosed that investigators searching
Yun's Summit business, Komex International Corp., found national
security documents marked secret and confidential.
   Today, she said those papers amount to 30 pages in English and
100 pages in Korean, which indicates some documents were jointly
classified by the U.S. and South Korean governments.
   ``He has a source of documents somewhere,'' said the prosecutor.
She said an espionage charge could be added to the indictment, which
charged Yun with conspiring to violate federal controls on arms
exports.
   Ms. Singer repeated that Yun boasted of high-level contacts with
civilian and military officials of foreign governments including
South Korea, the People's Republic of China and Yugoslavia.
   Yun ``would spend much money entertaining them when they came to
this country,'' she said.
   Sarokin asked the government for further transcripts of Yun's
dealings with an undercover customs agent posing as an arms dealer
before ruling on Yun's bail request. He did not indicate when he
would rule.
   A magistrate had set bail at $2 million, which Yun met through
friends posting their properties, but withdrew it last Friday after
Ms. Singer revealed Yun's alleged possession of the classified
documents.
   Yun's attorney, Stephen Dratch, argued it was unfair to hold Yun
on the basis of those documents without charging him for having them.
   Yun was arrested Jan. 12 at a meeting with an undercover agent.
The government said he conspired with London businessman Charles
Caplan to acquire the gas for possible export to Iran. Caplan was
also indicted and is a fugitive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
