<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Mideast     01-26 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Mideast,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Shamir Talk; No Visit Set</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush called Israeli Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir for ``a very general discussion,'' but no plans were
made for the two to meet, Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said
today.
   Fitzwater said Bush's call to Shamir on Wednesday ``was one of a
series of conversations'' the president has been having by telephone
this week with world figures who had sent congratulatory messages on
his inauguration.
   ``They did discuss the idea that they'd both like to visit each
others' countries,'' the spokesman said. But ``no dates were set and
no specific commitments were made.''
   Fitzwater also said the new administration opposes direct talks
between top U.S. officials and Yasser Arafat, chairman of the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   ``We believe it would be premature at this time'' for Arafat to
meet with Secretary of State James A. Baker III or with Bush, the
spokesman said.
   The U.S. government authorized State Department diplomats to have
contacts with PLO representatives in the waning days of the Reagan
administration. This came after Arafat publicly renounced terrorism
as an instrument of policy and said he accepted Israel's right to
exist.
   ``We will be watching the actions of the PLO as they undertake to
uphold their recent promises,'' Fitzwater said when asked whether
the United States would upgrade the level of contacts with the PLO.
   `` ... We are looking for a long-term commitment,'' he said,
``and we will be judging accordingly. But it's too soon at this time
to talk about those kinds of meetings.''
</TEXT>
