<FIRST>u w PM-CollectiveBarganining     01-26 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Collective Barganining,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wages Rose Average 2.6 Percent In First Year Of New Contracts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nearly 1.8 million workers in private
industry affected by collective bargaining settlements signed last
year received an average first-year pay raise of 2.6 percent, the
government said today.
   For the full term of major new contracts settled last year, wage
increases averaged 2.4 percent, the Labor Department reported.
Nearly 80 percent of the 1.79 million workers whose bargaining units
settled contracts in 1988 received a pay increase, while 2 percent
saw their wages decline and the rest say their pay stay the same.
   The Labor Department tracks wage settlements for 6 million
workers in private industry whose bargaining units have at least
1,000 members. Of that group, 1.79 million were affected by
contracts settled in 1988.
   The raises they received compared to average first-year increases
of 1.8 percent and overall average annual raises of 2.6 percent in
their prior contracts, most of which were negotiated in 1985 or 1986.
   In addition to their contractual raises, about 28 percent _
504,000 _ of the workers affected in 1988 also received some form of
lump-sum payment, generally performance or attendance bonuses. The
average contractual wage increase for those workers was 1.4 percent
both in the first year of the contract and throughout its term,
lagging behind the average pay raises for workers whose employers
did not provide lump-sum payments in addition to raises negotiated
through collective bargaining.
   The Labor Department said 38 percent, or 686,000, of the workers
affected by contracts signed last year will receive cost-of-living
adjustments under the pacts. Contracts allowing for such
adjustments, however, contained average wage increases of 1.8
percent a year compared to 2.8 percent a year in contracts without
COLA clauses. Those adjustments generally are based on the
government's Cosumer Price Index.
   Workers in manufacturing on average received a smaller percentage
increase in their wages than those in the non-manufacturing sector,
the government said. Settlements affecting 706,000 manufacturing
workers contained average pay increases of 2.2 percent in the first
year and 2.1 percent a year over the life of the contract. Wage
increases averaged 2.8 percent in the first year and 2.5 percent
annually overall for the more than 1 million workers in the
non-manufacturing sector of the economy covered by major settlements
signed in 1988.
   In all, there were 415 contracts settled last year involving
bargaining units of 1,000 or more workers. The average duration of
the new contracts was 33.3 months.
</TEXT>
