<HEAD>Australia to Accept More Vietnamese for Resettlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Australia will double to 4,000 its
annual quota for Vietnamese seeking permission to leave their
homeland, an embassy official said Thursday.
   Embassy Counselor Gervais Appave said Australia wanted to help
relieve the burden on Thailand and other Southeast Asian countries
to which Vietnamese have fled.
   The new quota, to begin in July, applies only to Vietnamese who
want to settle through a U.N.-sponsored Orderly Departure Program.
In addition, Australia allows 6,000 Indochinese to resettle in
Australia each year.
   About 120,000 Indochinese refugees, mostly Vietnamese, have
resettled in Australia since the end of the Vietnam War in 1975.
