<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-LiberalBlueprint     01-26 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Liberal Blueprint,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Liberals Tell Bush Chopping Deficit Too Fast Could Hurt Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of liberals in and out of Congress
urged President Bush Thursday to go slow in reducing the budget
deficit and abandon the Reagan administration's ``obsession'' with
the Star Wars program of space-based missile defense.
   The Democracy Project, a self-described progressive research
group based in New York, outlined its views at a news conference at
which officers of the project were joined by Democratic members of
Congress.
   ``The risks of reducing the deficit too quickly are at least as
serious as the risks of doing nothing at all,'' said James
Galbraith, a professor of economics at the University of Texas and a
former director of the Joint Economic Committee of Congress.
   Any ``precipitous'' balancing of the federal budget, the group
said in its report, would run the risk of triggering a recession.
   Paul Warnke, head of the Arms Control and Disarmament Agency in
the Carter administration, spoke for the organization on foreign
policy, saying that Bush ``has an almost unparalleled opportunity to
remove the risk of nuclear war and end the military confrontation in
Europe.''
   One of the principal obstacles standing in the way, he said, is
``the obsession that has existed with regard to strategic defense.''
But he said this obstacle ``is removing itself'' because ``neither
the technology nor the funds are there.''
   In its report the group recommended that the Bush administration
use the Star Wars plan as a bargaining chip in negotiations to
obtain reductions in nuclear weaponry, something the Reagan
administration refused to do.
   Commenting on the group's report, Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa,
suggested that congressional Democrats should not accept Bush's
budget if it makes only minor adjustments in the Reagan budget.
   ``We don't need to play on their turf; if we play on their turf,
we lose,'' said Harkin.
   ``We are going to be more than kind and gentle; we are going to
be bold and imaginative,'' said Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore.
   The Democracy Project report said, ``We now see the difference
between good acts and good acting and how popularity is not the same
as problem solving.''
   It said Bush failed to deal in his campaign with such issues as a
need for public housing and the problems of nuclear weapons plants.
   ``Stressing flags and furloughs may have been a winning political
formula, but it will now take a microscope to detect Bush's mandate
for change,'' said Mark Green, president of the project, in an
introduction to the book.
   The project also had some critical words for the Democrats and
their unsuccessful presidential nominee, saying, ``Clearly Reagan
and Bush have a very few understandable themes, involving less taxes
and government, while Democrats seem to flit from one framework and
slogan to another. Michael Dukakis tried to define himself as the
sum of his position papers, but it still didn't add up to a coherent
whole.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
