<FIRST>r a PM-Anti-Semitic     01-26 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Anti-Semitic,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Semitic Acts Climb in 1988 to 5-Year High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reported cases of anti-Semitic harassment rose 41
percent in the United States in 1988, and anti-Semitic vandalism was
up 18.5 percent, according to a survey released today by the
Anti-Defamation League.
   The figures showed the number of such incidents in 1988 reached
their highest level in five years.
   Abraham Foxman, national director of the Anti-Defamation League
of B'nai B'rith, called the nearly 1,300 incidents reported by law
enforcement authorities in 40 states, the District of Columbia and
Puerto Rico ``disturbing'' and ``a sign of concern.''
   Foxman could not point to a specific cause for the increase but
cited ``specific stimulants,'' including activities by organized
hate groups like the Ku Klux Klan and neo-Nazi Skinheads;
counter-activities during the 50th anniversary of Kristallnacht,
observed by many as the beginning of the Holocaust, and political
unrest in Israel's West Bank and Gaza.
   Foxman also pointed to an increase in anti-Semitic incidents on
college campuses and in the South, which has a small Jewish
population.
   The survey showed that there were 458 incidents of harassment
reported in 1988 compared to 324 in 1987, an increase of 41 percent.
The cases included seven arson incidents, one bombing and seven
attempted arsons.
   There were 823 incidents of anti-Semitic vandalism last year, up
from 694 the previous year, according to the survey. It marked the
second sharp increase in a row after a four-year decline.
</TEXT>
