<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Electricity     01-26 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Electricity,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Power Plant Up, but Many Iranians Still in Dark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Part of a giant Iranian power plant
damaged in the war with Iraq went back into service Thursday, a
radio report said, but Iranians still face blackouts.
   A 400-megawatt unit of the Neka plant in northern Iran began
operation, Tehran radio said. But the plant on the Caspian Sea will
produce only a fraction of its pre-war capacity of 1,760 megawatts.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, said the plant will boost the
country's sluggish power output by 6 percent. The facility was
heavily damaged during the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war and rebuilt
following the Aug. 20 cease-fire.
   ``Power plants have have been targeted as one of the priority
projects in Iran's (post-war) reconstruction plan,'' Prime Minister
Hussein Musavi said during Thursday's opening ceremony, the radio
said.
   Musavi has said electricity demand increased to 7,850 megawatts
from 2,876 megawatts in the past 10 years.
   The Neka plant, pounded twice in long-range Iraqi air attacks,
will cost around $50 million to repair completely.
   Power Minister Bijan Namdar Zanganeh was quoted by the radio two
weeks ago as saying power blackouts would continue in coming months
because not enough power could be restored to meet demand.
   The daily blackouts, which have lasted since the 1979 revolution
that put Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini in power, typically last up to
six hours in the major cities. Often, there is no advance warning.
   There has been a long-running debate in the newspapers about
whether the Power Ministry should announce the power cuts in
advance. A ministry official said authorities fear burglars would
plan ahead if such announcements were made.
</TEXT>
