<SECOND>PM-Barry, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0529,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>D.C. Council Members Said Urging Mayor to Retire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs grafs 2-3, ``The Washington ... Democrats,'' to show
both reports with five council members attending.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About half of the members of the city council
have privately urged Mayor Marion Barry Jr. not to run for
re-election in 1990, as federal prosecutors negotiated with the
mayor's attorney to broaden their investigation into his personal
activities, it was reported today.
   The Washington Post and WUSA-TV said five councilmen met with
Barry at the home of member Nadine P. Winter on Saturday and told
him they were concerned about his well-being, how the city was being
run, the political fallout and possible damage to the city's
relationship with the federal government.
   All the participants are Democrats. The council has 12 members.
   Barry, who has been in office 10 years, confirmed a meeting took
place but said the report of the council members' advice were
``erroneous.'' He said the meeting concerned only issues such as the
budget and housing.
   Others attending the meeting declined to comment on whether
Barry's political future was discussed.
   In the past two weeks, Barry has testified twice before a federal
grand jury looking into a Dec. 22 incident at a downtown hotel, as
well as the possible misuse of government funds in a joint
D.C.-Virgin Islands personnel project.
   Two police detectives investigating a drug complaint at the hotel
left after learning Barry was in the room of the suspect, Charles
Lewis.
   Lewis was the former director for the personnel project for the
Virgin Islands government. Police said traces of cocaine were found
in his room.
   According to the Post, prosecutors have sought to broaden the
hotel inquiry by asking Barry to submit to grand jury questioning
about whether he has used drugs in the last five years.
   Prosecutors and Barry's attorney, R. Kenneth Mundy, have
discussed the scope of the questions to be posed to the mayor before
the grand jury, the newspaper reported.
   Mundy said Wednesday that prosecutors ``are not trying to
compel'' Barry to testify about whether he has used drugs. ``That
statement is untrue. They have not asked that question,'' he said.
   Barry has repeatedly denied ever using drugs or knowingly being
associated with drug dealers or users.
   After Barry's second grand jury appearance Tuesday, Mundy said he
did not anticipate the mayor testifying again.
