<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     01-26 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops on Alert After Flareup in Ethnic Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Militant Sinhalese killed at least 45
people in pre-election violence, and the government ordered troops
on alert Thursday to protect political rallies, officials said.
   The Defense Ministry warned militants against ``subversive plans
to intimidate people, promote clashes between political parties, and
disrupt the Feb. 4 Sri Lanka independence day celebrations.''
   Troops went on alert nationwide to protect political party
campaigning for parliamentary elections Feb. 15, officials said on
condition of anonymity.
   A separatist war waged by ethnic Tamils in northern and eastern
Sri Lanka has prompted the Sinhalese backlash. Tamils make up 18
percent of the population of this island nation off the southern tip
of India.
   Officials said shortly after President Ranasinghe Premadasa took
office Jan. 2 that India had begun withdrawing troops it dispatched
in 1987 to try to disarm Tamil insurgents.
   At least 10 opposition candidates of the 1,393 people running for
225 seats in the national Parliament have been killed this month.
   On Wednesday, three attackers raked a house with machine guns at
Katugastotta about 60 miles from Colombo, killing opposition
candidate Nissanka Dharmatilleke, two brothers, and two supporters,
military officials said. They declined to say who was responsible.
   Police officials speaking on condition of anonymity blamed the
24-hour flareup in violence on militants of the Sinhalese People's
Liberation Front.
   The front opposes government efforts to make peace with the Tamil
rebels and has vowed to disrupt the elections.
   The opposition parties have blamed the candidates' killings on
supporters of the United National Party headed by Premadasa. Party
members deny the charge and blame the militant Sinhalese group. The
Front says it is not responsible.
   Sinhalese comprise 75 percent of Sri Lanka's population of 16
million people and dominate politics and the military. Tamils make
up 18 percent.
</TEXT>
