<FIRST>r w AM-People-Scobee     01-26 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Scobee,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Challenger Pilot's Widow to Marry Army General in June</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   June Scobee, widow of Challenger space shuttle
pilot Dick Scobee, is engaged to marry an Army general in June and
will step down as chairman of the Challenger Center for Space
Science Education, an aide said Thursday.
   Mrs. Scobee, 46, will marry Lt. Gen. Don Rodgers, commander of
the Global Army Information Systems Command at Fort Huachuca, Ariz.,
according to Lisa Turner, director of public and media relations for
the Challenger center in Houston.
   The two met last Easter at a sunrise service at Arlington
National Cemetery, where Mrs. Scobee had gone to visit the grave of
her husband, who died with the six other astronauts in the Jan. 28,
1986, explosion of the space shuttle.
   Rodgers, 54, is a widower. They did not see each other for five
months after that initial meeting, but then began dating and now
have set June 3 as their wedding date.
   Mrs. Scobee has spearheaded efforts to raise $30 million to
finance several centers around the country to teach children and
teachers about space. It is halfway toward that goal, with $5
million raised privately and $10 million recently appropriated by
Congress, Ms. Turner said.
   Mrs. Scobee will remain on the Challenger center's advisory board
after her two-year term as chairman expires March 16, Ms. Turner
said.
   Mrs. Scobee has two grown children, Kathie, 27, a media
consultant in College Station, Texas, and Rich, 25, an Air Force
pilot flying F-16s in West Germany.
   The Challenger center opened its prototype educational facility
at the Houston Museum of Natural Science last summer, and plans to
open three more this year at the Boston Museum of Science, the
Pacific Science Center in Seattle and at the Howard B. Owens Science
Center in Prince George's County, Md., near the Goddard Space Flight
Center.
   The center also plans to build a ``Space Life Station'' in the
nation's capital near the Mall.
   Mrs. Scobee, who has a doctorate in education, also plans to
resume her work as an educational consultant, at least on a
voluntary basis, Ms. Turner said.
   She will be the first Challenger widow or widower to remarry.
</TEXT>
