<FIRST>r a AM-People     01-26 0928</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0963</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANTANA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If all goes as planned, actor Burt Reynolds
will outmaneuver helicopters and dodge simulated gunfire in an
escape from prison Friday. But the sniping from unhappy townspeople
is a more immediate threat.
   Residents living near the Lantana Correctional Institution say
they've had enough of breakouts lately _ real or as part of a
television script.
   Reynolds' Blue Period Productions will film the escape from the
minimum-security prison for the third episode of the ``B.L.
Stryker'' detective series, publicist Carol Feder said Wednesday.
   The plot is a little too authentic for Lantana Town Manager Don
Harvey, who told Department of Corrections officials he objected to
the idea because his community is tense over a series of escapes
from the prison last year.
   ``The timing is absolutely inappropriate,'' Harvey said. ``I
don't think this community needs to go through any other trauma with
real or simulated events at LCI.''
   To avoid crowds of onlookers, producers normally don't release
advance information about filming locations, Feder said. But
concerns from Harvey and others prompted the production company to
alert residents to Friday's filming.
   ``We'll be posting notices in the area so residents won't be
concerned. We wanted to make sure nobody got upset,'' Feder said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The father in television's ``Family Ties'' has
a message for families in the real world: Be careful at railroad
crossings.
   ``Look, listen and live,'' actor Michael Gross says in a series
of public service announcements to be broadcast on TV and radio
starting March 1.
   The campaign is sponsored by Operation Lifesaver, a rail-crossing
safety program the Union Pacific Railroad started in 1972. Its
message is delivered throughout the United States and Canada.
   Gross has qualifications beyond his acting ability, Ed Trandahl
of the Union Pacific said.
   His grandfather and great-grandfather were railroad workers, and
Gross worked summers as a brakeman for the Chicago &amp; North Western
Transportation Co. while attending college.
   ``A lot of you parents may have children who are just getting
their driver's license,'' one script says. ``Do them a favor _ and
yourself, too. Tell them to be especially careful at highway
railroad crossings.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maestro Riccardo Muti's dream night for the
Philadelphia Orchestra came true when a television station
pre-empted network fare and moved a crew and co-hosts into the
Academy of Music.
   Muti and the musicians brought Beethoven's Symphony No. 4 to life
in a special two-hour ``Come And Meet The Music'' concert carried
live Wednesday night on KYW-TV.
   The effort, he said afterward, was a ``complete success'' no
matter what the viewer ratings turned out to be. He found a way to
reach from the Academy stage right into the home and he liked it.
   ``It was a good audience ... a good audience,'' he said,
referring both to those in the hall and those who tuned in.
   ``You need television because when you play a concert hall, you
can only reach two to three thousand people. You can reach many more
with television, and that's important.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1989 Golden Pen of Freedom Award has been given
to Sergei Grigoryants, founding editor and publisher of the
independent Soviet magazine Glasnost, the International Federation
of Newspaper Publishers said Thursday.
   The Paris-based federation applauded Grigoryants' dedication to
freedom of expression, but said it was concerned that Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev had denounced him as a ``parasite.''
   Grigoryants, 47, was hailed as a ``brave man whose treatment has
shown how much the attitudes of the Soviet authorities to the press
_ newly evidenced in the draft of a severely restrictive press law _
must change if the widely proclaimed policy of glasnost is ever to
become other than a propagandist's mockery,'' said the statement
issued after a meeting of the 30-member federation board in Zurich.
   Gorbachev has made glasnost, or the opening of Soviet society, a
hallmark of his rule.
   Grigoryants' wife, who is visiting Paris, said the award was
``wonderful and a tribute to all he has tried to do.''
   Grigoryants will be invited to receive his award at the 42nd
World Congress of Newspaper Publishers being organized by the
federation in New Orleans, Lousiana, June 11-14.
   The Golden Pen is awarded annually by the federation, which
strives to defend and promote press freedom and the economic
independence of news publishers as an essential condition for
freedom.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman will become a full-time network
weeknight television news anchor within the next decade, according
to the first woman to work in such a job _ albeit temporarily.
   ``I wouldn't want to predict what year,'' said Marlene Sanders,
who made TV history in 1964 when she sat in on NBC for an ailing Ron
Cochran.
   Ms. Sanders, age ``58, the same as Dan Rather'' will be in
October, spoke this week to the local chapter of American Women in
Radio and Television.
   When women anchors break the weeknight network sex barrier
``depends on how women do in the country at large,'' said Ms.
Sanders, co-author with Marcia Rock of ``Waiting for Prime Time: The
Women of Television News.''
   ``When we see more women in high places, it will filter down to
the networks,'' she said.
   After a decade as an Emmy-winning correspondent for CBS News, she
fell victim to a wave of network cuts in 1987, turning down an offer
to work nights and weekends for CBS Radio.
   ``I wasn't fired, exactly,'' she said. ``I decided to take my
chances in the outside world.''
</TEXT>
