<FIRST>r w AM-CollectiveBargaining     01-26 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Collective Bargaining,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wages Up 2.4 Percent On Average In Major 1988 Contracts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 1.8 million workers covered by major
collective-bargaining contracts signed in 1988 will receive average
annual pay raises of 2.4 percent, the government said Thursday.
   For the first year of those 415 contracts, covering bargaining
units with 1,000 or more members, the average pay gain is 2.6
percent, the Labor Department said.
   That compared to average first-year increases of 1.8 percent and
overall annual raises of 2.6 percent in those workers' prior
contracts, most of which had been negotiated in 1985 or 1986.
   On the whole, workers in manufacturing jobs fared less well than
workers in non-manufacturing positions.
   Nearly 80 percent of the 1.79 million owners affected by
contracts signed last year saw a boost in pay, while 2 percent face
wage cuts and the rest had their wages stay the same.
   About 28 percent of the workers affected in 1988 also received
some form of lump-sum payment, generally performance or attendance
bonuses. The Labor Department said 38 percent of workers were
eligible for cost-of-living adjustments under their new pacts.
   Settlements affecting 706,000 manufacturing workers contained
average pay increases of 2.2 percent in the first year and 2.1
percent a year over the life of the contract. Wage increases
averaged 2.8 percent in the first year and 2.5 percent annually
overall for the more than 1 million workers in the non-manufacturing
sector of the economy covered by major settlements signed in 1988.
   The average duration of contracts settled in 1988 was 33.3 months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
