<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     01-26 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who admits he ``had a terrible time
trying to play the clarinet when I was young'' is now president of a
company that turns musical morons into passable players who don't
even need to use their hands.
   Warble a ``do re mi'' into the ``Vocalizer 1000,'' and the notes
come out sounding like they were played on a piano, or a steel drum,
or one of 26 other instruments you select.
   If your ``do'' is a little sharp and your ``mi'' wavers, the
space-age circuitry makes the notes sound right. It even adds adrum
accompanyment.
   It may seem like a high-tech kazoo but the Vocalizer is more
sophisticated than that, said Darby Williams, who sells the item for
$300 and says even professional musicians are hooking the item up to
their synthsizers.
   His clarinet troubles of youth now far behind him (``I wasn't
much better at the guitar''), the 35-year-old Williams is president
of Breakaway Music Systems of San Mateo.
   Breakaway started selling the Vocalizer in the bible of fancy
gadget fans, the Sharper Image catalog, in November. Since then, it
has ``sold thousands on thousands of them,'' said Williams, who
added he wouldn't be more specific.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They missed a week of classes, but two high
school journalists who covered President Bush's inauguration say
they learned a valuable lesson about charm and persistence in the
nation's capital.
   Emmanuel Remy, 16, a reporter, and Jeremy Brilliant, 17, a
photographer, wrote to Republican officials in November to obtain
media credentials. They raised money for the trip from local
businesses and set out Jan. 16.
   But when they arrived in Washington, they learned inauguration
planners had overbooked journalists. No media passes would be issued
to students, they were told.
   Not taking ``no'' for an answer, Brilliant, a senior, headed for
the inauguration's news media headquarters, made small talk with
officials and obtained a single pass to several events. Remy decided
to visit the headquarters himself to try out his charm. It worked.
   ``The guy took me out into the hall and said, `I don't normally
do this ... I've turned down national media,''' said Remy, a junior.
``He gave me the passes and said, `Don't write anything bad. Now get
lost.'''
   Their week in Washington included meetings with Ohio congressmen
and Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., the opening celebration, several
inaugural balls and receptions, inauguration church services and the
inauguration itself.
   Their photos and stories, including an interview with Vice
President Dan Quayle's son Tucker, will appear in Friday's edition
of their high school's monthly news magazine, The Phoenix.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women whose beauty salons have been barred
from using traditional brush curlers are making a hair-raising noise
in the state Legislature, which is considering a bill to lift the
ban.
   ``This was the one thing we found during our campaign that people
were really opposed to,'' said Rep. Wilbur Vander Vorst.
   The state Board of Cosmetology issued its edict banning brush
curlers last July. The board contended the curlers, which are rather
like little round hairbrushes without handles, are unsanitary
because hair tends to stick in the bristles.
   But many women prefer them.
   Rep. Kathi Gilmore said the board should have sanctioned beauty
parlors whose brush rollers were found to have stray hairs on them,
rather than banning a vital tool of the trade. Gilmore, who is
sponsoring legislation to lift the prohibition, testified at a state
House committee hearing Wednesday.
   Legislators said they are being bombarded with calls about
Gilmore's bill. Gilmore said she had received more than 70, while
Sen. David O'Connell, reported getting more than 200.
   The committee took no immediate action on the legislation.
</TEXT>
