<FIRST>r a PM-TrainAccident     01-26 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Train Accident,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Killed As Two Freight Trains Strike Truck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FOSTORIA, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trucker apparently became confused at a
rail crossing and drove between two sets of tracks early today
before her rig was struck by a southbound freight train and then by
a northbound one, authorities said.
   A passenger in the tractor-trailer was killed, and a brakeman was
slightly injured.
   The truck driver escaped unhurt moments before the fiery
accident, sheriff's deputies said.
   ``I've got no explanation on why that woman drove 500 feet on our
railroad tracks, but that's literally what happened,'' CSX spokesman
Lloyd Lewis said.
   Sheriff Carl Runion said the truck driver, who may have confused
by the curve of the road, realized her mistake and apparently was
trying to back the rig onto the highway when a train clipped the cab
on one side about 5:30 a.m.
   Moments later, a train coming in the opposite direction struck
the back of the trailer. He said the rig, sandwiched between the
trains, was dragged along the tracks, spreading flames for several
hundred yards along the tracks.
   One freight car jumped the tracks, Lewis said.
   A woman, apparently sleeping in a bunk of the tractor cab, was
killed, authorities said. A CSX brakeman was treated at a hospital
and released.
   The names of the dead woman and the driver were not immediately
released.
   Lewis said the the engineer in the lead engine of the first train
reported the truck's headlights were off and were turned on after it
was too late for him to stop.
</TEXT>
