<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--Bakker-Trial     01-26 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Bakker-Trial,0142</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bakker, Dortch Ask For Delay of Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for former PTL leaders Jim Bakker
and Richard Dortch have filed motions seeking to have their clients'
trial postponed from next month's federal court session.
   In motions filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court in Charlotte,
the attorneys said they needed more time to prepare their case.
   Bakker, who resigned as PTL president in March 1987 following a
sex and money scandal, and Dortch, Bakker's top deputy at PTL, were
indicted Dec. 5 following a 16-month federal grand jury
investigation. The indictment accuses them of diverting more than $4
million in PTL funds for their personal use.
   Each was charged with 24 counts of mail fraud, wire fraud and
conspiracy to commit mail and wire fraud. Both have pleaded not
guilty to the charges.
</TEXT>
