<FIRST>u a AM-CulturalTax Bjt   01-26 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cultural Tax, Bjt,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cultural Tax Makes Denver Area One of Biggest Spenders on Culture</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The polar bears at the Denver Zoo helped sell
voters on a penny-per-$10 sales tax for cultural institutions that
is turning metro area residents into some of the nation's top
supporters of the arts and sciences.
   The ``polar bear tax'' _ so called because campaigners used a
drawing of a zoo bear to promote it, in order to defuse talk that
the arts are elitist _ sailed to victory in the Nov. 8 election with
75 percent of the vote in the six-county Denver region.
   The nine-member Cultural Arts District board, which will spend
the tax revenues, was selected this month and will soon send out its
first grants.
   Consultant Floyd Ciruli, who oversaw the campaign for the tax and
continues to advise the board, says the 0.1 percent sales tax is
unprecedented both in the amount of money it raises and the range of
organizations it helps.
   He hopes it will change Denver's sense of itself from ``cow
town'' to ``culture town'' and ensure a healthy financial future for
organizations that have seen their federal and city support sag in
this era of tight budgets.
   Every cultural organization in the area is eligible to receive
funds from the new tax, from mainstays like the symphony orchestra,
which last year had a brush with near-bankruptcy, to the most
esoteric dance and theater groups.
   The tax breaks down to a little more than $6 per person annually,
more than any other community pays per person in local tax money for
culture, according to Ciruli.
   Denver arts patrons got the idea for the tax from St. Louis,
where a property tax helps fund a few of the city's largest cultural
institutions. San Francisco draws from a lodging tax to help some of
its major facilities. But Denver's tax is drawn from the whole metro
area and finances many more institutions.
   Lawmakers rejected the idea of a culture tax in 1986 because of
squabbling in the arts community, said Greg Geissler, who heads the
city of Denver's Cultural Affairs Commission. Local arts and
government officials then hammered out the existing plan that offers
``something for everyone,'' he said. The Legislature endorsed it
last year, then the voters gave final approval in November.
   ``In the long run, the health of the large institutions is
directly tied to the overall health of the whole arts community,''
Geissler said.
   The largest chunk of tax revenues _ about $8.5 million _ is
earmarked for four big-budget institutions: the Natural History
Museum, the Denver Art Museum, the zoo and the Denver Botanic
Gardens.
   A second chunk _ about $3.3 million _ will go to midsize agencies
like the Denver Center for the Performing Arts, the Denver Symphony
Orchestra and the Denver Ballet.The remaining money, about 10
percent of the total, will go back to the six counties to be
distributed to small groups.
   There was little organized opposition to the cultural facilities
tax, but some critics said it taxed everybody to pay for ``elitist''
programs attended by the wealthy.
   To counter that criticism, backers turned to the popular zoo and
its polar bears, stressing that cultural facilities are used by a
wide variety of people and saying they help foster tourism.
Proponents said the alternative to the tax was high admission fees,
which price the poor out of supposedly public facilities.
   ``Cultural programming is becoming one of the best tourist and
economic development tools that you have,'' said Ciruli.
   ``There's no doubt that some of the funds _ a small part _ will
go to cultural styles that are enjoyed by very narrow groups of
people, but that's a tradeoff. ... There's a lot of diversity and
that's good.''
   Tom Peterson, the Denver Zoo's marketing director, said the zoo
will use its share of tax proceeds to expand education and
conservation programs and for projects such as renovation of a
display of grizzly and black bears. As for the polar bears, who
helped pass the tax: They already have new quarters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
