<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Ethics 1stLd-Writethru a0459 01-26 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Ethics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release 2:15 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Asks Executives To Help Him Set Good Example</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: First 10 grafs new with Bush speech, for release at 2:15 p.m.
EST. Picks up 4th graf pvs, In naming the, deleting pvs grafs 11-12, now
redundant.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today urged top federal
executives to help fulfill his quest for an administration beyond
ethical reproach, where government service is seen as ``a noble
calling.''
   ``There is a mandate to fulfill. And there are problems to
solve,'' Bush said in prepared remarks to some 3,700 top government
managers.
   Bush said the guiding principle of his policy will be ``simply to
know right from wrong. ... To avoid even the appearance of what is
wrong.''
   Bush began stressing ethics during the presidential campaign,
when the Reagan administration, in which he was vice president, came
under fire for what was dubbed the ``sleaze factor.'' More than 100
members of the Reagan administration at various times were accused
of unethical or improper behavior.
   Bush tried to neutralize that criticism by promising to make
creation of an ethics panel one his first acts as president.
   Continuing his emphasis on ethics, Bush made his first speech
outside the White House, going to the nearby Constitution Hall of
the Daughters of the American Revolution. There, he spoke to members
of the Senior Executive Service, comprised of top-level department
and agency managers, most of them career government employees.
   ``I pledge to try to make federal jobs more challenging, more
satisfying and more fulfilling,'' he said. ``I am dedicated to
making the system work and making it work better.''
   ``Our principles are clear _ that government service is a noble
calling and a public trust,'' Bush said.
   The president noted that he had appointed a commission Wednesday
to recommend new ethics reform proposals for all three branches of
government, indicating he wants to avoid the kinds of ethical
problems that often hounded the Reagan administration.
   Bush asked the eight-member advisory commission to come up with
recommendations for ethics legislation by March 9.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Embargoed Material</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   In naming the President's Commission on Federal Ethics Law
Reform, Bush said he wants a ``code of conduct to ensure that those
who serve the public trust avoid any actual or apparent conflict
between their personal and public interests.''
   The president said, however, the standards should not be so
``unreasonably restrictive'' that they dissuade capable people from
entering government.
   Last fall, President Reagan vetoed a congressional ethics
package, saying it was excessive and would hamper the government's
ability to attract top-rate people.
   Bush supported the veto, saying at the time that would put
together his own ethics reforms.
   ``Current federal ethics rules do not adequately serve to
eliminate use of public funds for private gains,'' Bush said
Wednesday.
   ``The current framework is fragmented, confusing and, most
important, it does not incorporate sufficient safeguards to protect
the public interest in an honest and fair government.''
   The panel is chaired by Griffin Bell, the former attorney general
in the Carter administration, and Malcolm Wilkey, a senior judge on
the U.S. Court of Appeals in Washington.
   Besides Bell and Wilkey, other panel members are former White
House counsels Fred Fielding and Lloyd Cutler, Washington attorney
Jan Baran who is counsel to the Republican National Committee,
former Rep. Harrison Schmitt of New Mexico, former counsel to the
Senate Armed Services Committee R. James Woolsey, and Judith Bello,
former counsel to the U.S. Trade Representative's office.
</TEXT>
