<FIRST>r w AM-ImportPrices     01-26 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Import Prices,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices of Imported Goods Resume Upward Trend After Brief Retreat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prices Americans pay for imported goods
resumed their upward trend in the final three months of 1988 to post
a 4.1 percent increase for the year, the government said Thursday.
   The Labor Department said import prices rose 1.6 percent from
October through December after falling 1.3 percent in the third
quarter. That had been their first decline in more than two years.
   The fourth-quarter increase was moderated by a drop in the cost
of crude oil and other imported fuels, which decreased 7.8 percent
after plunging 9.0 percent in the previous three months.
   From October through December, prices for imported crude
materials rose by 5.5 percent, imported machinery costs were up 2.5
percent, intermediate manufacturing products gained 2.4 percent and
chemical prices increased 2.3 percent.
   Removing the big drop in energy prices, all other imported goods
registered a 2.4 percent increase over the previous quarter.
   Last year's increase in import prices and a 10 percent rise
during the previous year were linked to the weakening of the U.S.
dollar, which fell in value by 2.6 percent in 1988 and 13.6 percent
in the previous year, according to a trade-weighted index used by
the Labor Department.
   The fall of the dollar, while improving the price competitiveness
of U.S. goods overseas and helping to lower the U.S. trade deficit,
also has the effect of boosting the prices of foreign goods bought
in the United States.
   The higher import costs affect inflation of consumer prices
overall, which rose 4.4 percent in 1988 and by a like margin during
the previous year.
   The price of U.S. exports, meanwhile, fell 0.2 percent during the
fourth quarter but still stood 6.3 percent higher than a year
earlier.
   The biggest decrease in export prices in the fourth quarter
occurred in the food category, which dropped 3.8 percent after
shooting up 14.8 percent in the previous quarter due to the summer
drought.
</TEXT>
