<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--EngineFire 1stLd-Writethru a0562 01-26 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Engine Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0562,0146</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Flight Lands Safely After Indicator Warns of Engine Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with FAA saying no fire occurred. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Airlines jet with 97 people aboard
made an emergency landing at O'Hare International Airport today
after an indicator light falsely warned of an engine fire, officials
said. No one was injured.
   The twin-engine McDonnell Douglas Super-80 en route to Chicago
from Indianapolis reported the emergency 53 miles from Chicago, the
airline said.
   Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Mort Edelstein said the
light came on after a ``blown duct pump'' forced hot air into the
engine compartment, activating fire warnings and prompting the pilot
to set off fire extinguishers.
   The emergency light then went out, said American spokesman Tom
Stack.
   The Super-80 is a longer version of the DC-9, said American
spokeswoman Mary O'Neill.
