<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     01-26 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Korean President Refuses to Testify</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Chun Doo-hwan on
Thursday defied the National Assembly, refusing to testify on his
role in the army's suppression of an uprising in 1980.
   About 500 radical students from several Seoul colleges clashed
with riot police Thursday at Dongguk University to demand the arrest
of Chun and President Roh Tae-woo, a former ally who has distanced
him from Chun. Radicals hurled hundreds of firebombs and rocks at
police surrounding the school.
   No serious injuries or arrests were reported.
   Officials took the order issued by the National Assembly to the
remote east coast Buddhist temple where Chun is living, but the
former president refused it, risking prosecution.
   Instead, he issued a statement accepting moral responsibility for
the civilian uprising in Kwangju.
   ``I think I was in a position to take moral and political
responsibility (for Kwangju), so I have no intention to avoid
responsibility,'' Chun said.
   He has said he will answer questions from lawmakers without
appearing, and Thursday he said he would testify ``indirectly.''
   Chun has denied any personal wrongdoing. However, he went into
rural exile after surrendering assets worth $24 million and
apologizing to the nation last November for abuses during his
administration. Several members of the ex-president's family have
been arrested or convicted on corruption charges.
   Former President Choi Kyu-ha, who briefly held office as a
figurehead before Chun took power with military backing in 1980,
also refused to accept an order to testify after officials took it
to his Seoul home.
   By official count, about 200 people were killed and more than
1,000 injured when the army put down the uprising in Kwangju.
Opposition groups claim the casualty toll was much higher, and the
uprising remains a highly emotional and controversial issue.
   Chun, a former general, was in control of the armed forces at the
time and took power of the government a few months later.
   The orders to testify were issued after a special Assembly
committee investigating the uprising resumed hearings in Seoul. The
Assembly is investigating allegations of widespread human rights
abuses and corruption under Chun.
   Both former presidents said previously that, as former heads of
state, they cannot compelled to testify. Roh has backed Chun's
refusal to testify.
   Under Korean law, the parliamentary committee has the power to
refer the case to prosecutors for legal action. But they must then
decide whether to act.
   The opposition is not expected to press immediately for Chun's
prosecution because keeping the issue alive furthers its political
aims.
   If convicted, the former presidents could be sentenced to up to
five years in prison.
   Chun is also being pressed to testify before another
parliamentary committee investigating corruption and other misdeeds.
Chun stepped down in February after a seven-year term and was
replaced by Roh, who won presidential elections in December 1987.
   The opposition is trying to use the Kwangju incident and other
legacies of the authoritarian Chun government to weaken the Roh
government. Roh is still identified with Chun in the eyes of many
Koreans.
   Opposition parties demanded this week that Roh keep an election
promise to submit to a referendum on his administration.
</TEXT>
