<FIRST>u w PM-Lujan     01-26 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lujan,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interior Nominee Says FDR is His Model, Stewardship His Job</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary-designate Manuel Lujan Jr.
said today that the words of Franklin Delano Roosevelt _ ``The
country will not be a good place to live in unless it is a good
place for all of us to live in'' _ will motivate his actions if he
is confirmed.
   At a confirmation hearing before the Senate Energy and Natural
Resources Committee, Lujan said he sees the job as one of
``stewardship,'' and said he hopes to enlist thousands of volunteers
as helpers in the national park and fish and wildlife systems.
   ``We want to be known as a team who passed on these national
treasures in better condition than we found them,'' he said.
   A native of New Mexico, Lujan grew up on lands that are now an
Indian reservation. As interior secretary he would oversee the
Bureau of Indian Affairs and, in response to a question, said he
would become personally involved if he heard of any Native Americans
being treated insensitively.
   Lujan outlined several specific points he called his agenda for
the Interior Department position.
   ``I will be an aggressive soldier on the war on drugs,'' he said.
He also said he has plans to provide work study and stay-in-school
programs for employees of the department.
   Lujan, 60, served in the House 20 years before retiring last
year. From 1981 to 1985, he was the ranking Republican on the House
Interior Committee and was mentioned twice in the past as a possible
choice for interior secretary.
   The full Senate plans to vote on Lujan's nomination next
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
