<FIRST>r a AM-HomelessVigil     01-26 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless Vigil,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man's Vigil Atop St. Paul Water Fountain Ends After Nearly 43 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A house painter ended his lonely vigil
atop a 20-foot-high downtown water fountain after 42{ days and after
raising less than $1,000 for the homeless, far short of his goal of
$1 million.
   But David Oferosky said Wednesday it was worth the effort.
   ``I'm proud of what I did, and I would do it again,'' he said.
   Oferosky, 34, began his vigil at 11:20 p.m. Dec. 13, scrambling
up a ladder to his campsite atop the concrete fountain and into a
tan tent pitched on a plywood floor.
   A portable toilet stood outside the tent, next to a propane flame
that Oferosky said symbolized his vigil and a bare evergreen tree
that was his only Christmas decoration.
   Inside, he had a cot, sleeping bag, kerosene lamp and small
propane heater, which he said he used only occasionally.
   A cellular telephone kept him in contact with the outside world.
For entertainment, he had a television that eventually burned out, a
radio, books and magazines and a mini-trampoline.
   Oferosky said he suffered chills some nights and the pain of an
abscessed tooth, but mostly he fought boredom and loneliness.
   ``You do have a lot of time to think, believe me,'' he said.
``It's like, `This is it, your coffee's not gonna get no hotter.
You've read that book? Read it again!' I never thought of giving
up.''
   Pas  ``It was bad when the gangs were shooting each other, but when
they start attacking innoncent people, it's time for people to do
something,'' said DeLen McRae, 44, an associate minister at St.
James' Baptist Church in Norwalk.
   The McRaes and their 17-year-old son were in back bedrooms of the
apartment, and no injuries were reported. But bullets pierced
windows, walls, furniture and even McRae's clergy robe, which was
hanging in a doorway.
   The incident remained under investigation.
</TEXT>
