<DOCNO> AP890126-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1522EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Irish-TV     01-26 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish-TV,0730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inquiry Largely Clears Controversial TV Film on Shootings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Filmmakers who outraged the government with their
TV documentary on the shooting of three unarmed Irish guerrilla
suspects were cleared Thursday by an inquiry into allegations of
unscrupulous journalism.
   The inquiry found the documentary flawed on two counts, but
concluded the filmmakers fully satisfied ``the requirements of
balance, fairness and impartiality.''
   The government said it continued to believe the documentary
contained ``many serious and damaging inaccuracies,'' and in a
demonstration of its displeasure took the unusual step of publishing
the points it made behind closed doors to the inquiry.
   John Wakeham, majority leader in Parliament, noted that an
inquest had ruled the killings were lawful, and said of the
inquiry's report: ``The government profoundly disagrees with it.''
   ``Death on the Rock'' was broadcast seven weeks after the
shooting of the unarmed suspects by a British anti-terrorist squad
last March in Gibraltar, and provoked uproar by strongly suggesting
that Mairead Farrell, Sean Savage and Daniel McCann were gunned down
without getting a chance to surrender.
   The government said the three were planting a car bomb in the
British colony, and the Irish Republican Army acknowledged that the
two men and one woman were in Gibraltar ``on active service.''
   But the fact that they were unarmed, and that no car bomb turned
up, provoked alarm that the security forces were taking too much
latitude in the struggle against IRA terrorism.
   The Foreign Office appealed to the Independent Broadcasting
Authority, which governs commercial TV, to suppress the documentary
as prejudicial to the inquest. Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
publicly denounced it, saying: ``If ever you get trial by television
or guilt by accusation, that day freedom dies.''
   Since then, Amnesty International has demanded a judicial inquiry
into the killings and civil libertarians said the attack on the film
is part of a broader government assault on media freedom.
   When Kenneth Asquez, the source of one of the film's most
provocative claims retracted his story under questioning at the
inquest, filmmaker Thames Television initiated the inquiry by Lord
Windlesham and senior attorney Richard Rampton.
   Windlesham is a former member of Mrs. Thatcher's Conservative
Party government and Rampton specializes in defamation law. Thames
said they were ``independent assessors'' with impeccable credentials
that have not been challenged from any quarter during their
four-month inquiry.
   Asquez, a Gibraltar bank clerk, claimed he was bullied and
offered money for a statement that he saw a security man standing
over McCann's body pumping bullets into his head.
   The investigators said viewers should have been told Asquez's
statement was unfilmed and unsigned. But they did not fault its
inclusion in the documentary and said the journalists ``did not
bribe, bully or misrepresent'' witnesses.
   The other criticism was of an ``inappropriately worded'' line of
commentary that the inquiry did not believe ``arose from any lack of
scrupulousness.'' The film said four witnesses saw the squad fire
without warning, whereas one witness was not in a position to see.
It had four witnesses saying the suspects made no sudden movements,
whereas two were not in a position to know that.
   The inquiry rejected about 20 other allegations, such as that the
filmmakers knowingly broadcast falsehoods, had preconceived
theories, sympathized with the IRA and wanted to pin a murder charge
on the British unit.
   The government called it ``irresponsible to the point of
dishonesty'' to include Asquez's story in the film, and pointed to
other contradictions between the film's narrative and evidence heard
at the inquest.
   The film said the suspects were under surveillance before
entering Gibraltar, and that Savage's car could have been stopped at
the border, said the government. The inquest heard otherwise.
   A witness told the filmmakers she saw plainclothed men jump from
a police car and shoot two suspects. The inquest heard the car
arrived after the shooting and contained uniformed policemen.
   A government statement said the reporters ``failed to pursue the
truth, to clarify the facts or to present evidence impartially.''
   The inquiry upheld the government's right ``to make the strongest
possible representations'' against programs deemed ``harmful to the
public interest.''
   But the broadcasting authority, ``must be prepared to withstand
pressure, however fierce and whatever the source,'' it said.
</TEXT>
