<FIRST>r i AM-Gulf-US     01-26 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gulf-US,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Admiral Who Led Vincennes Probe to Command U.S. Gulf Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The admiral who led the official
investigation into last year's downing of an Iranian jetliner by a
U.S. Navy cruiser has been chosen as the next commander of the
American naval force in the Persian Gulf.
   Pentagon officials said this week Rear Adm. William M. Fogarty
will probably assume command of the Joint Task Force Middle East in
March. He will replace Rear Adm. Anthony A. Less, who will join the
plans, policy and operations staff of the Chief of Naval Operations.
   The force includes 24 warships _ 14 in the gulf and a 10-ship
aircraft carrier battle group in the Arabian Sea.
   The appointment is the second top-level command shuffle in recent
months.
   In November, Army Gen. H. Norman Schwarzkopf succeeded retiring
Marine Gen. George B. Crist at U.S. Central Command in Tampa, Fla.
   Central Command is the administrative headquarters for U.S.
military affairs in 19 countries of the Middle East, including the
gulf region.
   Schwarzkopf is currently on a tour of the region. He conferred
Wednesday with senior government officials and Bahrain and also
planned to meet with the emir, Sheik Isa Bin Salman Al Khalifa.
   Fogarty, 51, a surface warfare officer, is director of plans and
policy at Central Command.
   He headed the team of experts that investigated the shooting down
of an Iran Air jet July 3 by the missile cruiser USS Vincennes in
the Strait of Hormuz.
   All 290 people aboard were killed when the warship destroyed the
jetliner in the belief it was an Iranian jet fighter.
   Fogarty's inquiry found the stress of first-time combat caused
some Vincennes crew members to misinterpret radar data on the jet.
   The gulf-based force was recently cut from 15 to 14 ships in a
move that U.S. officials said reflected a lowering of tension since
Iraq and Iran since they signed a cease-fire in August in their
8-year-old war.
   The United States has maintained a permanent naval force in the
Persian Gulf since 1949, but it was expanded in 1987 to protect
U.S.-flag shipping.
   Navy ships now only monitor U.S.-flag vessels from a distance,
and six of 11 Kuwaiti tankers that have sailed under the Stars and
Stripes since mid-1987 will soon revert to Kuwaiti registry.
</TEXT>
