<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1549EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CaesareanSections     01-26 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Caesarean Sections,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>C-Section Rate Leveling Off</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One in four American women gives birth by
Caesarean section, and that rate appears to be leveling off after
years of sharp increases, a public interest group said Thursday.
   However, the Public Citizen Health Research Group estimated that
more than half of the abdominal operations are unnecessary and that
women should be encouraged more actively to deliver naturally.
   The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists agreed
that the C-section rate appears to be leveling off, but the
professional organization rejected the report's claim that doctors
are abusing the procedure.
   The group's report analyzed data from 40 states and the District
of Columbia and found the rate of C-section births rose 0.3 percent
_ from 24.1 percent to 24.4 percent of all births _ from 1986 to
1987.
   The increase was the smallest annual rise in 12 years in a rate
that has more than quadrupled since 1970, when 5.5 percent of all
births were C-sections.
   ``It looks like this is for real, and it's long overdue,'' said
Dr. Sidney M. Wolfe, co-author of the report.
   Dr. Lynn Silver, the other author, said the change is due to
attention focused on the issue and women who are ``starting to ask
the right questions about this procedure.''
   The group said nearly 51 percent of the 934,000 surgical
procedures commonly called C-sections performed in 1987 nationwide
were unnecessary
   Silver said that cost the nation more than $1 billion in health
care costs and put thousands of women at higher risk needlessly,
Silver said.
   The report identified two hospitals where half or more of the
babies born in 1987 were delivered by C-section: Hialeah
Hospital-Dade in Florida, 53.1 percent of its 2,239 births, and
Montgomery County Memorial Hospital in Iowa, 50 percent of its 56
births.
   Wolfe said doctors and hospitals have an incentive to perform
C-sections because they make more money on the procedure, which is
more complicated than natural delivery and requires a longer
hospital stay for the mother. He also said doctors like the
convenience of scheduling a birth during working hours.
   The report found that private, for-profit hospitals had a higher
C-section rate, averaging 24 percent, and military and public health
service hospitals had the lowest, averaging 15 percent.
   The report estimates that the optimal average U.S. C-section rate
is about 12 percent. The figure is based on an estimate of Dr. E.J.
Quilligan, dean of the School of Medicine at the University of
California at Irvine. The estimate also is based on data from other
countries and U.S. hospitals that have tried to stop unnecessary
surgery, as well as clinical trials examining the usefulness of
C-sections for women, the report said.
   The group's estimate of unnecessary C-sections was derived by
comparing the 12 percent target rate with the actual rate.
   But Morton Lebow, a spokesman for the American College of
Obstetricians and Gynecologists, maintained that the report provides
``no reliable data to establish a correct rate for C-sections.''
   He said his group is ``concerned about the rate of C-sections''
and he noted the organization last fall strengthened its guidelines
recommending that pregnant women who previously gave birth by
C-section deliver vaginally if there is no medical reason not to.
   The report recommends that states require disclosure to maternity
patients of C-section rates for all doctors and hospitals in their
area and second opinions for C-sections that are not emergencies.
   It also says doctors should use more fetal tests to reduce the
number of false diagnoses of fetal distress, which often lead to
unnecessary C-sections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
