<DOCNO> AP890126-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1552EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     01-26 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa to Meet Interior Minister to Prepare for Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and the
interior minister will start preparatory negotiations Friday for
upcoming talks on the future of the banned union, a Solidarity
spokesman said.
   A statement released by Solidarity national spokesman Janusz
Onyszkiewicz on Thursday said Walesa will chair the Solidarity
delegation, but did not indicate who else from the union would
participate in the talks.
   Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak was the only government
official the Solidarity statement said would attend the talks. A
government spokesman declined to provide the names of any other
potential participants.
   Earlier Thursday, Foreign Ministry spokesman Stefan Staniszewski
said the long-awaited talks between the government and opposition
``should begin in the nearest days.''
   In response to question whether the talks would begin Feb. 5,
Staniszewski said, ``It is a very probable date.'' But he said since
that date falls on a Sunday, the talks could possibly also begin
Feb. 6.
   The talks are expected to address a broad range of issues,
including trade union, political and economic freedoms.
   Walesa arrived by train in Warsaw from his home city of Gdansk on
Thursday, said Jacek Ambroziak, a lawyer for the Roman Catholic
Episcopate.
   The Solidarity leader met with senior advisers of the banned
union, including Andrzej Stelmachowski, a lawyer who has been active
in arranging talks between Walesa and the authorities in the past.
   Stelmachowski declined to provide any details on the talks. Other
top Solidarity advisers were being cautious in discussing Walesa's
plans.
   Walesa eluded a group of journalists when he departed from his
usual practice of getting off the express from Gdansk at Warsaw
Central station and got out earlier at a station in the outskirts of
the city.
   The Solidarity statement said Walesa planned to hold a news
conference Saturday.
   The government first proposed the talks during a wave of strikes
in August, the country's worst labor unrest since the government
imposed martial on Dec. 13, 1981.
   Since August, Walesa has traveled to Warsaw four times for
discussions about the proposal with senior government officials
since August. But the Solidarity leader said he would not hold talks
on Poland's future until the authorities decided to legalize the
banned union.
   In a dramatic reversal of policy last week, the Communist Party
Central Committee approved an offer to allow more than one legal
trade union to exist and participation by the opposition in
government bodies.
   The Solidarity leadership on Sunday agreed to hold negotiations
with the government on legalizing the union.
   Deputy Prime Minister Ireneusz Sekula, explaining the party's
about-face on Solidarity in an interview with the state-run news
agency PAP, said only compromise could lift the people and economy
from the current state of apathy.
</TEXT>
