<FIRST>u a AM-Anti-Semitism Bjt   01-26 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Anti-Semitism, Bjt,0786</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Semitic Acts Rise to 5-Year High, ADL Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of anti-Semitic incidents rose to a
five-year high in 1988, with reports of harassment incidents up 41
percent and vandalism up 19 percent, a Jewish group said Thursday.
   Abraham Foxman, national director of the Anti-Defamation League
of B'nai B'rith, said he could not point to a single factor for the
increase, but said there were ``stimulants'' such as neo-Nazi
skinheads, the 50th anniversary of the start of the Holocaust and
developments in the Middle East.
   ``Isn't it ironic that in our lifetime we've conquered space and
even eradicated smallpox,'' Foxman said, ``yet we have not developed
a vaccine against the virus of hate.''
   An ADL survey released here included nearly 1,300 incidents
reported by law enforcement authorities in 40 states, the District
of Columbia and Puerto Rico. There were no incidents reported in 10
states, said ADL spokesman Richard Klein.
   New York led the nation with 208 incidents, half of those in New
York City. California had 121, Florida 89 and New Jersey 67.
   ``We may never be able to completely eradicate mindless bigotry
or the violence of hate,'' U.S. Attorney General Richard Thornburgh
wrote in a forward to the ADL survey. But ``we can pursue swift and
sure prosecution of these crimes against the American dream.''
   The number of anti-Semitic harassment incidents, such things as
threats and assaults, totaled 458 in 1988, up 41 percent from 324 in
1987.
   Of those, 325 were against Jewish individuals, including 21
physical assaults.The report cited a November attack against a
Yeshiva University student in New York City as being among the most
brutal. A gang of youths allegedly shouted anti-Semitic epithets as
they beat, robbed and stabbed the 19-year-old, who survived.
   It was a record year for harassment incidents against Jewish
institutions in the 10 years the survey has been taken. Threats and
other harassment incidents against institutions were reported in 133
cases, up about 10 percent from previous years, the group said.
   In the category of vandalism against individuals and
institutions, there were a total of 823 incidents reported in 1988,
up from 694 the previous year. Most of those were anti-Semitic
graffiti and cemetery desecrations, but there were more serious
incidents, such as a pipe bomb exploding inside a Florida synagogue
and an arson fire that destroyed a Brooklyn synagogue in September.
   An unusually large number of vandalism incidents were reported in
the South _ 172 cases in 12 states, up from 115 in 1987 _ where
there are mostly smaller Jewish populations, the report said.
   Geographically, the Northeast had the greatest number of
incidents _ 411 in 11 states and the District of Columbia _ while
the West was the only region to report a decrease. Figures there
dropped 7 percent from 157 incident to 146 in six states. Incidents
in the Midwest rose slightly from 85 in 1987 to 92 in 1988.
   Other disturbing statistics showed that of the 124 people
arrested for anti-Semitic acts in 1988, approximately 90 percent
were under 21.
   Foxman said the 1988 survey makes it clear ``We have a long way
to go and still have much to do.''
   He called for continued efforts by law enforcement authorities to
apprehend those who practice hate crimes, better anti-bias education
programs for youths in schools, churches and after-school programs
and strict enforcement of anti-bias legislation, which is now in
effect in 43 states.
   As for the cause of the increase in bias incident reports, Foxman
said, ``We cannot so easily say this is the cause and this is the
effect.'' But he noted some specific ``stimulants,'' including:
   _The uprising by Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza, which
began in late 1987. Foxman said he believes anti-Semites used the
situation to carry out acts of hatred ``under the guise of a
political conflict.'' There were 117 incidents were linked to the
uprising.
   _A proliferation of neo-Nazi Skinhead gangs, who preach violence
and hatred against blacks, Hispanics, Jews, Asians and homosexuals.
They were said to be responsible for 41 anti-Semitic incidents last
year.
   _Publicity marking the 50th anniversary of Kristallnacht in
Germany, believed by many to have been the start of the Nazi
Holocaust. More than 60 anti-Semitic incidents were reported during
the weeklong observation in November.
   The report said there was a significant increase in the number of
American colleges reporting anti-Semitic incidents _ from 14
campuses in 1987 to 38 campuses in 1988. The 54 incidents at the 38
schools included vandalism, threats, harassment and assault.
</TEXT>
