<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     01-26 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Urges Pressure on Iraq for Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran on Thursday warned of ``dangers''
threatening regional peace from within Iraq and asked a U.N. envoy
to pressure Baghdad to stick to terms of the cease-fire in the
Persian Gulf War.
   Iranian Prime Minister Hussein Musavi told visiting U.N. envoy
Jan Eliasson that Iran ``will spare no effort'' to secure a
permanent peace treaty with Iraq, according to the official Islamic
Republic News Agency monitored in Nicosia.
   Eliasson, U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar's
special emissary, arrived in Tehran on Monday seeking to breathe new
life into peace talks broken off Nov. 11. The talks followed a
cease-fire agreed to by both sides on Aug. 20 after eight years of
war that left an estimated 1 million people dead.
   The U.N. envoy was scheduled to visit Baghdad on Friday to meet
senior leaders and seek ways of fully putting into effect the U.N.
Security Council's cease-fire resolution.
   Iraqi Information Minister Latif Nussayif Jasim said Wednesday
that ``any spark'' on the tense border, where both sides still have
large numbers of troops, could trigger new hostilities.
   President Saddam Hussein of Iraq alleged earlier this month that
Iran was massing troops along the 730-mile border between the two
countries.
   U.N. military observers say the cease-fire is holding, despite
clais of violations by both sides. But the stalemate in peace talks
appears to have hardened.
   The Iranian news agency quoted Musavi as saying, ``We are
concerned about dangers threatening the accomplishment of peace from
inside Iraq and believe that an international effort is needed to
make the Baghdad regime understand that it should respect
international agreements for the cause of peace.''
   The report did not elaborate on the alleged threat.
   Musavi stressed Iraq still occupies about 260 square miles of
Iranian border territory and refuses to withdraw its troops, the
agency said.
   ``How can we believe that Iraq will abide by the articles of the
(U.N.) resolution while part of our country is still under
occupation?'' he was quoted as saying.
   The agency quoted Eliasson as saying, ``We expect both sides to
pave the way for peace by taking positive steps.''
</TEXT>
