<FIRST>r i AM-Honduras     01-26 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Patrols, State of Alert After General's Assassination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavily armed police and soldiers
patrolled the country Thursday in a crackdown on ``subversive
activity'' a day after the assassination of the former armed forces
chief.
   Gen. Gustavo Adolfo Alvarez Martinez, who allowed Contra rebels
from Nicaragua to use Honduran territory to stage operations, was
killed by six gunmen as he sat in his car Wednesday, officials said.
His chauffeur was also killed, and his son-in-law was wounded.
   ``We have increased security measures to protect citizens and
stop the increase of subversive activity in our country,'' National
Police chief Col. Leonel Riera Lunatti said Thursday.
   Military sources said an alert was declared Wednesday after a
meeting of the National Security Council with President Jose Azcona
Hoyo. On Thursday, leaders ordered stricter security measures,
including searches of vehicles and residents, the sources said.
   The leftist Popular Liberation Movement said in a communique that
one of its units carried out the attack on the former head of the
armed forces. But police said they had no evidence to confirm the
claim.
   Alvarez, 56, had supervised a counterinsurgency campaign against
suspected Honduran guerrillas.
   Top-level military officials said they fear leftist guerrillas
had begun a clandestine operation aimed at killing top military
officials. Government forces on Thursday closely guarded homes of
high officials, said a military official on condition of anonymity.
   Guards at military bases have been reinforced and dogs trained in
bomb detection have been deployed, the official said.
   Alvarez, who headed the national police in 1981 and supervised
the armed forces from 1982 to 1984, once was considered the most
powerful man in Honduras. He was overthrown by officials led by Gen.
Walter Lopez Reyes, who accused him of corruption and abuse of power.
   The local Human Rights Commission accused Alvarez of ordering the
political killings of hundreds of people, but the armed forces deny
the accusations.
   Alvarez also presided over the beginning of joint U.S.-Honduran
military exercises in Honduras that were designed to intimidate the
rulers of neighboring Nicaragua.
   He played a key role in supporting Contra rebels by telling late
CIA director William Casey that they could operate from Honduran
territory. They used their Honduran bases to attack Nicaragua's
leftist government.
   On Jan. 7, Nicaraguan rebel military commander Manuel Adan Rugama
Acevedo was fatally shot just outside the capital.
   On Monday, two gunmen killed Carlos Diaz Lorenzana, a lawyer for
reputed drug baron Juan Ramon Matta. His extradition to the United
States last year led to riots and a state of emergency.
</TEXT>
