<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1604EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Pope-Lithuania     01-26 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Lithuania,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cardinal Says Soviet Union Still Opposes Papal Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist authorities in the Soviet republic of
Lithuania would welcome a visit to the Roman Catholic stronghold by
Pope John Paul II but Moscow continues to oppose the idea,
Lithuania's cardinal said Thursday.
   Cardinal Vincentas Sladkevicius, in Rome for talks with the pope,
said he raised the issue of a papal visit in a meeting this week in
Moscow with an official in the government's council for religious
affairs.
   ``At this time, the government of Moscow is very much against a
visit of the pope,'' the 68-year-old cardinal said in an interview
with The Associated Press.
   He said Sergei Kuznetsov, head of the Soviet department on
Catholic affairs, ``answered with an objection, saying, `Why isn't
the Vatican taking steps to meet the East's desires? Why isn't the
pope taking steps to improve relations?'''
   Sladkevicius said the Kremlin position differed from that of
Lithuania's Communist Party chief, Algirdas Brazauskas, who
indicated at a recent meeting in Kaisiadorys that the local
government was very much in favor of a papal visit.
   The cardinal said the Lithuanian government is ``still very
dependent on Moscow'' and could not clear the way for a papal visit
on its own.
   The Polish-born pontiff frequently has expressed the desire to
travel to the Soviet Union but insisted he would go only if
permitted to visit his flock throughout the country.
   He has said that at least on two occasions he has been refused
permission to visit Lithuania.
   Lithuania, an independent country before World War II, was
occupied by the Soviet Union in 1940 and has been viewed as a
stronghold of nationalism. Sladkevicius said about 80 percent of
Lithuania's 3.5 million people are Roman Catholics.
   Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev is scheduled to make an
official visit to Rome in November, and the Vatican has said the
pope is open to a meeting with him. Such a meeting has been
portrayed as a possible prelude to the first ever visit by a pope to
the Soviet Union.
   Sladkevicius, who was confined to virtual house arrest from 1959
until 1982, was elevated to cardinal in June by the pope. He said
the situation of the Catholic church in Lithuania had improved under
Gorbachev but that Catholics ``are still second-class citizens.''
   ``If the natural desire for independence becomes realized, then
... religious problems will resolve themselves,'' he said, speaking
slowly in English in the interview in a tiny hotel room.
   On the positive side, he said the Soviet government recently
decided to allow Bishop Juliajonas Steponavicius to resume his
official duties as apostolic administrator of Vilnius after nearly
28 years of internal exile.
   Sladkevicius said the government on Feb. 5 will return the
Vilnius Cathedral, which was converted into a state art gallery in
1950, to the church. On the same day, a Catholic magazine,
Believers' World, will start up in Vilnius.
   St. Casimir's Church, which has been a museum since 1962, will be
returned to the church in March, he said.
   ``We are evaluating the changes. They are very good but we are
not certain about the future,'' said Sladkevicius.
   ``The nation was faithful to its Catholic faith but only part of
the nation could practice openly. Now the obstacles have been
removed,'' he said.
   Sladkevicius is one of two cardinals in the Soviet Union.
Julijans Vaivods of Latvia was elevated by John Paul in 1983.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
