<FIRST>u i AM-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru a0602 01-26 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0602,0767</SECOND>
<HEAD>Speculation Increases Two British Hostages to be Freed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Ramsay return, embassy saying
no news; Picks up 4th graf pvs, ``The reports...''; Restores dropped word
in 17th graf, ``Foreign Minister ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radio and press reports Thursday said the
release of two British hostages might be imminent, and British
Ambassador Allan Ramsay crossed into Moslem West Beirut.
   After Ramsay's return to the British Embassy, in the Christian
sector of the divided capital, an embassy official said, ``We have
no additional information.''
   Asked whether a hostage release was expected, he said, ``All I
can tell you is that we're not on alert.'' The official spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Earlier, when asked by telephone if his trip was linked to the
press reports, Ramsay said from the British consular office in the
Moslem sector: ``I often come to west Beirut and there's nothing
significant in my current visit.''
   An embassy spokesman had said the purpose of Ramsay's journey was
to check the reports.
   The British Embassy and Ramsay's residence are in east Beirut.
Most hostages are believed held in west Beirut's Shiite Moslem slums.
   The reports said kidnapped British journalist John McCarthy and
teacher Brian Keenan, who has Irish and British citizenship, could
be freed within days.
   Patrick McCabe, who is Ireland's ambassador to Lebanon but is
based in Iraq, said he would fly to Beirut immediately to
investigate.
   McCarthy and Keenan are among 15 foreigners missing in Lebanon,
who include two more Britons and nine Americans. Held longest is
Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated
Press, who was abducted March 16, 1985.
   One of the other Britons is Terry Waite, a Church of England
envoy who disappeared Jan. 20, 1987, after leaving his west Beirut
hotel to negotiate with people holding American hostages.
   Most of the foreigners are believed to be captives of Shiite
extremists loyal to Iran, but no faction has claimed to hold Waite
or McCarthy and Keenan, who were seized in April 1986.
   Reports of the possible release came from the Voice of Lebanon, a
Christian radio station, and Al-Hayat, an Arabic-language newspaper
published in London. The paper spoke of ``discussions under way
between Iran and countries involved'' about freeing Keenan and
McCarthy.
   Ramsay said in the telephone interview none of the reports or
attendant rumors ``can be verified. ... I'm anxious to avoid
speculation on that subject.''
   Earlier, the embassy spokesman said: ``We have heard a report and
we're making enquiries.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   McCarthy, 31, a producer for London-based Worldwide Television
news, was kidnapped April 17, 1986, as he drove to the airport to
catch a flight home. Keenan, 38, of Belfast, Northern Ireland, an
English language teacher at the American University of Beirut, was
seized six days earlier in west Beirut.
   McCabe, the Irish ambassador, said he was visiting Lebanon ``to
investigate a rumor'' circulated Wednesday in Baghdad that the two
men would be freed within 72 hours, but that he had no specific
information.
   ``Is there something hard behind the rumor?'' he said. ``I don't
know. ... I am always skeptical about the rumor-mill in Beirut.''
   Sources in Belfast said privately the British Foreign Office told
Keenan's family there were hopes for ``good news'' soon. His two
sisters were said to be planning a trip to Beirut.
   Foreign Minister Brian Lenihan of Ireland met with his Iranian
counterpart Ali Akbar Velayati in Paris this month during an
international conference. Declan Connolly, who is Irish ambassador
to Syria from his base in Saudi Arabia, met with the Syrian foreign
minister, Farouk al-Sharaa, on Wednesday in Damascus.
   On Thursday, Connolly said he had heard the hostage reports but
was in Syria on a routine visit.
   Syria has about 40,000 soldiers stationed in Lebanon and is the
country's main power broker. It also supported Iran in the war with
Iraq, in which a cease-fire was reached in August.
   Relations have improved between Britain and Iran, which restored
full diplomatic relations in November after a break of 17 months.
Nicholas Nicola, a 23-year-old Briton held in Iran for two years
after a shooting incident, was freed earlier this month.
   Iran's official news agency quoted Interior Minister Ali Akbar
Mohatashami on Thursday, however, as saying British businessman
Roger Cooper would be punished according to Islamic law. Cooper has
been in jail since 1986 on espionage charges.
</TEXT>
