<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Taba     01-26 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Taba,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egypt Reported to Back Away From Declaring Sovereignty in Beach Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli official said Egypt backed away from
a demand to take control Sunday over a disputed beachfront after
Israel warned that such a move would jeopardize talks on the strip.
   The director-general of Israel's Foreign Ministry, Reuven Merhav,
told Israel Radio that Egypt reconsidered its demand to take control
of the area, known as Taba, this weekend because of pressure from
Israel and the United States. Washington is mediating the talks.
   Israel has insisted that decisions about access for Israeli
tourists and ownership of a luxury hotel and resort village at Taba
be decided with the transfer issue. The resorts are now owned by
Israelis.
   ``The order that was to be published Sunday (by Egypt) will
apparently be changed,'' Merhav said. ``We relayed a message to the
Egyptians that a step like this would disrupt the negotiations.''
   Taba, a 250-acre beach area on the Red Sea, has been a subject of
dispute since Israel refused to hand it back to Egypt in 1982. At
that time, Israel withdrew from the rest of the Sinai Peninsula
under terms of the Israel-Egyptian peace treaty.
   Last November, an international arbitration panel delineated the
border, putting Taba in Egyptian territory. But the panel was not
empowered to decide the final boundary line, which Egypt and Israel
were to work out in their own talks.
   Nabil Araby, Egypt's chief negotiator on Taba, on Wednesday said
the land should be returned to Egypt on Sunday, since Israel and
Egypt agreed to adhere to the arbitration ruling 60 days after it
was handed down.
   But Israel Radio said Egypt had backed away from its demand
because of Israeli concern the move would give the Egyptian Tourism
Ministry broad ownership rights over the hotel before the question
of ownership was settled.
   Instead, Israel Radio said, Egypt plans to issue an order
authorizing the Tourism Ministry to negotiate for the hotel's
purchase.
</TEXT>
