<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-US     01-26 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guards Shut out Local Mayor From U.S. Military Housing Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guards on Thursday kept an inspection team from
entering the construction site of a controversial U.S. military
housing project that local officials have been fighting, a city
official said.
   Mayor Kiichiro Tomino of Zushi and 10 other people went to the
wooded area about 30 miles southwest of Tokyo to check construction
of more than 850 apartment units for U.S. Navy personnel and their
families, said Soichi Takagi, a Zushi official.
   City officials have tried to stop the project, saying it would
jeopardize one of the few remaining wilderness tracts in the Tokyo
area.
   ``Japanese guards employed by U.S. military authorities locked
the gates and refused entry to the city officials, saying the city
should have obtained a permission from proper authorities,'' Takagi
said.
   Tomino argued unsuccessfully that Zushi city has legal authority
to conduct inspections of the 717-acre project and surveys of the
nearby hills, Takagi said. The city of 58,000 people borders on the
naval port city of Yokosuka.
   The Ikego Hills have escaped ravages of development around the
metropolis because they have been off-limits to civilians for the
past 52 years.
   Under the U.S.-Japan security treaty, Japan provides land and
some facilities together with part of the costs for stationing U.S.
servicemen in Japan. About 64,000 U.S. servicemen are based in Japan.
</TEXT>
