<FIRST>r w AM-Cattle-Feedlots     01-26 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cattle-Feedlots,000</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inventories Down 4 Percent from Year Ago</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cattle feedlot inventories in the nation's 13
leading beef states totaled 9.41 million head as of Jan. 1, down 4
percent from a year ago but 2 percent more than two years ago, the
Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   Only California, Idaho and Kansas showed increases from a year
ago, while decreases were reported in Arizona, Colorado, Illinois,
Iowa, Nebraska, Oklahoma, South Dakota, Texas and Washington.
Minnesota was unchanged.
   Marketings of fed cattle for slaughter during October, November
and December totaled 5.49 million head, a 2 percent decrease from
the same period of 1987 but 2 percent more than in 1986, the report
said.
   The placement of new cattle and calves on feed during the final
quarter of the year totaled 6.65 million head, down 1 percent from
the previous year and 2 percent fewer than in the same period of
1986.
   Cattle feeders indicated they expect to market 5.73 million head
during January, February and March, down 2 percent from last year's
first quarter and off fractionally from 1987, the report said.
   State feedlot cattle inventories are listed here for the 13
states, which account for about 85 percent of the nation's beef. The
first number is the number of cattle, in thousands, as of Jan. 1,
and the second number is the percentage of a year earlier.
</TEXT>
