<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1716EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-RockyFlats     01-26 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rocky Flats,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colorado Governor Threatens To Close Plant In May</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colorado will shut down the federal
government's Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant in May unless a new
site is found for its hazardous wastes, Gov. Roy Romer said Thursday.
   The plant, about 16 miles from Denver, is considered a critical
part of the nation's network of nuclear weapons factories. It is the
only plant capable of processing plutonium for nuclear weapons and
is the only fabricator of triggers for nuclear warheads.
   Radioactive waste from Rocky Flats used to be shipped north for
storage at the Idaho National Engineering Laboratory. In October,
however, Idaho sealed its borders against the shipments, forcing a
buildup of waste at the Rocky Flats complex.
   ``Our regulations allow only a limited quantity of wastes _ 1,600
cubic yards _ to be stored temporarily on site,'' Romer told the
Senate Governmental Affairs Committee. ``At the present rate of
waste generation, the plant will exceed this limit sometime in May
1989.''
   ``We must find a solution by May or we aren't going to have
production at Rocky Flats,'' Romer said, adding that he doesn't want
to close the plant but that ``it is an action I will take if I have
to.''
   Romer said another temporary waste storage site, far away from
population centers, must be found quickly.
   A forced shutdown of Rocky Flats would aggravate a growing
problem for the federal government, which last spring lost its only
nuclear reactor capable of making tritium, a perishable gas vital to
making nuclear weapons. That reactor, at the Savannah River Plant
near Aiken, S.C., was closed for safety and technical reasons and is
not expected to be restarted before late 1989.
   Rocky Flats borders a metropolitan area with 1.5 million people.
The plant has just begun the job of gradually reopening the building
that reprocesses plutonium. It was closed last October after some
workers were contaminated.
   Romer said he supports storing the wastes at the unopened Waste
Isolation Pilot Plant near Carlsbad, N.M.
   ``I think that ultimately is a safe facility,'' he said.
   Idaho Gov. Cecil Andrus complained to the committee about delays
in opening the New Mexico facility.
   Andrus said the Energy Department promised in 1973 it would
remove by 1980 waste temporarily stored in Idaho. That timetable was
pushed back several times until the state finally was told the waste
would be moved out in 1988. When it wasn't, the state drew the line
at 2.4 million cubic feet of material.
   ``We have been lied to for the last time,'' Andrus said. ``Idaho
has kept its part of a difficult bargain but the federal government
and the Department of Energy has not kept its word to us.''
   Andrus, Romer and Ohio Gov. Richard Celeste all urged the Senate
panel to make sure the government didn't turn the nuclear bomb
plants in their states into ``dumps of last resort'' or ``national
sacrifice zones.''
   In response to questioning by the committee chairman, Sen. John
Glenn, D-Ohio, an Environmental Protection Agency official said
``there may be'' some contamination at nuclear plants that is so
severe removing it would be more dangerous than fencing it in as a
sort of isolation area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
