<FIRST>r w AM-BeefDispute     01-26 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beef Dispute,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Say No Deal to Texas' Hormone-Free Beef</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Agriculture Commissioner Jim Hightower
won't be allowed to make an end run around an intercontinental trade
dispute and sell hormone-free beef from Texas to the European
Economic Community, a federal official said Thursday.
   ``It's not going to happen,'' said Roger Bolton, a spokesman for
the U.S. trade representative's office, even as officials of the
Texas Agriculture Department and the EEC continued working on ways
to open trade between Texas beef producers and European importers.
   ``We see no legal ability for them to stop it unless they impose
a formal embargo,'' Hightower said. ``We're taking a states' rights
position. If Ollie North can go run a private war with the applause
of the administration, why are they getting in the way of a few
cattlemen who want to make a sale to our very best customers?''
   Ella Krucoff, spokeswoman for Sir Roy Denman, head of EEC
delegation in Washington, said the EEC was in ``active contact with
the state of Texas. We are interested in maintaining the trade; we
want that trade to be in hormone-free meat.''
   The European Economic Community has banned imports of U.S. beef
and beef products because the meat, worth about $100 million in
sales, contains growth hormones that the EEC contends are a health
threat. The United States disputes those claims and retaliated by
setting about $100 million worth of higher tariffs on various Common
Market products.
   Ms. Krucoff said the EEC would be willing to accept certification
of the meat's purity from Texas authorities if the federal
government is not willing to certify the meat as hormone-free.
   Hightower said the Texas agency has asked acting Agriculture
Secretary Peter Myers to accept a provision with the EEC to certify
beef from Texas and other states for export, but ``we've had no
communication back.''
   The U.S. trade representative's office contends there is no way
Texas can verify the meat as hormone-free, thus effectively
prohibiting its export.
</TEXT>
