<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1630EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Nuke-Sleeping Bjt   01-26 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuke-Sleeping, Bjt,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>No More Cushy Chairs at Sleep-Plagued Nuke Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DELTA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The troubled Peach Bottom nuclear plant will
use everything from less comfortable chairs to a new shift rotation
to prevent a recurrence of control room operators sleeping on duty,
officials said Thursday.
   About 60 reporters were handed hardhats, goggles and tiny
radiation monitors as Philadelphia Electric Co., operator of the
dormant plant on the Susquehanna River, conducted its first media
tour of the facility.
   The utility is trying to convince the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission that things have changed since the NRC ordered the two
Peach Bottom reactors shut down in March 1987 because of widespread
sleeping and horseplay on the job by control room workers.
   The problems resulted in a $1.25 million fine, largest in NRC
history. Operator negligence was so pervasive that the commission
also levied fines ranging from $500 to $1,000 against 33 current and
former workers for ``sleeping and-or inattention to duty.''
   To combat the catnaps, plant officials said they have replaced
comfortable, high-backed chairs with low-backed models.
   Shift rotations have been changed so that operators work a week
of days, followed by a week of an afternoon-evening shift, and then
work the overnight. The rotation, which includes days off, used to
go in the reverse order.
   The moves are part of a plant shakeup that also includes new top
managers and revamped training courses for control room personnel.
   Peach Bottom officials said they hope to get NRC permission to
restart the plant in late March or April.
   Dave Woodrow, a control room shift supervisor, said the shutdown
has been ``a burden on myself and my family,'' and that operators
were eager to start again. ``We would like to prove to the public
that we are good operators,'' he said.
   Woodrow said sloppiness in the control room may have arisen
partly because Philadelphia Electric was devoting so much attention
to construction of the Limerick II nuclear plant in suburban
Philadelphia.
   ``It was a feeling we were being forgotten,'' he said.
   Efforts to improve worker morale were reflected in improvements
in plant equipment, and even in the distribution of gold-lettered
pens that proclaimed, ``I work at Peach Bottom Atomic Power Station
and I'm proud of it.''
   On-the-job napping was not the only problem at the plant. Since
the shutdown, the NRC also cited deficiencies in Peach Bottom's
security force _ which has recently been replaced _ and said the
plant needed to do a better job cleaning up surface contamination.
   Philadelphia Electric has had to pay about $150 million for
replacement power because of the outage, and Chairman Joseph
Paquette said Thursday, ``Our credibility certainly has been
damaged.''
   But Paquette added: ``We're obviously approaching the finish
line. We did not want the public to come in until we were sure we
had something you'd be impressed with.''
   After submitting background information to plant officials, the
group of reporters touring the plant was shown the control, turbine
and fuel storage rooms, stopping several times to step into phone
booth-sized radiation detectors.
   Peach Bottom is concentrating on getting its 14-year-old Unit 2
into operation first. A second unit would be restarted sometime
afterward.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890126-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1632EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-BoskinConfirmation     01-26 0709</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boskin Confirmation,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Confirmation Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Boskin, author of President Bush's
``flexible freeze'' approach to balancing the budget without
increasing taxes, defended the proposal Thursday and said defense
and health care are two areas where he believes spending cuts can be
made.
   Boskin, nominated to be Bush's chief economic adviser, said the
president would provide specific details on how the flexible freeze
will work when he unveils his budget recommendations during an
address to a joint session of Congress on Feb. 9.
   During the presidential campaign, the flexible freeze became
Bush's all-purpose answer to queries on how he planned to increase
spending for a variety of domestic programs while still lowering the
budget deficit without an increase in taxes.
   The flexible freeze would limit the growth in overall federal
spending to the rate of inflation. Any programs allowed to grow at a
faster pace would require offsetting cuts in other areas.
   While Bush mentioned several areas where he would increase
spending, he never specified where the cuts would be made.
   Boskin, who was Bush's principal economic adviser during the
campaign, was pressed during his confirmation hearing Thursday
before the Senate Banking Committee to point out areas where Bush
would recommend cuts.
   ``If there are no new taxes, that means there will have to be
some massive cuts in the federal budget,'' said Sen. Larry Pressler,
R-S.D., who repeatedly asked Boskin to specify ``three or four
areas'' where spending reductions should be made.
   Boskin emphasized that Bush had not made any final decisions on
the budget, but he said he would personally favor reducing the rate
of growth in the defense budget and in the government's health care
costs.
   ``If I was looking for large savings, they would have to come
from areas where there is large spending,'' Boskin said.
   President Reagan's final $1.15 trillion budget for the fiscal
year which begins next Oct. 1 did propose $5 billion in cuts in
Medicare and Medicaid. However, it protected Reagan's defense
buildup, recommending that defense spending authority rise 2 percent
above the rate of inflation.
   Boskin's comments appeared to support the widely held expectation
that Bush will seek cuts in defense to pay for increased spending in
domestic programs to fulfill his campaign promises.
   Boskin, 43, received widespread praise during his confirmation
hearings from senators who said Bush had made an excellent choice in
picking the highly regarded Stanford University economist to lead
the three-member Council of Economic Advisers.
   On other subjects, Boskin said:
   _ Social Security benefits will not be touched in the Bush
budget. Boskin has been a long-time proponent of changes in Social
Security and other middle-class benefit programs, calling them
``welfare for the wealthy.'' But in answering questions from
senators, Boskin said, ``President Bush has made it clear that
Social Security cuts are off the table and I don't advocate any
cuts.''
   _ The Bush budget will accept the basic economic growth
projections on which the Reagan budget was based. Critics have
charged that the administration's growth, interest rate and
inflation forecasts are too optimistic and the economy's actual
performance will make it impossible to meet the deficit goals. The
budget budget projects a 1990 budget deficit of $92.5 billion, below
the $100 billion target established by the Gramm-Rudman deficit
reduction law.
   _ The president remains committed to his pledge not to increase
taxes. Boskin said the proposal being considered to raise revenues
to deal with the savings and loan crisis by imposing a fee on
depositors at S&amp;Ls and other financial institutions could be
considered a user fee imposed on depositors for the protection they
recieve from having the federal government insure their savings.
   The Council of Economic Advisers, created in 1946 to advise the
president, fell on hard times during the Reagan administration. At
one point, the president considered abolishing the panel after his
advisers grew disenchanted with former Chairman Martin Feldstein's
suggestions that tax increases should be considered because of the
huge budget deficits.
   Boskin said he had been assured he would play a major role in
helping to formulate policy in the new administration and intended
to make suggestions to fill the other two spots on the panel as
quickly as possible.
</TEXT>
