<FIRST>r w AM-All-TerrainVehicles     01-26 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-All-Terrain Vehicles,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commerce says Japanese ATVs Being Dumped in US</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department on Thursday ruled that
Japanese all-terrain vehicles are being sold in the United States at
less than fair value and proposed anti-dumping duties to erase the
price advantage.
   The duties would affect Japanese exports of certain three- and
four-wheel vehicles designed for off-the-road use by one person, the
department said.
   The money is to be held as a cash deposit or bond while the U.S.
International Trade Commission determines if the imports injure or
threaten to injure U.S. manufacturers. The panel has 45 days to make
a decision.
   If the ITC rules there is injury, the Commerce Department would
issue a final order instructing the Customs Service to collect the
anti-dumping duties.
   The proposed anti-dumping duties vary, based on the gap between
what it cost Japanese companies to make the vehicles and the lower
prices they charged in the United States.
   The proposed duties are: Honda, 32.89 percent; Yamaha, 8.47
percent; Suzuki, 14.12 percent; Kawasaki, 35.43 percent; and all
others, 24.59 percent.
   Imports of all-terrain vehicles from Japan in 1987 were valued at
$534.4 million.
</TEXT>
