<FIRST>r a AM-DestroyerAground 1stLd-Writethru a0647 01-26 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Destroyer Aground, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0647,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Destroyer Runs Aground In Bahamas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with detail, including type of naval training
exercises, length of ship and size of crew, and divers conducting inspection.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy destroyer USS Spruance ran aground
during anti-submarine warfare exercises near Andros Island in the
Bahamas, the Navy said Thursday.
   No one was injured in the Wednesday night incident, but the
563-foot ship had minor damage, said Lt. Cmdr. John Lloyd, a
spokesman at Atlantic Fleet surface force headquarters in Norfolk,
Va.
   Lloyd said the ship, based in Mayport, is in no danger of
sinking. The guided missile frigate USS Boone and Navy tugs were
working to refloat the Spruance, and divers were conducting an
inspection, officials said.
   The Navy was investigating the cause of the mishap. Lloyd said
winds were blowing about 30 mph when the ship ran aground and
continued strong with gusts up to 35 mph Thursday.
   The ship, more than twice the size of World War II destroyers,
left Mayport on Tuesday and had been scheduled to return Friday. The
vessel was commissioned on September 1975 and carries a crew of 20
officers and 267 enlisted men.
   The underwater warfare training takes place in a deep-water
trough east of Andros. The are, where water is as deep as 8,000 feet
or more, is fringed by reef-filled shallows.
   Andros, the largest of the Bahamian islands, is about 180 miles
east of Key West, Fla. The grounding occurred three miles from of a
Navy pier on the island, which is home to the Navy's Atlantic
Undersea Test and Evaluation Center.
</TEXT>
