<FIRST>r w AM-SoybeanOutlook     01-26 0130</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soybean Outlook,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>It's Not Good</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's soybean farmers are still being
affected by crop prospects in Brazil and Argentina, an Agriculture
Department report said Thursday.
   Combined production of the two countries is forecast at 31
million metric tons, up 3.3 million tons from last year, the
department's Economic Research Service said.
   ``However, prospects are more uncertain this year because of
delayed plantings in both countries and dry weather, especially in
Argentina,'' the report said. ``The size of the South American crop
will influence soybean prices and U.S. plantings in 1989.''
   U.S. soybean production last year, the lowest since 1976, dropped
to about 1.54 billion bushels, or 41.9 million tons. A metric ton is
about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of soybeans.
</TEXT>
