<FIRST>u w AM-Lujan-Interior     01-26 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lujan-Interior,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lujan Promises to Protect Environment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manuel Lujan, President Bush's choice for
interior secretary, told senators Thursday he is ``committed to
protecting and enhancing'' the nation's natural resources, but said
that doesn't preclude some development.
   ``We can do both. We do not have to choose between them,''
declared Lujan, whose Senate confirmation is expected without major
controversy.
   Lujan, who spent 20 years representing New Mexico as a
congressman, received a warm reception from both Democrats and
Republicans on the Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee
which is expected to send his name to Senate floor for a vote,
probably next week.
   One of two Hispanics selected by Bush for his Cabinet, Lujan
reminded the committee he is a westerner who grew up ``where
reverence for the beauty and the sanctity of our land was instilled
in me from the earliest days of my youth.''
   Lujan's childhood was spent on land that is now an Indian
reservation, said the 60-year-old former congressman. As interior
secretary he would oversee the Bureau of Indian Affairs and, in
response to a question, said he would become personally involved if
he heard of any native Americans being treated insensitively.
   But Lujan's nomination has received only lukewarm endorsement
from most environmental and conservation groups, who complain that
in 20 years in Congress he voted against environmental interests on
a number of occasions.
   Some of those votes have raised ``signals ... that you are not
sympathetic to environmental legislation,'' said Sen. Mark Hatfield,
R-Ore., citing specifically Lujan's vote against legislation,
sponsored by Hatfield, which expanded wilderness areas.
   Lujan defended his record on environmental and conservation
matters and said he and Bush ``are committed to protecting and
enhancing the nation's natural resources, as well as proceeding with
their environmentally sound development.''
   Noting that some of these issues are highly controversial, Lujan
said, ``we all need to lower our voices so that we can hear each
other.''
   ``Development of our most promising domestic resources is called
for because continued development is essential to the national
security and economic well being of the United States,'' he said.
   ``At the same time, we will oppose development in those
environmentally sensitive areas where the risk of damage is great,''
he continued.
   Environmental groups have raised concern about the possibility of
oil and drilling on the vast Arctic National Wildlife Refuge in
northeastern Alaska and have noted that Lujan sponsored legislation
in the last Congress that would have allowed such drilling.
   Sen. Timothy Wirth, D-Colo., noted that ``the lines are already
being drawn'' on the question of whether oil companies should be
allowed onto the Alaska refuge.
   Lujan said he was ``not happy'' that ``we're starting off in a
confrontational way'' as far as the wildlife drilling question is
concerned, suggesting that some of the difference might be worked
out through discussions and compromise.
   Oil and gas development in the refuge would require congressional
approval. Lujan said while he favored such development, he is
opposed to a land swap deal suggested by the Reagan administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
