<DOCNO> AP890126-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1706EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador     01-26 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftists Denounce Government Qualms with Rebel Election Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leftist coalition on Thursday
accused the government of hiding behind the constitution to prevent
the Marxist-led guerrilla movement from taking part in the March
presidential election.
   ``This is the moment for the political parties to demonstrate
whether they want peace or bones,'' Guillermo Ungo, presidential
candidate of the leftist Democratic Convergence, told a news
conference.
   The guerrillas, who have been fighting the U.S.-backed government
for nine years, offered Tuesday to take part in elections if certain
conditions were met. The rebels previously have boycotted all five
elections held this decade.
   The insurgents' proposal dropped their longstanding insistence on
sharing power in a transitional government, the major stumbling
block in three rounds of unsuccessful peace talks between 1984 and
1987.
   The guerrillas' main condition for participation was postponement
of presidential elections from March 19 to September.
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte, a Christian Democrat, and the
rightist opposition Republican Nationalist Alliance, or Arena,
rejected the rebel proposal as unconstitutional.
   The constitution says presidential elections must be held no
later than two months before the end of the five-year presidential
term. Duarte's term ends June 1.
   ``The constitutional problem invoked by some seems to us no more
than a pretext to prolong the war and impede the advent of peace,''
the Democratic Convergence said in a communique.
   Ungo and Ruben Zamora, another Democratic Convergence leader,
presented a constitutional solution to the election date quandary.
   ``The problem is not constitutional, it is one of lack of
political will,'' said Zamora.
   Convergence members said parties contesting the elections could
force a postponement by withdrawing from the March balloting.
   ``The absence of candidates would prevent the holding of
elections,'' said Ungo. He cited the constitutional provision for
election by the legislature of an interim president who would serve
until elections are held.
   ``The constitution exists to serve the people, as an instrument
providing for peace and coexistence _ not to impede peace and
coexistence,'' said Ungo.
   Zamora said the Christian Democrats and rightists ``are using the
constitution as a skirt to hide behind.''
   Arena candidate Alfredo Cristiani led Christian Democratic
candidate Fidel Chavez Mena in recent polls. Ungo is running a
distant third, according to the polls.
   The guerrillas said they would throw their support behind the
Democratic Convergence candidates if their conditions of
participation were met.
   The coalition, in its press conference, cited examples of
repeated violation of the country's charter under the current
government.
   For example, the constitution requires security forces to obtain
a search warrant before entering a citizen's home. But army troops
and police regularly sweep through entire working class
neighborhoods, entering homes and going through drawers and personal
belongings without warrants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
