<FIRST>r i AM-Arafat     01-26 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arafat,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aide Says Arafat Canceled Speech, Won't Seek Visa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yasser Arafat will not request a U.S. visa in
order to address an Arab-American group and will visit the United
States only if he gets an official invitation, an aide said Thursday.
   The PLO chairman arrived in Spain from Iraq on Thursday to meet
with the foreign ministers of Spain, France and Greece in his
campaign for international peace conference on the Middle East.
   Those countries have been assigned by the 12-member European
Economic Community to gather support for a U.N.-sponsored
conference. The Israeli government opposes such a forum and wants
direct negotiations with Arab countries, but refuses to deal with
the PLO.
   Abdeen Jabara, president of the American-Arab Anti-Discrimination
Committee, said this month the group had invited Arafat to speak at
its April meeting and he had accepted.
   In his comments in Cairo on Thursday, Nabil Shaath did not
explain why Arafat changed his mind beyond saying the Palestine
Liberation Organization chief ``said he will not go on an invitation
from an unofficial group.''
   Shaath, a top political adviser, said Arafat would accept only an
official invitation from Washington.
   The United States refused Arafat's request for a visa to address
the U.N. General Assembly in December, saying he condoned terrorism,
and the assembly moved its session from New York to Geneva.
   After a Geneva news conference in which Arafat renounced
terrorism and recognized Israel's right to exist, the United States
began talks with PLO officials in Tunisia.
   Israel considers the PLO a terrorist organization and has
bitterly criticized the decision by its principal ally.
   A diplomat in Madrid said privately Thursday: ``It's no secret
the United States is the only party that has any influence over
Israel. What the EEC is trying to do is send a message to
Washington.''
   Another said it ``would not be surprising'' if Arafat requested
EEC recognition of a Palestinian state during his meeting Friday
with Foreign Ministers Francisco Fernandez Ordonez of Spain, Roland
Dumas of France and Carolos Papoulias of Greece.
   The Palestine National Council, which acts as the PLO
legislature, proclaimed an independent Palestinian state Nov. 15 at
a session in Tunis. The EEC reacted favorably but did not extend
official recognition.
   Spain holds the rotating presidency of the trading bloc for the
first six months of 1989.
