<FIRST>r a AM-NitroLeak     01-26 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nitro Leak,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Leak In Week Reported At Superfund Site In Nitro</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NITRO, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There is no way to prevent another leak of
chemicals stored at the abandoned Artel Chemical Co. plant, said a
federal Environmental Protection Agency official investigating two
leaks in the last week.
   ``I believe we will be experiencing these things over and over
until the warm weather is over,'' said Jerry Saseen, the EPA's
coordinator of the Artel Chemical cleanup.
   Saseen and Nitro Mayor Don Karnes both blame unseasonably warm
weather for a leak Wednesday night and a leak Jan. 19. Temperatures
have been fluctuating from the 20s and 30s to the 50s and 60s during
a January warm spell.
   In each case, moisture built up in a sealed 55-gallon drum, and
the water reacted with the substance inside to create a cloud of
chemical vapor.
   No injuries were reported in either accident, but both times
nearby traffic was blocked and residents were asked to stay in their
homes.
   ``I guess this could happen two or three times a day,'' Karnes
said. ``I hope it doesn't. There are a lot of chemicals over there.''
   The EPA on Thursday still was trying to determine exactly what
was in the drum of waste acid that leaked Wednesday.
   There was a danger the substance could cause problems with
thousands of other drums of chemicals at the EPA Superfund site,
Saseen said.
   ``The lid blew off, and since it was acid, we wanted to stop any
corrosion of the other drums, so we dusted it with soda ash,''
Karnes said.
   Cleanup crews could begin moving more than 5,000 drums of toxic
and hazardous chemicals from the abandoned plant as early as
mid-February, said EPA official Doug Fox. The plant was closed and
turned over to the EPA in June after the federal government declared
it a public health hazard.
   EPA crews were still sampling the drums to find out exactly what
was stored at the site, Saseen said.
   The leak last week involved thionyl chloride, which reacted with
water and released hydrochloric acid and sulfur dioxide, which can
be deadly in high amounts, the EPA said.
</TEXT>
