<FIRST>r w AM-DrugProgram     01-26 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Program,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Announces New Drug-Testing Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Random drug testing for key personnel,
including astronauts, will start in March at the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration, the chief of the agency
announced Thursday.
   NASA administrator James C. Fletcher said a system of random drug
testing will be applied to all employees in sensitive positions,
including senior level management, astronauts, flight controllers,
researchers and engineers.
   Additionally, Fletcher said in a NASA announcement, ``drug
testing may be required if there is a reasonable suspicion of
illegal drug use or an accident or unsafe practice.''
   Fletcher said because of the ``limited scope of drug abuse in the
agency,'' the NASA drug program will emphasize education, training
and assistance through the NASA Employee Assistance Program for
employees ``who may be experiencing a problem related to such drug
use.''
   ``NASA recognizes that drug abuse is debilitating and that
prolonged illegal drug use makes it progressively more difficult for
the individual to refrain from such drug use,'' Fletcher said.
   Dwayne Brown, a NASA spokesman, said the drug program is
scheduled to start March 27, which is 60 days from the date of
Fletcher's announcement.
   Fletcher said the new drug program is in support of an executive
order from the Reagan administration that calls for a drug-free
federal workplace.
</TEXT>
