<FIRST>r a AM-Spy-Glasnost     01-26 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spy-Glasnost,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>KGB Defector: Espionage Increases Under Glasnost</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet spies are flourishing as
relations between the two superpowers improve, said a former
high-ranking Soviet KGB officer who defected to the United States.
   ``The nicer the relationship between the United States and the
Soviet Union, the more aggressive Soviet intelligence is,''
Stanislav Levchenko told the Palm Beach Round Table on Wednesday.
   ``Soviets know Americans very well,'' said Levchenko, who
defected to U.S. authorities 10 years ago in Tokyo, where he spent
four years as a major in the KGB. ``The better the relationship, the
kinder, more open-hearted Americans become. Americans are very
trustworthy people.''
   The 47-year-old former spy said one of the first things he
learned upon joining the KGB was that his colleagues were nothing
like those in the movies.
   In films, ``basically, you understand within five minutes who the
good guys are because they look good and bad guys look bad,'' he
said. ``What I learned unfortunately was that bad guys looked like
good guys and sometimes much better.''
   MICE is the international acronym in the espionage world for the
four means of recruiting agents and informants, Levchenko said. The
letters stand for money, ideology, compromise and ego.
   ``It's a very real thing that is going on,'' he said. ``The
Soviet intelligence against this country is dramatically growing and
expanding.''
</TEXT>
