<FIRST>r i AM-OPEC 1stLd-Writethru a0649 01-26 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OPEC, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0649,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>OPEC, Independents Agree on Joint Responsibility for Oil Prices</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with communique, meeting over, late
oil prices; longer version moved on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts from six OPEC nations and seven independent
oil producers agreed Thursday to recommend further steps for
bolstering world oil prices, but stopped short of making specific
plans for cooperation.
   Oil ministers from both sides will meet at a yet-undecided date
for further discussion on the issue, OPEC General Secretary Subroto
told reporters after the daylong closed meeting.
   The non-OPEC countries also stated in a communique that they
supported OPEC's goal of achieving a target price of $18 a barrel
``as soon as possible.''
   ``They agreed on the need to take further steps to enhance
improvements already achieved and to further strengthen the oil
market, especially in the second quarter of 1989,'' the communique
read.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries has been trying
to enlist the support of non-OPEC producers since the cartel agreed
at its November ministerial meeting to curtail its own production in
order to boost prices.
   Since the OPEC agreement prices have moved higher, and the chief
U.S. crude _ West Texas Intermediate _ sporadically has topped $18 a
barrel in recent futures trading.
   The spot price of North Sea Brent Blend, the most widely traded
international crude oil, fell to $16.25 a barrel Thursday night,
down 43 cents from late Wednesday.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the March contract for West
Texas Intermediate plunged 40 cents to settle at $17.72 a barrel,
the lowest level of Thursday's session. The contract had jumped 58
cents on Wednesday.
   The communique did not specify possible steps for supporting
prices, although Subroto said a 5 percent production cut ``is an
option.''
   Non-OPEC sources had speculated some of the independent producers
might offer to cut their collective production by 5 percent without
requesting reciprocal cuts from OPEC.
   The two sides said they also agreed ``this initial effort should
be continued in the second half of the year and consolidated
thereafter to establish a more permanent, long-term cooperation for
achieving durable oil market stability...''
   Analysts said the futures markets may have been disappointed by
the lack of concrete plans.
   ``They didn't recommend any specific action,'' said Nauman
Barakat, vice president of energy investments at Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in New York. ``Their statement was so vague that it
didn't really mean anything.''
   The attending OPEC nations were Kuwait, Algeria, Saudi Arabia,
Indonesia, Venezuela and Nigeria. The other OPEC members are
Ecuador, Gabon, Libya, Qatar, Iran, and the United Arab Emirates.
   The communique from the independents said the non-OPEC group
consisted of representatives of Angola, China, Colombia, Egypt,
Malaysia, Mexico, and Oman and observers from the Soviet Union,
Norway, the Yemen Arab Republic, the Canadian province of Alberta
and the U.S. states of Alaska and Texas.
   OPEC members agreed in November to limit their production to 18.5
million barrels a day, effective Jan. 1.
   OPEC members are producing an estimated 19.5 million barrels a
day, down as much as 3.5 million barrels a day from the fourth
quarter. That has helped oil prices recover from around $12 a barrel
in December.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
