<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     01-26 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians Stop Shiite Gunbattle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias fought a
30-minute gunbattle in the south Beirut slums Thursday before Syrian
patrols moved in to stop it, police reported.
   A police spokesman said there was no casualty report. Each side
blamed the other for the fight between the Syrian-backed Amal
militia and the pro-Iranian fundamentalists of Hezbollah, or Party
of God.
   Officials of Syria and Iran, which are allies but have
conflicting interests in Lebanon, have been meeting in Damascas in
an effort to end a power struggle between the militias. A
``preliminary'' cease-fire was proclaimed Wednesday but collapsed
within hours.
   Syria has 40,000 soldiers stationed in Lebanon and is the
war-ravaged nation's main power broker.
   Amal and Hezbollah have been fighting in Beirut and south Lebanon
since last April for supremacy among the 1 million Shiites, the
country's largest sect. Nearly 700 people have been reported killed
and more than 1,800 wounded.
   Two Moslem leaders left for Tunis on Thursday for talks with an
Arab League committee on how to end a political crisis that could
cement the sectarian division resulting from nearly 13 years of
civil war.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem who heads a
Moslem cabinet vying for power with a rival Christian government,
and Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini, a Shiite, are to meet with
the committee Monday.
   In south Lebanon, Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir paid a
three-hour visit to Israel's ``security zone'' just north of its
frontier, which is patrolled by soldiers and a predominantly
Christian surrogate militia.
   He told Israeli soldiers at a post on the zone's northern edge:
``The small units of soldiers here who are guarding the border .. .
are fully carrying out their duties. There is security in the
country, on the northern borders and the settlements.''
   Israel established the zone, which ranges in depth from six to 10
miles, after withdrawing in June 1985 from a three-year invasion and
occupation of Lebanon.
