<FIRST>r w AM-TritiumAlternative     01-26 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tritium Alternative,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elite Scientific Panel Briefed on Accelerator Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elite panel of scientists, whose advice to
the Department of Defense is often cloaked in secrecy, has received
a briefing from researchers who believe a linear accelerator may be
a cheaper, safer and quicker way to produce tritium than building
new reactors.
   The Defense Department has consulted the panel, known as the
``JASON Group,'' on military projects involving complex technologies
since 1959.
   The briefing, late last week in La Jolla, Calif., was made by
researchers from the Los Alamos and Brookhaven national laboratories
and the Westinghouse-Hanford Co. who for more than a year have been
exploring the possibility of using an accelerator to produce tritium
_ a key ingredient in nuclear weapons.
   ``They seemed to be very enthusiastic and highly supportive of
the idea,'' said William Kato, chairman of the Department of Nuclear
Energy at Brookhaven.
   Kato said that the normal practice of the group would be to write
a report that ``I assume would go to the Department of Defense and
Department of Energy.''
   Others who attended the briefing, but asked not to be identified,
said the presentation marked the first time the accelerator concept
had been presented to an independent, technical review team.
   Kato said the presentation was similar to one made to Department
of Energy officials in Washington last August.
   The Energy Department, which builds nuclear weapons for the
military, is proceeding with plans to construct two new tritium
producing reactors.
   A top official of the Energy Department told a Senate committee
on Wednesday that the department felt technology was not ``mature''
enough to use a linear accelerator rather than a nuclear reactor to
produce tritium.
   An accelerator is essentially a long tunnel in which subatomic
particles are whipped at high speeds until they crash into a target,
in this case lithium clad in aluminum. The resulting collision
produces tritium, a radioactive gas used in nuclear weapons.
   The nation's existing tritium producing reactors, located at the
Savannah River complex in South Carolina, have been beset with
safety problems and are currently shut down.
   Chris Sankey, a department spokeswoman, said Thursday that as a
``long-range option to augment, not replace our plans for two new
production reactors, we may undertake additional evaluation of the
accelerator concept. That would take place when a concrete proposal
is presented to the department.''
   The JASON Group is composed of about 55 scientists who do
``sophisticated scientific research and analysis in support of the
national security community,'' said Jan Bodanyi, a spokeswoman for
the Defense Department.
   Ms. Bodanyi said most members are physicists and include Nobel
laureates and other highly respected scientists.
   he group has studied such other problems as designing the
Strategic Defense Initiative and detecting plastic guns, said Ms.
Bodanyi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
