<FIRST>r w AM-Baker     01-26 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Baker, On the Job Only Hours, Closes Kabul Embassy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new secretary of state, James A. Baker III,
spent his first day at work Thursday settling into his 7th floor
suite _ and deciding to close the U.S. Embassy in Kabul, Afghanistan.
   Baker, one of President Bush's closest friends and the man who
managed the final months of Bush's campaign for the White House,
kept a low profile during his first working day and issued no
schedule.
   Within hours of being sworn in Wednesday night, however, the
rising turmoil in the Afghan capital required his attention.
   A U.S. official, who asked not to be identified, said Baker had
decided that the U.S. contingent, reduced to less than 10 officers
and security guards in recent weeks, would be pulled out over the
next several days.
   The move came as the Soviets continued to pull out troops that
have been in the country since 1979 and as fighting increased
between the pro-Moscow government and U.S.-backed rebels battling
for control of the country.
   The official added that the decision had been put off by Reagan
administration officials and left for Baker to deal with after he
was sworn in, which took place shortly after the Senate confirmed
his nomination.
   Asked about Baker's day, department spokesman Charles Redman
would say only that his new boss was ``getting established, that's
his first priority'' and that Baker had ``met with his top people.''
   Asked by a reporter to identify those individuals _ so that clues
might be drawn about who might in line for the top slots in the
department during the new administration's overhaul of personnel _
Redman smiled and declined to reveal Baker's appointments, evoking a
round of laughter from journalists.
   Redman also said he had no information about any foreign contacts
that Baker planned to have and said the new secretary looked toward
Monday as being his day to ``get ... into operation.''
   True to the former treasury secretary's crisp and formal style,
Baker held early-morning meetings with top aides in his formal
office workspace _ attired in suit and tie, said one senior official
who met with him.
   Baker's predecessor, George Shultz, had been known to strike an
informal note, meeting with aides in his more cozy sitting room,
doffing his suit coat for a sweater and poking intermittedly at the
embers in his fireplace.
   Baker was sworn in in a private ceremony at the street-floor
transition office he'd been using since his nomination. A more
formal oath-taking ceremony was set Friday afternoon in the elegant
East Room of the White House.
</TEXT>
