<FIRST>u i AM-Italy-Calvi     01-26 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Calvi,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules Head Of Banco Ambrosiano Was Murdered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civil court has ruled that Roberto Calvi, the
central figure in a banking scandal that reached into the Vatican,
was murdered in 1982 and did not commit suicide, news reports said
Thursday.
   Calvi's body was found hanging from a London bridge days after he
disappeared from Italy, where he was under investigation for his
inability to account for $1.4 billion in loans and interest on the
books of the bank he headed, Banco Ambrosiano.
   A coroner's jury in London in June 1983 left open the question of
whether Calvi hanged himself, or whether he was murdered to stop him
from revealing details about the financial scandal.
   Calvi was called ``God's banker'' for his close relations with
the Vatican.
   The Milan civil court suit was filed by Calvi's widow, Clara, who
wanted to collect on the banker's $3 million life insurance policy
issued by Assicurazioni Generali, Italy's largest insurance company.
   ``I am very satisfied by the sentence of the Milan civil court
which has recognized the death of my husband as an assassination and
not a suicide,'' Mrs. Calvi was quoted as saying by the Italian news
agency ANSA.
   A spokesman for Assicurazioni Generali, Armando Zimolo, confirmed
that the policy prohibited payment in the case of suicide. He said
the company had held off paying until the cause of death was
established.
   Wednesday's verdict did not mean the Calvi family would collect
on the policy. The Calvi case has yet to go before a criminal court,
and the Milan tribunal's decision could be overturned on appeal to a
higher civil court.
   The Turin-based newspaper La Stampa said the Milan court ruled on
the basis of the autopsy and a reconstruction of what the court
believed happened on the night of June 17, 1982, at Blackfriers
Bridge in London.
   Calvi was found dangling from scaffolding under the bridge, with
11 pounds of bricks stuffed into his pockets and another brick
jammed down the front of his pants.
   Banco Ambrosiano collapsed following its failure to collect $1.4
billion in loans made to 10 dummy companies in Latin America
controlled by the Vatican bank.
</TEXT>
