<FIRST>u i AM-China-US-Korea     01-26 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-US-Korea,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>US, North Koreans Diplomats Meet in Beijing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American and North Korean diplomats have held two
meetings in Beijing, apparently the first in at least a year,
according to reports Thursday in China and in Washington.
   Sin In Ha, the North Korean ambassador, told a news conference in
the Chinese capital the talks ``were not anything to shout about.''
   ``It was very simple,'' he said. ``Living together on the same
planet it is impossible not to have contact. ... We always keep the
door open for talks but the United States closes the door.''
   Neither he nor the U.S. State Department would reveal details.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman gave the
meeting dates as Dec. 6 and last Tuesday.
   ``We believe that these contacts have been useful,'' he said.
``Both sides stated their positions on Korean peninsula political
and security issues.''
   Redman said the meetings between the political counselors of the
two embassies were arranged through the ``good offices'' of China,
an ally of communist North Korea.
   He said North Korea delivered a letter from Foreign Minister Kim
Yon-Nam to George P. Shultz, then secretary of state, at the
December meeting and the United States responded at this week's
session.
   The meetings were believed to be the first since Washington
relaxed rules last fall on contacts between the two countries, which
do not have diplomatic relations.
   In January 1988, the State Department declared North Korea a
terrorist nation and barred ``substantive discussions'' with North
Korean envoys in third countries. The action responded to the
bombing of a South Korean jetliner in November 1987 by a woman who
said she was a North Korean agent.
   When the 1988 Seoul Olympics concluded in October without
disruption by North Korea, the United States again authorized such
contacts.
</TEXT>
