<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     01-26 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Cancels Meetings In Indonesia, Paris and Bangkok</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Norodom Sihanouk, once Cambodia's ruler and
now a rebel leader, said Thursday he will not attend peace talks
next month because the Vietnamese-sponsored government of his
homeland rejected his proposals.
   Sihanouk, who heads a coalition fighting Vietnam's decade-long
occupation of Cambodia, said in a statement that ``it is absolutely
useless for me to be in Jakarta,'' capital of Indonesia, for the
negotiations.
   He also said he would not go to Paris in the spring for a meeting
of the three rebel factions and the Cambodian government, and had
called off a meeting in Bangkok with Siddhi Savetsila, foreign
minister of Thailand, scheduled for the end of February.
   Representatives of Vietnam, Laos, the warring parties of Cambodia
and the non-communist Association of Southeast Asian Nations are to
meet Feb. 19-22 in Jakarta for a second session of peace talks. The
first was held last July.
   Members of ASEAN are Thailand, Indonesia, Singapore, Malaysia,
the Philippines and Brunei.
   Sihanouk arrived in Beijing on Tuesday and had said the next day
he would go to Jakarta but not participate in the meetings.
   His five-point plan proposes that international peacekeeping
force supervise Vietnam's withdrawal from Cambodia, which it invaded
in December 1978 and has occupied since.
   Hun Sen, premier of the government Vietnam installed in Phnom
Penh, claims the plan would facilitate the return to power in
Cambodia of the Khmer Rouge, the strongest of the three resistance
groups.
   The Khmer Rouge led Cambodia from the end of the Indochina war in
1975 until the Vietnamese invasion and was responsible for at least
1 million deaths.
   China's army attacked Vietnam in 1979 to ``punish'' it for
invading Cambodia invasion, but last week the two countries held
their first high-level meeting in a decade.
   Vietnam agreed in principle to withdraw from Cambodia by
September if a political settlement is reached. It also agreed to
supervision by an international group, whose makeup has not been
determined.
   China said it would slow aid to the rebel coalition in tandem
with the Vietnamese departure.
   The agreement in principle does not represent a change in
position by either country.
   Sihanouk said Tuesday he opposed linking ``an end to material aid
to the resistance and the withdrawal of Vietnamese troops'' and was
pessimistic about easy solutions.
   Progress had been made on solving the international aspects of
the conflict, he said, but a ``deadlock'' remained on the
composition of a future Cambodian government.
   In Bangkok, Prime Minister Chatichai Choonhavan urged all
factions to attend the Jakarta negotiations.
   ``The Cambodian parties must face one another,'' he told
reporters after two days of talks with Hun Sen. ``It's pointless for
them to fight and kill one another.''
</TEXT>
