<FIRST>r a AM-Kidnap-Murder     01-26 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kidnap-Murder,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Report Two Arrests In N.J. Murder-Kidnapping</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NR3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arizona fugitive and his companion
were charged Thursday in the abduction-slaying of a man shot to
death after the his wife paid a $25,000 ransom.
   John Martini, 58, and Therese Afdahl, 30, were arrested after
being spotted by police at a Fort Lee motel Wednesday and were
charged in the slaying of 58-year-old Irving Flax.
   Flax's body was found Tuesday morning with three gunshot wounds
to the head in a shopping mall parking lot in Paramus. An autopsy
showed he apparently had been shot about four hours after his wife
dropped off the ransom Monday night.
   FBI agents trailing the kidnapper who picked up the ransom in
Flax's car lost track of the auto about 45 minutes later in New York
City.
   ``There was a lot of evasive driving before we lost him,'' said
John C. McGinley, the FBI agent in charge of the bureau's Newark
office. ``It looked as though he was looking for any signs of our
surveillance.''
   Acting Bergen County Prosecutor John Holl said the investigation
continued.
   ``It's possible there may be more arrests,'' he said.
   Superior Court Judge Charles R. DiGisi ordered Martini held
without bail because he is also wanted on a Glendale, Ariz., murder
warrant in which two people were found dead in a mall parking lot,
authorities said.
   Ms. Afdahl was ordered held on $500,000 cash bail.
   Both face murder and weapon possession charges in New Jersey. The
court entered innocent pleas for the two until they can consult with
attorneys.
   In Arizona, Glendale police said a warrant issued Nov. 29
accusing Martini of shooting to death Teresa Marie Dempster, 27, and
David Richard Uhl, 42, whose bodies were found Nov. 8 in a car
parked at a small shopping center.
   Holl said Martini knew Flax when the two worked as drivers for
the Miller Trucking Co. two decades ago. Martini turned up on Flax's
doorstep Monday morning and invited him to go for coffee, the
prosecutor said.
   Holl said Flax was taken at gunpoint to an apartment in Fairview
that Martini and Ms. Afdahl had rented. Calls were then made to
Flax's wife, telling her to bring the $25,000 to a diner that
evening.
   At the diner Martini motioned for her drop the brown bag
containing the ransom, picked it up and fled in Flax's car, Holl
said. After losing the FBI agents, he returned to the Fairview
apartment and took Flax to the shopping mall where he was shot about
11:30 p.m., Holl said.
   The prosecutor said the couple were caught Wednesday night after
an anonymous tipster alerted Bergen County authorities that Martini
was in New Jersey.
   When arrested the two were carrying a duffel bag containing
$29,000 and a .32 caliber handgun. The serial numbers on $25,000 of
the cash matched the numbers of the bills used in the ransom,
authorities said.
</TEXT>
