<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     01-26 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Kill Judge, Seven Village Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUANCAYO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist rebels forced a judge and seven
village leaders to lie down in the town square, shot them to death
and ordered their bodies left untouched, police said Thursday.
   Justice of the Peace Honorato Salazar and the village leaders
were slain Sunday in Vilca, a tiny Andean hamlet 40 miles west of
Huancayo, police said.
   Ten Shining Path rebels disguised in army uniforms and
brandishing machine guns and rifles disrupted a celebration in the
square and ordered the eight to lie on the ground.
   The insurgents accused the men of supporting Peru's elected
government, and shot them to death, police said.
   They said rebels remained in Vilca for two days, threatening
violence for anyone touching the bodies. They said the rebels
ordered the bodies left untouched as ``food for the dogs.''
   Police said villagers late Wednesday carried the bodies to
Huancayo, 125 miles east of Lima, and informed officials of the
attack.
   The Shining Path stepped up its attacks across rural Peru late
last year, killing hundreds of peasants, police, soldiers and other
officials.
   The government says violence surrounding the rebels' nine-year
insurgency has claimed more than 12,000 lives.
