<FIRST>r a AM-Bomb-Animal     01-26 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bomb-Animal,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company President Acknowledges Infiltrating Animal Rights Groups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A surgical supply company president who was
the target of a bombing attempt by an animal-rights activist
acknowledged Thursday that his company has used paid informants to
infiltrate animal-rights groups.
   ``If we didn't have somebody in the animal rights group that
believed in right and wrong, you and I would not be having this
conversation _ I'd be dead,'' said Leon C. Hirsch, president and
founder of U.S. Surgical Corp.
   Fran Trutt was arrested Nov. 11 in Norwalk after police said she
placed a radio-controlled pipe bomb packed with roofing nails on the
grounds of U.S. Surgical. They said she apparently opposed the
company's use of live, anesthetized dogs in surgical equipment
demonstrations.
   Meanwhile, CBS News obtained a tape-recorded conversation of a
woman it identified as Trutt telling an informant that she ``knew
what had to be done'' and planned to ``go for Leon,'' an apparent
reference to Hirsch.
   Hirsch, in a telephone interview Thursday with The Associated
Press, asserted that ``terrorists'' within the animal-rights
movement have left U.S. Surgical and other medical companies little
choice but to wage a sort of counter-offensive to protect themselves.
   ``Many of them are very dangerous organizations,'' he said.
``They don't believe in right and wrong as most people in society
do. They believe that human beings are on the same par as rats and
dogs and they are prepared to take violent actions to enforce their
beliefs.
   Hirsch dismissed suggestions that Trutt, 33, of New York City had
been entrapped, saying that neither his company, the Norwalk police
nor his security consultant, Perceptions International Inc. of
Stratford, had aided or coerced Trutt into planting the bomb.
   ``There was absolutely not a shimmer of entrapment involved
here,'' he said. ``That woman attempted to kill me. It was her idea
... it was her orchestration.''
   The Westport News reported earlier this month that U.S. Surgical,
through Perceptions International, had recruited Marc Mead of
Westport to strike up a friendship with Trutt and to inform U.S.
Surgical of her activities.
   The authorities have said Mead, 30, helped transport the bomb to
U.S. Surgical's parking lot and was with Trutt when she was arrested
that same day. Mead has not been charged in the case.
   Mead's attorney, Kenneth D'Amato, said he wouldn't discuss the
case.
   Trutt is being held under $500,000 bond and is scheduled to
appear in Stamford Superior Court for a pretrial hearing Feb. 2.
   On the tape-recording obtained by CBS, the woman the network
identified as Trutt said: ``Then I'm going to do what has to be done
... I'm going to go for Leon. I'm going to learn to make a bomb if I
have to make it myself.''
   In an on-camera interview with CBS, Trutt reiterated previous
statements that she only meant to frighten Hirsch.
   Trutt said an informant gave her the money for the bomb, but said
she wasn't coerced into planting it.
</TEXT>
