<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs, Jan. 27, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A series of four TV religious specials, ``The
Promise of America,'' produced by the Interfaith Broadcasting
Commission through a grant from NBC, begins on the network this
Sunday.
   The commission is made up of Protestant, Roman Catholic, Eastern
Orthodox and Jewish representatives.
   The first hour-long special, ``The Hunger Next Door,'' looks at
conditions of hunger and poverty and efforts to relieve it. The
documentary was produced by the Southern Baptist Radio-TV Commission.
   Other programs scheduled in the series are:
   April 16 _ ``Discovery,'' a drama about a 13-year-old boy's
feelings about his bar mitzvah, produced by the Jewish Theological
Seminary of America.
   May 14 _ ``America's Children: Poorest in a Land of Plenty,'' a
study of seven families to dispel stereotypes about poverty,
produced by the National Council of Churches.
   June 4 _ ``The Energies of Love,'' profiles of selfless people
across the country, pointing up the values of altruistic giving,
produced by the U.S. Catholic Conference.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TAIZE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ecumenical monastic community of Taize
says it is sending 1 million pocket-size New Testaments to the
Soviet Union for free distribution through the Russian Orthodox
Church.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Back from talks with Soviet officials, the
president of the World Jewish Congress says major changes in Soviet
policy have opened a ``window of opportunity'' for strengthening
Jewish life there.
   Edgar M. Bronfman says there has been ``a sharp and continuing
rise in the number of Jews permitted to emigrate, the backlog of
longtime refuseniks has been all but eliminated'' and Jewish
prisoners ``have all been freed.
   ``Equally important are the new opportunity to practice the
Jewish faith and express Jewish culture that the Soviet regime has
recently made possible.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's proclaiming of a National
Day of Prayer and Thanksgiving on Jan. 22, the Sunday after his
inauguration, was protested by an atheist group, the Freedom From
Religion Foundation.
   It said the action entangled church and state and he had no
authority for such a religious step. ``You have been elected
president, not pope,'' the organization said.
   Such special days of prayer have been proclaimed by most
presidents since George Washington.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen United Methodist bishops from
the United States, East Germany and the Philippines were on a
``mission for peace'' this week in Nicaragua.
   Sponsored by the United Methodist Council of Bishops and the
Council of Bishops of Evangelical Methodist Churches in Latin
America, the visit sought these objectives:
   ``To witness the call of Jesus Christ for peace, justice, freedom
and self-deterimination'' and ``to be in solidarity with the people
of Nicaragua and Central America.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GARRISON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mutual efforts ``are bringing our separated
churches to fuller unity in Christ,'' says a joint interchurch
statement in connection with observance Jan. 18-24 of the annual
Week of Prayer for Christian unity.
   In ``our rich diversity we are individually members of one
another,'' said Archbishop John L. May, president of the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops, and the Rev. Patricia McClurg,
president of the National Council of Churches.
   They cite Scripture from Romans 12 saying, ``We, though many, are
one body in Christ and individually members of one another. Having
gifts that differ according to the grace given us, let us use them.
...''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, Jan. 27</NOTE>
