<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv26   01-26 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 26,0814</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thurs Jan. 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>Some Ideas For Increasing Savings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frustration and lamentation long have been
associated with the low personal savings rate in America, and the
latest to join the crowd is Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal
Reserve Board.
   Speaking before the House Banking Committee, the erudite analyst
of all things economic, confessed that in at least one area he was
baffled. He too, he said, had little idea of how to get people to
save more.
   But there are plenty of savings ideas floating around, and some
of them might work. But just as importantly, there are many ideas
about the savings rate that say it isn't nearly as low as a lot of
folks think it is.
   Statistically speaking, the U.S. rate is low. During the period
from 1947 to 1981 it averaged 4.8 percent of gross national product.
From 1982 to 1987 it averaged 3.7 percent. But the trend may have
reversed.
   More recent figures indicate that in the first half of 1988 the
rate averaged 4.1 percent, up from 3.2 percent in 1987. In that time
it reached a low of 1.8 percent in August 1987 and a high of 4.3
percent in June 1988.
   How do these numbers compare with other nations? Terribly.
Japan's personal savings rate, for example, is sometimes higher than
20 percent. Several other nations are near or close to double
digits. The United States is near bottom.
   But hold on! Do these statistics really say that Americans are
unable or unwilling to save? Maybe not.
   Among the more effective critics of the low-savings theory is
Edward Yardeni, an individualist among a fraternity of like
thinkers. Let us not forget the baby boomers, says Yardeni,
Prudential-Bache director of economics.
   Yardeni maintains that much of the lowered savings rate is a
result of the bulge of young people working its way through the
economy. He observes that the baby boomers _ born after World War II
_ have been in the expensive period of life, financing housing,
furniture, babies, education, cars and the like.
   Baby boomers, he points out, now are becoming couch potatoes.
They are retiring from the spending mode and entering a slacker,
more reflective time of life. Figuratively, they are sitting on the
couch watching television.
   As a result, Yardeni bravely forecasts a sharp rise in the
savings rate from 4 percent or so to 10 percent over the next five
years.
   Paul Craig Roberts, the assistant secretary of the Treasury for
economic policy under President Reagan who now is chairman of the
Institute for Policy Economy, not only cites Yardeni's thesis but
adds other evidence.
   A methodological quirk, for example, is involved in the low
savings rate. Says Roberts: ``In computing GNP, rental values are
imputed to housing and counted as consumption whether the housing is
owned or rented by occupant,''
   Any time, therefore, that there is a demographic bulge of
household-forming young adults, the ``consumption'' of housing will
rise relative to disposable income. But, in a practical sense,
buying a house helps more people put more money away for future use
than any other tool conceived by mankind.
   But are there ways to raise the savings rate as measured
traditionally? Of course _ through incentives. An important
incentive, the Individual Retirement Account, already exists,
although badly watered down.
   A possible incentive could be engineered through a change in the
tax laws that would reduce the amount of taxes on interest earned.
All interest on savings is now subject to taxes. There is a
disincentive to save.
   Various proposals have been made to allow freedom from taxes for
the first few thousand dollars in savings accounts. Other proposals
would include an expansion of IRAs, on which taxes are deferred
until retirement age, to include money saved for meeting education
expenses or the down payment on a house.
   Why not? Isn't education an investment for the national good?
Isn't a fully-owned house one of the best retirement insurance
programs in existence?
   While he expressed concern over his inability to conceive ways to
raise savings rates, Greenspan already is doing something about it.
In seeking to keep inflation restrained, he is restoring faith in
the importance of saving.
   That faith was shattered in the 1970s, and many people will never
forget it. While savers lent their money to banks for as little as
5.25 percent interest in passbook accounts, raging inflation cut the
buying power of those savings to a fraction.
   Those who borrowed prospered because they repaid in cheaper
dollars. Those who saved financed the new wealth of borrowers while
going broke themselves. It takes time to forget.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs., Jan. 26.</NOTE>
</DOC>
