<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1431EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv27   01-26 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 27,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Friday, Jan. 27</HEAD>
<HEAD>So Much For Self-Regulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Among the less obvious victims of the wholesale
shenanigans in the securities and commodities marketplaces is the
treasured and fragile concept of self-regulation.
   Millions of Americans are asking themselves these days if it
works _ ``it'' being the belief that buyers, sellers and their
agents, and the general public too, are served best if those who run
the markets also police them.
   Hoping to retain freedom from outside interference, all major
securities and commodity exchanges study trading patterns and other
activities for violations of standards, such as price-rigging,
collusion and misinformation.
   Offenders are fined, suspended from exchanges, banned from
trading and, if required, reported to law officers for possible
prosecution. Most of those caught are relatively little fish; their
ill-fortune hardly roils the waters.
   In recent months, however, some of the biggest fish since the
1930s have been turning up in the nets, not of the self-regulators
but of the Federal Bureau of Investigation. And the violations seem
more pervasive than isolated.
   The government's investigation of futures trading and the
possible routine cheating of customers at the Chicago Board of Trade
and Chicago Mercantile Exchange, suggests how ineffective
self-policing might have become.
   So well-known were certain questionable futures trading
practices, and so often were they criticized publicly within and
outside the exchanges, that the FBI found reasons to act where the
self-policers had been, if not idle, then ineffective.
   The actions of the Mercantile Exchange following the issuance of
subpoenas, illustrates how unaggressive and impotent self-policing
appears to have become.
   After acknowledging that the exchange itself had studied
activities in the so-called ``yen pit,'' where trades involving the
Japanese yen were conducted, Leo Melamed, chairman of the exchange's
executive committee, stated:
   ``I don't think we could have done any better. The practices and
the way we conduct business gives the opportunity for a violation.
No one watching, just standing there, could have done anything.''
   The Feds did do something. They infiltrated trading pits,
recorded deals being made, observed what they believed to have been
fraud, gathered names, established a grand jury to hear evidence and
arranged for subpoenas.
   The Mercantile Exchange then acted, appointing a 10-member panel
to review trading procedures, a move similar to that made following
accusations that futures trading practices helped worsen the stock
market crash of 1987.
   There would be no sacred cows in its own investigation, said
Melamed. ``We've got to change the rules so even (the) few can't do
anything dishonest with a public order,'' he declared.
   What matters, he said, ``is that we use this opportunity to act
responsibly and make improvements where they are necessary.''
   The exchange-appointed panel that studied the impact of futures
trading in the stock market crash of October 1987 tended to
exonerate the exchange, suggesting instead that it was a bulwark
against even further damage.
   There seems little likelihood that the current panel cannot
suggest changes in trading practices that would allow better
surveillance, improve recording of transactions and eliminate the
confusing, fish market-like pit procedures.
   But whatever corrections emerge from what appears to be another
public trading debacle _ others involve misuse of inside stock
information, trading conspiracies, collusion and the like _ public
confidence has been shaken.
   The entire concept of self-regulation has been put on trial, as
it was in the 1930s, when it was demonstrated that the policemen not
only had reneged on their responsibilities but had used their
authority to mask their misdeeds.
   Those earlier shenanigans resulted in more government regulation.
It took years for the industry to recapture a degree of self-control
and public trust, which it requires if its practitioners are to make
the good living it affords.
   Now the fear exists that they might have tossed it away again,
and with it the entire notion that free markets operate most
efficiently when governmental interference is held to a minimum.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday, Jan. 27.</NOTE>
</DOC>
