<DOCNO> AP890126-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 0524EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Britain-Theater Adv30   01-26 0870</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Britain-Theater, Adv 30,0891</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, Jan 30 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>New York Shows Invade London</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's beginning to look like Broadway in Britain as
New York shows hit London in a reversal of the usual westward flow.
   No fewer than 10 recent New York productions are now running in
London or will open shortly, including some that failed financially
in the United States, and others that might seem unlikely candidates
for British transfers.
   American plays and musicals have always been featured on the
London stage, from Arthur Miller plays, some of which are now
running, to musical revivals such as the current ``Brigadoon'' and
the recently closed ``South Pacific'' and ``Can-Can.''
   But what's surprising about the rest of the American lineup is
its specific resemblance to that of New York's current fare. Among
American shows already running are the off-Broadway musical ``Three
Guys Naked From the Waist Down'' at the Donmar Warehouse; David
Mamet's Broadway hit ``Speed-the-Plow'' at the government-subsidized
National; and the two-character ``A Walk in the Woods,'' at the
Comedy, which ended its commercially unsuccessful Broadway run last
June.
   Soon to arrive are stand-up comic Jackie Mason's solo show, ``The
World According to Me,'' which starts its six-week run Feb. 15 at
the Playhouse; the satiric revue ``Forbidden Broadway,'' opening
March 2 at the Fortune and subtitled ``The West End Edition''; and
Robert Harling's ``Steel Magnolias,'' due March 7 at the Lyric.
   Add the spring premieres of ``M. Butterfly,'' ``Frankie and
Johnny in the Clair de Lune'' and Jerry Zaks' spirited revival of
``Anything Goes,'' and clearly what plays in New York is
increasingly deemed a safe bet to play in London.
   Mason appeared to prove the point in November when his brief
appearance on the annual Royal Variety Show won universal critical
acclaim. Until then New York Jewish shtick invariably bombed in
Britain.
   Part of the sudden interest in American productions is that they
fill the gap left by those British playwrights who are either
writing less frequently or have switched to other media.
   In shopping for products, creators and producers emphasize that
their work transcends parochial, national boundaries.
   ``I'm doing `Steel Magnolias' because I think this is a
particular play that's universal,'' said David Pugh, who is
producing the British debut of the long-running off-Broadway hit set
in a Louisiana beauty parlor.
   Directed by actress Julia McKenzie, the comedy will star
British-born Rosemary Harris, a Broadway regular, and Joely
Richardson, the younger of Vanessa Redgrave's two thespian daughters.
   ``It happens to be as relevant in Stoke-on-Trent as it is in
Louisiana,'' said Pugh, who in 1987 co-produced Lyle Kessler's
``Orphans,'' an earlier London production of an American play and
one which closed at a deficit.
   In the case of ``Speed-the-Plow,'' David Mamet is seen as an
international writer who merits inclusion in the repertory of any
major theater.
   ``He has very much been a writer for the National,'' said David
Aukin, executive director of the theater where the author's Pulitzer
Prize-winning ``Glengarry Glen Ross'' had its world premiere in 1983.
   ``Speed-the-Plow,'' which starred Ron Silver, Joe Mantegna and
rock singer Madonna who was roasted by critics, opens Jan. 25 with a
mixed Canadian and British cast.
   American writers, in turn, enjoy the prestige of a London run.
Terrence McNally, whose ``Frankie and Johnny in the Clair de Lune''
is in its second year off-Broadway, said he was as excited about
that play's London opening in May as he would be if it were the New
York debut.
   The London production's two-character cast consists of Britons
Brian Cox and Julie Walters, who was Rita in ``Educating Rita.''
   ``London is very special to me; it's not just another
engagement,'' McNally, 49, said by telephone from New York,
dismissing worries that a romance set in Hell's Kitchen might be too
American to travel.
   ``I can't worry about that when I write,'' he said. Shows work
when you're very specific. It's when you try to appeal to everybody
that you get into trouble.
   McNally's musical ``The Rink'' flopped in London last year as it
had earlier on Broadway.
   The fate of ``The Rink'' and ``Orphans'' indicates that London
productions aren't always the money-makers dreamed of by scarred
veterans of New York's hit-flop mentality.
   Neither ``Follies,'' the 1971 Stephen Sondheim musical which ends
its debut London engagement Feb. 4, nor ``Driving Miss Daisy,'' the
Alfred Uhry comedy which finished six months on the West End last
November, fully recouped its investment. But the West End's lower
costs are appealing. Both ``Steel Magnolias'' and ``Forbidden
Broadway: The West End Edition'' cost 200,000 pounds ($375,000
dollars), equal to or less than the price of today's average
off-Broadway show.
   The theatrical traffic is not, of course, entirely one way.
   ``Shirley Valentine,'' the one-woman play by Liverpudlian Willy
Russell, opens at Broadway's Booth Theater on Feb. 16.
   Such London hits as ``Lend Me a Tenor'' (written by an American)
and ``Run For Your Wife'' open in March on Broadway, and Peter
Shaffer's much-awaited ``Lettice and Lovage'' has been postponed for
Broadway until next season because its star, Maggie Smith, has
broken a shoulder.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Jan. 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890126-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w AM-Ex-SenatorMelcher Adv31   01-26 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ex-Senator Melcher, Adv31,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv31</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues AMs, Jan 31, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Defeated Montana Senator Settles Into New Role as Lobbyist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was just like old times when John Melcher
got together with agribusiness consultant Martin Sorkin for lunch at
the Watergate the other day.
   With one glaring exception.
   ``I told him that this time I would pay, and I did, indeed,
pay,'' confesses the 64-year-old Democrat, who last November lost
his bid for a third Senate term from Montana.
   Gone are the days when Melcher, an affable, white-haired
veterinarian known as ``Doc,'' could assume that the lunch tab would
be picked up by someone else.
   ``They used to call me,'' says the Democratic veteran of 12 years
in the House and seven in the Senate. ``Now I call them.''
   It was a close election. A turnaround of 7,000 votes would have
given Melcher a new, six-year lease on his Senate office.
   But Melcher ran into a GOP challenger, Conrad Burns, who was a
popular farm broadcaster at a time when his own base in the Grain
Belt was getting shaky after four years of drought and unpopular
policies blamed on Washington.
   Television ads featuring talking cows that boosted Melcher in
1982 proved a bust this time in a state anxious to shed its bucolic
image and spotlight an above-average education level as a means to
lure new, high-tech industries.
   Melcher also declares ruefully that he played into Republican
hands in dealing with a sensitive bill to preserve Montana
wilderness areas. He ended up losing support among both
conservations and the lumber industry.
   When the election was over, so was Melcher's congressional
career. His colleagues gave him a loyal sendoff.
   ``He has protected the rights of farmers in Montana and fought
for fairness in public power systems,'' declared Sen. Christopher
Dodd, D-Conn., in a farewell to Melcher from the Senate floor.
   Fast Eddie and Abigail, a pair of cats that had romped through
his office at will in happier times, also had to go. An aide took
one and the senator himself bundled the other into his car and took
it to live in his suburban Maryland home.
   Then Melcher sat down to write letters and make phone calls on
behalf of aides already looking for new jobs. About half are now
employed while others are still hunting or have decided the time has
come to retire.
   Melcher himself is not planning to retire and there are two
reasons why.
   ``I have to earn some money,'' he says. ``I can live off my
retirement in Montana but if I want to stay here I've got to do
something.''
   Moving back to Montana, he says, would provide him with a more
pleasant place to live. But that would mean saying goodbye to the
issues that he has been campaigning for over almost two decades.
That is the second reason why he refuses to retire.
   Working off a borrowed desk in a downtown law firm, Melcher is
offering his services as a consultant on those issues. That is, as a
lobbyist.
   ``Well, call it what you may,'' he says, ``I think we have a
tendency to say consult but it's lobbying.''
   In that, Melcher is like scores of former lawmakers who stay on
in Washington after they retire or lose elections _ they move into
downtown suites and earn their living as hired guns in the
never-ending battle of Gucci Gulch.
   Senate rules designed to head off conflicts of interest bar
Melcher from contacting his former Senate colleagues about bills for
one year. But he is free to testify when their committees hold
hearings on bills. And he is free to ply the corridors of the
Agriculture Department on behalf of clients.
   Melcher already has one client, the Society for Animal Protection
Legislation.
   ``I have a profound interest in the well-being of primates that
are used in medical experiments,'' says Melcher. He says they
deserve decent surroundings and the company of their fellow
creatures.
   A broader plan Melcher is working on would establish a coalition
to fight potential cuts in the Food for Peace program, an
Agriculture Department export subsidy designed to give grain
companies an incentive to provide food for the hungry people of the
world.
   ``Those are the two items I'm working on now,'' says Melcher, who
pauses to reflect for a moment, then adds, ``I'm open to others.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues AMs, Jan 31</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
