<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 0150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     01-26 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0813</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Business Highlights now runs in one take.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. will fire its
embattled junk bond chief Michael R. Milken as part of a record $650
million plea bargain with federal prosecutors in the nation's
largest securities fraud investigation, court papers show.
   The 12-page agreement released Wednesday also specifies that
Drexel will not pay Milken, head of the firm's Beverly Hills,
Calif.-based high yield ``junk'' bond department any of his expected
multimillion dollar compensation for 1988.
   Milken was named along with Drexel in a Securities and Exchange
Commission insider trading civil lawsuit in September.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says he hopes the Federal
Reserve Board's concern about inflation won't lead the central bank
to stifle economic growth by driving up interest rates.
   Bush said Wednesday he believes the economy is ``reasonably
stable,'' adding, ``There's no signals out there in the markets that
this economy is in real trouble.''
   The president's comments came one day after Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan told a House committee that the central bank
is likely to keep a tight grip on the money supply to control
inflation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange announced creation
of a special panel to strengthen control over floor transactions as
a federal grand jury convened to probe allegations of fraud in the
financial futures industry.
   The panel, created Wednesday to review trading procedures and
practices and recommend changes where necessary, is made up of five
industry officials and five former or current public officials,
among them former Sen. Thomas Eagleton of Missouri.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says his administration is
considering charging depositors to help pay for the savings and loan
crisis, but members of his own party in Congress quickly stuck a pin
in the trial balloon.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady said Wednesday a proposal
under review by his department would impose an insurance fee of 25
cents for every $100 in deposits. But he stressed that the option
has not been forwarded yet to Bush.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government reported an $11.6
billion budget deficit for December, as red ink was held to less
than half the level of a year earlier thanks to a shift in the
payment date for Social Security checks.
   The Treasury Department reported Wednesday receiving $93.8
billion in revenues last month, up 9.7 percent from the same period
a year earlier. Spending, meanwhile, was down 4.1 percent from
December 1987 to $105.4 billion. The December 1987 deficit had been
$24.4 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials from OPEC and independent oil-producing
nations huddled separately to plot strategy for today's joint
meeting over cooperation in supporting crude oil prices.
   The independent group indicated support Wednesday for OPEC's
attempt to limit production and stated both producer and consumer
nations would be served by stabilizing prices.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing single-family homes last year
hit their highest level since 1979 as buyers shopped in lower price
ranges rather than leave the market when costs rose, a real estate
trade group said.
   The National Association of Realtors said Wednesday that 3.63
million homes were sold in 1988, up 2.9 percent from 1987 when 3.53
million homes had been sold. It was the highest sales volume since
3.83 million homes were sold in 1979.
