<DOCNO> AP890126-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 0157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel-Milken Bjt   01-26 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel-Milken, Bjt,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fired Trader Was Architect of Firm's Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drexel Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Milken was the engine that
propelled Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. up through the ranks of the
securities business, but the junk bond trader may have become excess
baggage.
   Drexel revealed Wednesday it will fire Milken as part of a record
$650 million plea bargain with federal prosecutors who charged the
Wall Street firm with securities fraud.
   The junk bond market Milken nurtured through a decade is crucial
to Drexel's profitability, but it was unclear how Milken's departure
would affect the firm's role in the market.
   And in one very real sense, jettisoning the chief of the Beverly
Hills-based division Drexel refers to as the high-yield bond unit
helps the firm out of its present straits: The plea agreement calls
for the firm to withhold Milken's 1988 salary and bonuses, which, at
an estimated $200 million, is enough to pay a sizeable chunk of the
fine.
   The Los Angeles-born trader is widely credited with
single-handedly persuading investors that there was gold in
high-yield, high-risk bonds issued by companies too small or too
weak to earn the endorsement of bond-rating firms. He preached the
idea that a junk bond investor could earn high interest and protect
himself from potential default of one company by holding a portfolio
of bonds in a number of companies.
   Drexel made millions as the dominant firm in the junk bond
market, which has funded corporate raiders and struggling
entrepreneurs alike.
   Milken, who got the firm to allow him to set up shop in
California, was said to control a network of investors. Often, a
businessman who had financed his dreams by selling junk bonds became
a ready buyer for another company's bonds when pitched by Milken.
   But there are indications his role as the indispensable engine of
the junk bond market _ and so his value to Drexel _ has diminished.
   By some accounts, Milken has spent little time in his Beverly
Hills office during the two years it was publicly known Drexel was a
target of federal fraud investigations.
   Yet despite inroads made by other firms, Drexel has remained the
acknowledged leader in the junk bond market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890126-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 0158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Boeing-Condit Bjt   01-26 0722</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing-Condit, Bjt,0740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing's Schedule For New 747 May Have Been Too Ambitious, Exec Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENTON, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing Co. may have been too ambitious
in its schedule for introducing its new 747-400 jumbo jet, a top
Boeing Commercial Airplanes executive says.
   ``The expression that `hindsight is perfect' applies. You can
always look back and see things you could do better,'' Phil Condit,
the Boeing division's executive vice president for engineering and
production, said Wednesday in an interview.
   Boeing had hoped to get the first of the new planes to customers
by late last year. But a series of glitches has delayed the delivery
schedule three times, and increasingly impatient customers still
haven't got the initial planes.
   In bringing out the 747-400, the world's largest commercial
jetliner, Boeing, in effect, was introducing four aircraft models
simultaneously, Condit said. Some 21 operators have ordered 166 of
the new planes, which will be capable of carrying 412 passengers
more than 8,000 miles nonstop.
   The plane can be ordered with one of three different types of
engines, and in a combination freight-passenger configuration. Each
variation had to be certified with the Federal Avation
Administration. In addition, Condit said, each of the customers
signed up for the planes wants the jets customized.
   ``That's a big, complex task,'' Condit said. ``If I had it to do
over again, I would have spread some of that out.''
   Condit is meeting with groups of reporters this week to answer
questions about Boeing production delays and recent troubles that
have plagued Boeing aircraft.
   Among incidents in recent weeks, an older Eastern 737 made an
unscheduled landing after losing cabin pressure from a fuselage
hole; a new British Midlands 737-400 crashed in Great Britain after
one engine failed and another was shut off; an engine fell off a
Piedmont 737-200, which landed safely in Chicago; and a wing panel
came off an Eastern 757.
   In addition, the FAA ordered checks for possible cross-wiring in
cargo hold fire extinguishers on 757s and 767s. Eight instances of
cross-wiring were found on 757s, the latest last week on a plane
owned by the Mexican government, but none have been found so far on
the 767 widebodies.
   Boeing said Tuesday that inspections had been completed on 98
percent of the world's fleet of 479 737-300s and 16 737-400s, and no
wiring problems had been found. The checks were ordered as a
precaution after it was speculated that cross-wired engines might
have contributed to the British Midlands crash.
   ``What we have had is a set of very unrelated incidents. They
flat aren't connected at all, except by one thing and that's time,''
Condit said.
   In October, Boeing told its 747-400 customers that wiring
problems would delay deliveries of the first 20 or so jets, but the
schedule would be back on track early in 1989. A second delay
occurred in December, when it took longer than expected for the FAA
to certify the planes. Last week, Boeing again said it was
re-examining its delivery schedule, and would tell customers by the
end of January when to expect their planes.
   Condit refused to say what the revised schedule would be, or
whether some deliveries would be bumped from 1989 to 1990, saying
Boeing would be contacting its customers this week so they could
know first. Boeing's annual earnings report will be out Monday, and
it will contain an estimate of 1989 aircraft delivery levels, he
said.
   Boeing last week also completed a five-day ``readjustment'' of
Boeing's 747-400 line, to catch up work and get it back in sequence.
Condit said a similar three-day readjustment took place in October,
and in December, some employees worked on the plane through their
Christmas break.
   ``We've started out on a new, very large, complex program,''
Condit said. ``While you'd like every program to go perfectly, when
you do big programs they don't all go perfectly. We've had some part
shortages, we have some work that got out of sequence.''
   Asked whether Boeing's credibility was hurt by its troubles,
Condit said no.
   ``The airlines themselves understand the process. The
fundamentals of this business is, one, it's very visible, and two,
whatever happens, you set out to go fix it. I think that's Boeing's
record ... When you have a problem, go fix it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
