<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was little changed in light European
trading early today amid fears that central banks might intervene to
stop the currency from rising.
   Gold prices were higher.
   Dealers said a round of dollar-selling late Wednesday by the
Federal Reserve Board and the French central bank, which again cut
short a modest rally, had temporarily confused the market.
   ``Even though there's still commercial demand for dollars, taking
on the central banks doesn't seem like a very good idea right now,''
said a trader at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt, West Germany.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.13 Japanese yen to a closing 127.52 yen. Later, in
London, it rose back up to 128.00 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.8435 West German marks, unchanged; 1.5680 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5670; 6.2755 French francs, up from 6.2715; 2.0820
Dutch guilders, unchanged; 1,348.75 Italian lire, down from
1,350.50; 1.1834 Canadian, down from 1.1840.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7730 from $1.7710 late
Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $406.25 a troy ounce, up
from $404.25 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $406.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $406.10, up from $404.25 bid
late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.13 to close at a bid $407.70.
Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $6.20 a troy ounce,
up from $6.12 bid late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
