<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     01-26 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off Slightly, Tokyo Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar declined slightly today against the
Japanese yen, and the Tokyo Stock Exchange's leading index fell back
from its record high of the previous day.
   Dealers said the foreign exchange and stock markets both were
affected by Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita's comment
Wednesday that the central bank might take early action, if
necessary, to curb inflation in Japan. This was taken as a hint of
higher interest rates.
   The dollar closed at 127.52 yen, down 0.13 yen from Wednesday's
close of 127.65 yen. After opening at 127.37, it stayed in a narrow
range between 127.30 yen and 127.60 yen in relatively quiet trading.
   ``Gov. Sumita's comment and (the U.S. Federal Reserve Board's)
intervention (to check the dollar's rise) discouraged players from
actively buying the dollar,'' said a dealer at a major bank in
Tokyo. ``Players were also worried about intervention by the Bank of
Japan.''
   Higher interest rates in Japan would make the yen more attractive
to investors.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues lost 55.98 points, or 0.18 percent, closing at 31,511.81,
following a record high close of 31,567.79 on Wednesday.
   Securities dealers said a bearish mood persisted in the stock
market throughout the day because of investors' fears of an interest
rate hike.
   ``Trading was slow and not many shares were moving actively on
the trading board today except automobile shares,'' said a dealer at
Nikko Securities Co., speaking on condition of anonymity.
``Profit-taking activities were also notable today. That probably
pushed most shares down.''
   He added, ``The market only took a brief relief today, but I
think the market environment is still favorable for most stocks.''
</TEXT>
