<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 0802EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BudgetDeficit Bjt   01-26 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget Deficit, Bjt,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artificial Relief for Budget Deficit in December</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A temporary shift in the payment of Social
Security benefits held last month's budget deficit to less than half
the level of a year earlier but economists still expect the
shortfall for fiscal 1989 to exceed last year's level.
   December's deficit was $11.6 billion, down from $24.4 billion in
the same month a year earlier, the Treasury Department reported
Wednesday. For the first three months of fiscal 1989, which began
Oct. 1, the budget gap was $67.7 billion, down 17.8 percent from the
same period a year earlier.
   Michael K. Evans, an economic consultant in Washington,
attributed the improvement to an ``end of the year fluke'' in which
Social Security checks that normally would have been mailed out in
January 1988 went out at the end of the previous month, artificially
inflating the deficit for December 1987.
   The fiscal 1989 deficit actually is running about as expected,
and should exceed last year's $155 billion shortfall by about $10
billion, Evans said.
   While the deficit is expected to continue to grow in fiscal 1989,
with President Bush unlikely to tame it, the shortfall shouldn't
hinder economic growth, Evans said.
   ``It's just not going to affect the economy,'' he said. ``I don't
see this as a disaster.''
   The Reagan administration, in its final budget proposal this
month, projected a $161.5 billion deficit for fiscal 1989. The
Congressional Budget Office, meanwhile, forecasts a $141 billion
shortfall.
   Bush plans to detail his administration's priorities in an
address to Congress on Feb. 9 and to unveil his budget proposals
shortly thereafter.
   Economists are forecasting slower growth in the second half of
1989, and rising interest rates early in the year, both of which
hinder efforts to reduce the deficit. Weak growth slows tax
collections, while higher interest rates force the government to
spend more to finance the $2.7 trillion national debt.
   As usual, the largest spending categories in December were the
military, Social Security, other programs in the Department of
Health and Human Services, interest on the national debt and farm
subsidies.
   Military spending totaled $28.2 billion last month and $77.3
billion for the past three months, up 4 percent from the same period
a year earlier.
   Interest on the national debt totaled $35 billion in December and
$68.3 billion for the first three months of the fiscal year, up 11.7
percent from a year earlier.
   Spending for Social Security was $18.8 billion during December
and $54.6 billion for the first three months of fiscal 1989, down
20.9 percent from a year earlier because of the shift in payment
dates.
   Other HHS programs, including Medicare and Medicaid, cost $14.7
billion in December and $40 billion so far in the fiscal year, up 6
percent from the same period in fiscal 1988.
   Spending by the Agriculture Department totaled $4.9 billion in
December and $16 billion for the first three months of fiscal 1989,
down 3.9 percent from the previous year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
