<FIRST>r f PM-SkinnerConfirmation     01-26 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Skinner Confirmation,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skinner Headed for Confirmation as Transportation Secretary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Samuel K. Skinner, one of the few Washington
outsiders named to President Bush's Cabinet, is headed toward
confirmation as transportation secretary after squelching a lone
objection to his nomination.
   The former U.S. attorney, who is an active pilot and administers
the nation's second-largest mass transit system, testified for 2{
hours Wednesday before the Senate Commerce Committee. The Chicago
resident pledged support for mandatory drug testing, a battle
against air terrorists and promotion of competition in the nation's
air, sea and land transportation.
   Committee chairman Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., said he was
keeping the hearing record open until noon today for further comment
but said he expected approval when the committee meets to vote on
the nomination next Tuesday. A full Senate vote would follow.
   ``I don't think you'll have any trouble next Tuesday morning,''
Hollings told Skinner, 50, at the end of the hearing. ``You've done
a superb job. You're a breath of fresh air.''
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, had tried to delay the
confirmation hearing over questions about Skinner's actions as a
U.S. attorney in Chicago in 1977, but withdrew his objection after
speaking with Skinner.
   In his testimony, Skinner said he would fight for fairness for
U.S. airlines abroad even if it put him at odds with the State
Department.
   ``I think we've got a right to compete in the world on an equal
basis,'' he said, when asked about the difficulty encountered by
U.S. airlines seeking access to some airports abroad, including
Tokyo, even after diplomatic agreements are concluded.
   ``I'm not going to take a back seat,'' Skinner said.
   Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., applauded Skinner's intention not to
take orders from the State Department, saying, ``Don't let them
shove you around.''
   ``It may be a little naive, but that's the position we're going
to take,'' said Skinner, although he also called himself ``a team
player'' and said he would work with Secretary of State-designate
James Baker.
   Skinner said he supports random drug tests for transportation
workers, pledged to battle drunken driving, promised to help build
up the Coast Guard and the maritime industry, and announced he would
draw up a long-range national transportation policy.
   Several committee members urged that the government continue to
subsidize air service to small airports that deregulated carriers
otherwise might abandon. Skinner pledged to work with Congress and
said it would be foolish for the Transportation Department to end
the service and then be forced to restore it.
   No committee member raised an objection to the nomination or
strongly questioned any of Skinner's statements.
   Metzenbaum had questioned Skinner's failure as a prosecutor in
1977 to prosecute G.D. Searle Co. on allegations that it falsified
test results on its Nutrasweet artificial sweetener.
   Skinner told the senators the decision not to prosecute was made
by his successor. He acknowledged some minor mistakes as he left
office and joined the law firm that represented Searle, but said he
had nothing to do with the Searle case as a private lawyer.
   Metzenbaum said he was satisfied with the explanation and that he
would vote for Skinner's confirmation.
</TEXT>
