<DOCNO> AP890126-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 0808EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FarmScene     01-26 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets May Buy Record Grain This Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has given the go-ahead to the
Soviet Union for buying more U.S. grain this year, including
subsidized wheat, raising the possibility that total sales might
exceed the record level of four years ago.
   Agriculture Department officials said Wednesday the Soviets have
been cleared to buy up to 20 million metric tons of grain in
1988-89, up from the 16 million tons specified earlier. Purchases
already total more than 12 million tons.
   The department also said the Soviets have bought an additional
150,000 tons of soybean meal, which has a potential current market
value of about $36 million.
   Under a long-term grain agreement, the Soviet Union was
originally limited to 12 million tons of U.S. grain a year without
further consultations with Washington, but that was increased to 16
million tons on Dec. 23. The agreement had expired last Sept. 30 but
was later extended.
   Officials said the increase for 1988-89 ``takes into account
recent public confirmation by Soviet authorities'' that the Soviet
Union's grain harvest last year was below expectations.
   In a related development, Acting Undersecretary Richard W.
Goldberg announced that Moscow has been authorized an additional 2
million tons of wheat that it can buy under the department's Export
Enhancement Program, or EEP.
   Earlier this week, for example, the department announced an EEP
wheat sale to the Soviet Union of 635,000 tons, or about 23.3
million bushels. The subsidies shaved $23.05 per ton off the regular
market price, or about 63 cents per bushel.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat.
   The EEP arrangement allows private exporters to sell wheat and
other designated commodities to specified countries at reduced
prices in order to meet foreign competition. The exporters then
collect free government surpluses of grain or other products as
bonuses, or subsidies.
   Only wheat is approved for sale to the Soviet Union under the EEP
subsidy arrangement.
   Sales of wheat and corn now total more than 11.6 million tons for
delivery in the long-term agreement's sixth year, which began last
Oct. 1.
   That comprises about 10.2 million tons of corn and 1.4 million
tons of wheat. In addition, the Soviets have bought 450,000 tons of
soybeans, 1.28 million tons of soybean meal, and 500,000 tons of
grain sorghums.
   Under the agreement, each ton of soybeans or meal counts for two
tons of grain.
   If Moscow buys the full 20 million tons of U.S. grain now
authorized, it would exceed the record level of 18.6 million tons of
1984-85, most of which was corn.
   The current agreement was a 5-year pact that began on Oct. 1,
1983, and then extended last fall through 1990.
   Under the pact, the Soviet Union is committed to buy at least 9
million tons of grain each year, including a minimum of 4 million
tons each of wheat and corn. The remaining 1 million tons can be
wheat, corn, soybeans or soybean meal, or a combination of those
commodities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
