<FIRST>u f PM-DurableGoods Bjt   01-26 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Durable Goods, Bjt,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Orders Jump 6.4 Percent In December</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to factories for ``big ticket'' durable
goods shot up 6.4 percent in December, the biggest increase in six
months, the government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said demand for durable goods, items
expected to last three or more years, totaled a seasonally adjusted
$130.85 billion in December.
   The 6.4 percent jump was the biggest since an 8.7 percent
increase recorded last June. It reflected widespread demand in both
civilian and military categories.
   The December orders figure closed out the year on a strong note,
with orders for the last 12 months totaling $1.43 trillion, a 10.8
percent increase from 1987.
   It was the best showing since a 12.3 percent increase in 1984.
Orders had edged up a slight 1.2 percent in 1985 and 0.4 percent in
1986, two years in which American busineses were losing domestic and
overseas sales to foreign manufacturers.
   American manufacturing enjoyed a rebound in 1987 and 1988 as a
decline in the value of the dollar against foreign currencies made
U.S. products competitive once again on overseas markets.
   Orders in the volatile military category, influenced by when big
government contracts are signed, jumped 21.1 percent in December to
a seasonally adjusted $10.16 billion following a 21.5 percent
decrease in November.
   But even excluding defense, orders for durable goods were up 5.4
percent during the month.
   Orders for non-defense capital goods shot up as well, rising 7.8
percent to $38.6 billion last month. The category is closely watched
for signals of business intentions to expand and modernize.
   December's increase in demand for non-defense capital goods was
the biggest since a 12.5 percent jump in June.
   In another volatile category, transportation orders increased 20
percent in December to $38.9 billion after a 7.2 percent decrease a
month earlier.
   The strength in transportation included large gains in the auto,
aircraft and shipbuilding industries.
   Excluding transportation, the December increase in orders for
durable goods was 1.6 percent.
   In other industries, orders for primary metals rose 5.3 percent
to $13.3 billion, demand for electrical machinery was up 1.1 percent
to $20.3 billion, while orders for non-electrical machinery dropped
3.2 percent to $20.7 billion. Most of the decline in the
non-electrical category was in engines and turbines.
   Shipments of durable goods increased 3.8 percent to $124.46
billion in December, following a 1.2 percent increase in November.
   Shipments for the year totaled $1.39 trillion, up 9.9 percent
from 1987.
</TEXT>
