<HEAD>Factory Orders Jump 6.4 Percent In December</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with report on durable goods. Picks
up 2nd graf pvs, President Bush ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Factory orders for ``big ticket'' durable goods jumped 6.4
percent in December, the biggest increase in six months, the
government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said demand for durable goods, items
expected to last three or more years, totaled a seasonally adjusted
$130.85 billion last month.
   The 6.4 percent rise was the largest since an 8.7 percent
increase recorded last June. It reflected widespread demand in both
civilian and military categories.
   The December figure closed out 1988 on a strong note, with orders
for the 12 months totaling $1.43 trillion, a 10.8 percent increase
from 1987 and the best showing since a 12.3 percent rise in 1984.
   President Bush, meanwhile, said Wednesday he thinks the economy
is ``reasonably stable'' and added, ``There's no signals out there
in the markets that this economy is in real trouble.''
   The president said he was concerned, however, that higher
interest rates could stifle economic growth.
   His remarks came a day after the Federal Reserve Board chairman,
Alan Greenspan, told a congressional panel the central bank is
likely to keep a tight grip on the money supply to control inflation.
   ``I haven't talked to Alan lately, but I don't want to see us
move so strongly against the fear of inflation that we impede
growth,'' Bush said.
   Reporting on the federal budget, the Treasury Department said
Wednesday that the deficit shrank to $11.6 billion for December,
less than half the level of a year earlier thanks to a shift in the
payment date for Social Security checks.
   The Treasury reported receiving $93.8 billion in revenues last
month, up 9.7 percent from the same period a year earlier. Spending,
meanwhile, was down 4.1 percent from December 1987 to $105.4 billion.
   The December 1987 deficit had been $24.4 billion.
   Also Wednesday, the Federal Reserve's 12 district banks reported
stronger economic activity in December and early January, fueled by
strength in retail sales and manufacturing.
   The report, based on surveys conducted by the banks, found little
change in other sectors of the economy. Demand for bank loans was
generally flat; construction work was subdued in most parts of the
country, and continuing dry weather threatened the winter wheat crop
in some areas.
   ``It would appear, on the basis of these reports, that the
national economy gained momentum in recent weeks as consumer
spending strengthened, manufacturing activity continued to rise and
producers scheduled more investment in plant and equipment,'' said
the report.
   And a real estate trade group said sales of existing
single-family homes last year hit their highest level since 1979 as
buyers shopped in lower price ranges rather than leave the market
when costs rose.
   The National Association of Realtors said 3.63 million homes were
sold in 1988, up 2.9 percent from 1987 when 3.53 million homes had
been sold. It was the highest sales volume since 3.83 million homes
were sold in 1979.
</TEXT>
