<FIRST>r f PM-Motorola-Hitachi     01-26 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Motorola-Hitachi,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hitachi Files Lawsuit in Patent Infringement Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle of the microprocessors is continuing,
this time with a federal patent infringement lawsuit filed by
Hitachi Ltd. against Motorola Inc. of Schaumburg.
   The lawsuit filed Wednesday in U.S. District court came a week
after a similar lawsuit filed by Motorola against Hitachi.
   The dispute centers on Motorola's 68HC11 and Hitachi's H-8
microprocessors, the digital electronic devices that perform the
control and arithmetic functions of televisions, watches,
videorecorders and other products.
   ``We want unspecified monetary damages and an injunction to stop
the sale and use of their unit,'' said attorney Jon Nelson, who
filed the lawsuit on behalf of Hitachi, a Japanese company whose
U.S. subsidiary is based in Tarrytown, N.Y.
   ``I wouldn't characterize it as as a countersuit,'' Nelson said.
   Motorola, however, called the action an ``expected countermove.''
   ``Motorola expects that the suit will either be withdrawn or
disposed of summarily,'' the company said.
   Motorola's lawsuit, filed Jan. 18, says the Hitachi H-8 series
infringes on at least four Motorola patents. The company is seeking
monetary damages and an injunction.
   Company spokesman Tim Kellogg said Motorola had granted patent
licenses concerning use of microprocessing technology over a 10-year
period without previous problems.
   Both sides opened negotiations in October, but there was no
resolution and Motorola started legal action last week.
</TEXT>
