<FIRST>u f PM-CommoditiesProbe 1stLd-Writethru f0017 01-26 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0017,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merc Says It Will Clean Own House; Report Says Agents Still Undercover</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with 2 grafs after 9th graf, ``Sources told ...'' with
report of probe into money laundering; picks up 10th graf pvs, ``During
the ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange have
promised that there will be ``no sacred cows'' when they review
their rules in response to a federal investigation of suspected
fraud in the financial futures market.
   ``We've got to change the rules so even (the) few can't do
anything dishonest with a public order,'' said Leo Melamed, chief
counsel at the Merc and one of its most powerful figures.
   The exchange announced Wednesday it was forming a 10-member panel
to review trading procedures in the wake of the FBI undercover
investigation, known as Operation Sourmash.
   The announcement came as a grand jury convened to hear
prosecutors present evidence in the case, which involves floor
dealings at the Chicago Board of Trade and the Merc _ the world's
largest-volume futures exchanges.
   Although trading activity reflected a business-as-usual
atmosphere at both exchanges, traders admitted to some nervousness.
   ``People say, `Buy the rumor, sell the news,''' said a currency
trader at the Merc who declined to be identified. ``Nobody feels
like they can differentiate between the two any more.''
   The Chicago Tribune, citing unidentified sources, reported today
that the FBI has kept two undercover agents on the trading floors of
the exchanges in a highly unusual move to record traders reacting to
waves of subpoenas.
   The agents have been posing as clerks or messengers to document
statements as traders swap tales of earlier encounters with the FBI
or discuss how to respond to hundreds of subpoenas issused since the
scandal broke last week, the Tribune said.
   Sources told the newspaper that prosecutors are interested in
getting evidence of obstruction of justice.
   The Chicago Sun-Times reported today that part of the
investigation has focused on money laundering through the exchanges.
   Citing federal sources it did not name, the newspaper said an FBI
agent posing as a trader told a real trader he had a ``very
sizeable'' amount of cash he could not report to the goverment and
asked for records showing the money came from trading profits. The
trader agreed, the newspaper said.
   During the investigation, which became public a week ago today,
FBI undercover agents posed as traders, and published reports said
other traders agreed to wear recording devices after confronted by
authorities with evidence of wrongdoing.
   The Tribune today said Operation Sourmash was planned as early as
1984.
   Although federal marshals sealed off the 16th floor of the
downtown Everett Dirksen Federal Building, which in the past has
been used for grand jury testimony, U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas, in
keeping with office policy, declined even to confirm that an
investigation was under way.
   But the Merc's announcement of the creation of the special panel
said improvements in practices and procedures may be necessary ``in
the wake of revelations of a federal investigation.''
   ``It matters not whether this (federal) investigation involves
one member, or many members, of the exchanges,'' said Melamed.
   ``What matters is that we use this opportunity to act responsibly
and make improvements where they are necessary,'' he added. ``There
will be no sacred cows.''
   The panel is made up of five industry officials and five former
or current public officials, among them former Sen. Thomas Eagleton,
D-Missouri.
   ``The Justice Department has no quarrel with me,'' Melamed said.
``While we don't know what they were doing, that doesn't mean we are
on the opposite side of the intent. We're going to use this
opportunity. Here is an environment in which we can make this a
model exchange.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
