<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0307</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices turned downward today as traders
cashed in on the market's recent gains.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 3.39 to 2,262.50
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 9 to 5 in the early tally of
New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 310 up, 565 down and 549
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 24.92 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Selling was encouraged by rising interest rates in the credit
markets. Prices of long-term government bonds, which move in the
opposite direction from interest rates, fell by nearly $5,000 for
each $1,000 in face value.
   Analysts said stock and bond traders were unsettled a bit by word
of a 6.4 percent rise in new factory orders for durable goods last
month.
   That figure, which came in well above advance estimates, was
interpreted as a sign of persistent strength in the economy.
   Traders apparently concluded that it would serve as one more
incentive for the Federal Reserve to maintain a relatively
restrictive credit policy.
   Losers among the blue chips included General Motors, down ] at
89{; Sears Roebuck, down [ at 41{; DuPont, down { at 98, and Eastman
Kodak, down \ at 46~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
.34 to 161.99. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .24 at 319.26.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 9.46 to
2,265.89.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by nearly 4 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 803 up, 627 down and 539 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 183.61 million shares, against 189.62
million in the previous session.
