<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1344EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Media     01-26 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Media,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Jones Reports 14.5 Percent Earnings Drop; Time Inc. Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. on Thursday reported a 12 percent earnings increase in
the fourth quarter of 1988, but Dow Jones &amp; Co. said a yearlong
financial advertising slump was to blame for a 14.5 percent drop in
profits in the period.
   A.H. Belo Corp., owner of The Dallas Morning News and broadcast
properties, said earnings fell about 51 percent in the quarter,
partly because of an asset write-down.
   Time, based in New York, reported earnings of $58 million, or
$1.01 a share, on revenue of $1.21 billion. That was up from $52
million, or 88 cents a share, on revenue of $1.13 billion in the
corresponding 1987 quarter.
   Time said the increase came despite a $35 million pre-tax charge
to reduce the value on its books of a satellite 50 percent owned by
Home Box Office Inc., a Time subsidiary.
   Operating profits from Time's magazines were $87 million, up from
$81 million a year earlier, while cable television profits increased
to $57 million from $40 million in the 1987 period.
   For the full year, earnings were up 16 percent to $289 million,
or $5.01 a share, on revenue of $4.51 billion. In 1987, they were
$250 million, or $4.18 a share, on revenue of $4.19 billion.
   New York-based Dow Jones reported earnings of $43.1 million, or
43 cents a share, on revenue of $413 million in the fourth quarter.
That was down from $50.3 million, or 52 cents a share, on revenue of
$417 million in the corresponding 1987 quarter.
   For the full year, Dow Jones earnings increased 12.4 percent to
$228 million, or $2.35 a share, on revenue of $1.6 billion, compared
to profits of $203 million, or $2.10 a share, on revenue of $1.31
billion in 1987.
   But without $29.4 million in income from sale of its Richard D.
Irwin Inc. book-publishing subsidiary in early 1987, Dow Jones would
have posted an earnings decline for 1988.
   It said Wall Street Journal advertising linage declined 11.6
percent overall and Barron's advertising fell 16.3 percent last year.
   In the wake of the October 1987 stock market crash, circulation
of both influential financial publications also fell, with the
Monday-to-Friday Journal dropping 4.8 percent to 1.95 million and
the weekly Barron's slipping 13.4 percent to 246,500.
   A.H. Belo said earnings for the fourth quarter were $2.5 million,
or 12 cents per share, compared with $5.1 million, or 25 cents per
share, for the same quarter in the previous year.
   The company blamed the drop partly on a write-down of syndicated
programming and higher newsprint cost.
   Net income for all of 1988 were $10.1 million, or 51 cents per
share, compared with $22.3 million, or $1.04 per share, in 1987.
   In addition to the Morning News, A.H. Belo owns WFAA-TV of
Dallas, KHOU-TV of Houston, a Dallas-Fort Worth suburban newspaper
chain, KXTV in Sacramento, Calif., WVEC-TV in Hampton-Norfolk, Va.,
and KOTV in Tulsa, Okla.
</TEXT>
