<HEAD>London Share Prices Rise Sharply</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to update.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose sharply Thursday on the London
Stock Exchange as continued institutional buying combined with a
lack of sellers in certain issues to produce sudden rises among the
leading shares.
   Dealers said the market continued to benefit from growing
optimism about interest rates, which has sparked renewed buying
interest among major institutions. Recent signs of a slowdown in
consumer spending have helped convince many participants that base
lending rates have peaked at their current 13 percent level.
   But the market still faced a test Friday with the scheduled
release of British current account data for December. The market
expects the December current account gap to narrow slightly.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed up 20.8
points, or 1.07 percent, at 1959.8.
   The narrower Financial Times 30-share index closed 20.5 points
higher at 1601.3. Volume was 624.5 million shares, down from 924.7
million shares a day earlier, but still well above the prevailing
level toward the end of last year.
   The Financial Times 500-share index was 1,104.02, up 11.38.
