<FIRST>r f BC-Standard&amp;Poor's     01-26 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Standard &amp; Poor's,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Standard &amp; Poors Reclassifies Several Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. said Thursday it has
reclassified four companies in its index of 500 stocks under
different industry groups to reflect the changing focus of the
companies.
   Owens Corning Fiberglass Corp., Whitman Corp., N.L. Industries
and Primerica were approved for transfer by the S&amp;P 500 Index
committee.
   Owens Corning was moved to the building materials group from a
miscellaneous heading because of its recent restructuring. Owens
Corning, which divested its aerospace and strategic materials
divisions in 1987, now gets most of its revenue from construction
products, mainly fiberglass products. It will represent 14.8 percent
of the market value of the S&amp;P Building Materials Group.
   Whitman has been transferred to foods from conglomerates after
selling several of its businesses, including Illinois Central
railroad. Its current operations include Pet Inc. and Pepsi Cola
Bottling. Whitman, formerly I.C. Industries, will represent 6.5
percent of the S&amp;P Foods group.
   N.L. Industries is now under the chemicals heading, transferred
from oil well equipment &amp; services after spinning off its petroleum
services business.
   Primerica will be recategorized under financial miscellaneous
from personal loans. Primerica is the new name for the former
commercial credit group which recently acquired Primerica Corp.
   N.L. will represent 2 percent of the chemicals group and
Primerica will represent 8.1 percent of the financial miscellaneous
group.
   The S&amp;P 500 is made up of 500 stock prices including 400
industrials, 40 utilities, 20 transportation and 40 financial
issues. The index is further broken down into 89 industry groups.
   The index is designed to provide investors with a representative
measure of overall stock market performance.
</TEXT>
