<DOCNO> AP890126-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1528EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CampbellSoup 1stLd-Writethru   01-26 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Campbell Soup, 1st Ld-Writethru,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>FTC Charges Campbell Soup Co. Deceptive in Advertising</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: CORRECTS ``low in fiber'' to ``high in fiber'' in graf 8, The
Commission. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campbell Soup Co. was deceptive in advertising
its soups as good for the heart without disclosing their high sodium
content, the Federal Trade Commission charged today.
   The company said it stands behind the ads in question, which are
no longer running, and will contest the commission's charge.
   The FTC complaint said Campbell did not have substantiation for
its claim that most of its soups ``make a positive contribution to a
diet that reduces the risk of heart disease.''
   The commission is seeking an order from an administrative law
judge that would forbid Campbell from asserting that soups
containing more than 500 milligrams of sodium per eight-ounce
serving are good for the heart without also stating the sodium
content of the soup.
   Campbell makes 70 different kinds of condensed soup, plus two
different low-sodium lines. The commission staff declined to discuss
what it knows about the sodium content of all the regular varieties,
but an inspection of six at a supermarket showed sodium levels
ranging from 710 milligrams for turkey vegetable to 910 milligrams
for chicken noodle.
   Sodium is part of sodium chloride, ordinary table salt, which
manufacturers add to food to enhance taste. A teaspoon of salt
contains about 2,000 milligrams or two grams of sodium.
   A committee of the National Academy of Sciences has recommended
that most Americans limit their sodium intake to 1,100 to 3,300
milligrams per day. Though 200 milligrams is considered adequate,
most Americans get 4,000 to 6,000 milligrams a day.
   The commission objected to a magazine ad which said the company's
soups were high in fiber, low in fat and cholesterol and high in
calcium when made with milk.
   Chicken noodle, it said, ``is low in fat and has just 15
milligrams of cholesterol. And that's especially good to know
because research tells us that a diet low in fat and cholesterol may
help reduce the risk of some forms of heart disease.''
   ``We are always supportive'' of health information in ads, said
William MacLeod, director of the commission's Bureau of Consumer
Protection.
   But health claims, if made, must not be directly undermined by
undisclosed facts, he said.
   ``If they don't advertise the heart-healthiness of the soup, this
(proposed) order wouldn't come into play,'' he said.
   Many experts contend that excess sodium leads to high blood
pressure, which is known to increase the risk of heart disease and
heart attack. But some dissenters argue that studies show some
people tolerate a wide range of sodium in the diet without change in
blood pressure while, for unknown reasons, other people are ``salt
sensitive,'' with pressure rising sharply once a threshold of sodium
concentration is passed.
   MacLeod acknowledged the scientific dispute, and said the
commission would rely heavily on last year's ``Report on Nutrition
and Health'' issued by the surgeon general, which said diets high in
sodium ``clearly contribute'' to high blood pressure.
   In Camden, N.J., Campbell spokesman David Hackney said, ``We
stand behind our advertising and we don't think it's misleading''
since the sodium content is disclosed on every can.
   The two-page magazine ad in question has not run since March
1988. Hackney said the company's decision to drop it had nothing to
do with the commission's investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890126-0269 </DOCNO>
