<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Dun&amp;Bradstreet     01-26 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Dun &amp; Bradstreet,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dun &amp; Bradstreet Posts Higher Quarterly, Annual Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp., a leading marketer of
business information, including the well-known Nielsen television
rating system, on Thursday reported higher profits for the fourth
quarter and all of 1988.
   The company netted $123.06 million, or 66 cents per share, for
the period ended Dec. 31, up 18 percent from earnings of $104.47
million, or 56 cents, in 1987. Revenue rose 11 percent to $1.13
billion from $1.02 billion.
   For the year it earned $498.96 million, or $2.67 a share, on
revenue of $4.26 billion. That was 14 percent higher than 1987
earnings of $439.05 million, or $2.36, and revenue of $3.78 billion.
   Last year was marked by the announcement of a major restructuring
in which the company said it would discontinue some businesses and
product lines. In December it sold the the Official Airline Guides,
which includes travel guides and magazines, to British publisher
Robert Maxwell for $750 million.
   The restructuring also included employee reductions,
consolidation and streamlining of computer and production facilities
and the phaseing out of the manual collection of household panel
information by Nielsen Marketing Research. ``Our 1988 results met
our expectations, and we believe the actions we have taken will
enhance D&amp;B's ability to sustain its strong operating performance in
1989 and beyond.'' Chairman Charles W. Moritz said in a statement.
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet said the pre-tax costs associated with the
restructuring exceeded by $32.05 million the pre-tax gain from the
sale of Official Airline Guides.
   The fourth-quarter results also included the $140 million cash
acquisition of American Credit Indemnity Co., the nation's leading
business credit-insurance company, from Commercial Credit Co. In
addition, Dun &amp; Bradstreet announced it acquired Logistics Data
Systems Inc., a worldwide supplier of software and systems for
retailers.
</TEXT>
