<FIRST>r f AM-Gulf&amp;Western-Garden     01-26 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gulf &amp; Western-Garden,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arena's Facelift Will Triple Pricey Box Seats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Madison Square Garden will shut down for the next
two summers for a $100-million makeover to expand amenities and
triple the number of exclusive box seats, Gulf &amp; Western Inc., the
arena's owner, said Thursday.
   The announcement effectively confirmed reports that Gulf &amp;
Western had decided against building a new Garden for $300 million
at another site and erecting a $1-billion office complex on the
Garden's current site.
   Garden President Richard H. Evans denied that a softening market
for office space had played a role in the decision.
   ``It may have had something to do with what went up on this site
if we moved,'' he said. ``It did not have anything to do with the
decision about whether or not we should move.''
   Fans attending sports and entertainment events will notice 40
percent more rest rooms, bigger concession areas with more varied
menus and the disappearance of about 10 percent of the cheapest
seats.
   There also will be better lighting and sound and an up-to-date
video display scoreboard, Evans told a news conference. The arena's
capacity will remain the same, about 20,000 depending on the event.
   The most extensive renovation will occur in the Garden's
adjoining theater, the Felt Forum, which will be turned around 180
degrees, given a new, modern stage and 1,500 more seats, bringing
capacity to 6,000, Evans said.
   The Garden will be closed June-August for two years to
accommodate the construction. The Felt Forum will close in September
for two years, reopening in September 1991 as the Forum Theater, he
said.
   The renovation will not interfere with the Garden's professional
basketball and hockey teams, the Knicks and Rangers, both of which
also are owned by Gulf &amp; Western. Evans said an alternate facility
was being sought for the Garden's boxing promotions while the Felt
Forum is closed.
</TEXT>
