<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     01-26 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises; Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign exchange traders pushed the dollar
slightly higher Thursday, again testing central banks' commitment to
holding the U.S. currency in check.
   Dealers said there was no firm reason for the dollar's climb,
although there was a brief rally after a report that U.S. durable
goods orders surged 6.4 percent in December. Many had expected a 0.3
percent rise.
   The dollar retreated somewhat when details showed some of the
gains were from large defense and transportation orders.
   The Federal Reserve sold some dollars for West German marks late
in New York's trading session, dealers said.
   The underlying demand for dollars comes from investors who want
to take advantage of relatively high U.S. interest rates, said
Phillip Eriksen, a senior vice president at Wells Fargo Bank in San
Francisco.
   High yields also have attracted investors to the Canadian and
Australian dollars and the British pound, Eriksen said. The Canadian
dollar touched a seven-year high against the U.S. dollar in
Thursday's session but ended slightly below Wednesday's level.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell to 127.52 Japanese yen from 127.65 late
Wednesday. In London late Thursday the dollar traded at 128.15 yen,
and later in New York the dollar rose to 128.32 yen from 127.43 late
Wednesday.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7730 from $1.7710 late
Tuesday. In New York, sterling fell to $1.7673 from $1.7708 late
Wednesday.
   Other late rates for the dollar in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8475 West German marks, up from
1.8405; 1.5705 Swiss francs, up from 1.5630; 1.1850 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1841; 6.2833 French francs, up from 6.2553; and
1,351.6 Italian lire, up from 1,345.5.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with
Wednesday's late rates, included: 1.8440 West German marks, up from
1.8435; 1.5671 Swiss francs, up from 1.5670; 6.2705 French francs,
down from 6.2715; 2.0815 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0820; 1,350.25
Italian lire, down from 1,350.50; and 1.1816 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1840.
   Gold bullion rose by about $1.50 a troy ounce in Europe but fell
later in New York.
   The closing price in London and Zurich was a bid of $405.75 a
troy ounce, up from $404.25 in both cities Wednesday. Earlier in
Hong Kong, gold closed at $407.70 a troy ounce, up from $406.57.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $403 an ounce from $406 on Wednesday. Later,
Republic National Bank of New York quoted gold bullion at $402 an
ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down from $405.25 late Wednesday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid of $6.19 a troy
ounce, up from $6.12. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery fell to $6.104 an ounce from $6.17 Wednesday.
</TEXT>
