<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds 1stLd-Writethru   01-26 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds, 1st Ld-Writethru,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rise For Third Straight Week To Another Record Level</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS third graf pvs, ``The Investment...$120.43 billion'' to
CORRECT $2.4 million to $240.8 million. Interest rate figures reported
by Donoghue's Money Fund Report are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures
are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 454 money market mutual
funds rose $737.2 million in the latest week, reaching a record
level for the third straight week, the Investment Company Institute
said Thursday.
   The rise, to $285.34 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a much bigger rise of $2.2 billion in the funds'
assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual
fund trade group. It was the third consecutive week in which the
assets have expanded to a new high.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 137 institutional funds rose $1.05 billion to $74.99
billion. Assets of 226 general purpose funds fell $240.8 million to
$89.92 billion and holdings in 91 broker-dealer funds dropped $73.7
million to $120.43 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.38 percent from 8.35 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 8.34 percent from 8.30 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 32
days, compared to 30 days the week before, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan associations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
6.28 percent as of Wednesday from 6.26 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, remained at 5.13 percent, unchanged from the week before.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.33
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 8.30 the
previous week. Yields were 8.58 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 8.54
percent; 8.67 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 8.65 percent; and 8.79
percent on 5-year CDs, up from 8.77 percent.
</TEXT>
