<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     01-26 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0584</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices took a roller coaster ride Thursday while
wheat advanced and corn was mostly higher on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Soybeans bounced back in early trading from Wednesday's losses of
up to 18\ cents, then lost ground before the final bell and settled
up 12 cents for March spot contract.
   ``After the market failed yesterday, traders were very jittery,''
said Mickey Luth, soybeans analyst in Chicago for Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc.
   Confirmation of U.S. soymeal sales to the Soviet Union supported
soybean futures, but hurting prices were expectations of a good crop
from South America, said Luth.
   Wheat and corn prices were boosted by Agriculture Department
moves strengthening the possibility of more sales of those two
commodities to the Soviet Union, said G.H. Miller analyst Jerry
Gidel in Chicago.
   Wheat settled 3 cents to 4\ cents higher, with the contract for
delivery in March at $4.44 a bushel; corn was { cent lower to 1{
cents higher, with March at $2.71} a bushel; oats were 4 cents to 5\
cent lower, with March at $2.20 a bushel; and soybeans were 8} cents
to 13 cents higher, with March at $7.54 a bushel.
   Futures prices for pork were off sharply and cattle traded mostly
lower on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   The markets suffered from concerns about oversupply and mix
demand, said Paul Hare of Linnco Futures Inc.
   But traders said figures from U.S. Agriculture Department
cattle-on-feed reports released after the day's trading sesssion
were near expectations.
   Live cattle settled .10 cent to .48 cent lower, with the contract
for delivery in February at 72.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were
.45 cent lower to .07 cent higher, with January at 83.20 cents a
pound; live hogs were .07 cent to .70 cent lower, with February at
42.70 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .82 cent to 1.08
cents lower, with February at 38.82 cents a pound.
   Precious metals prices declined on the Commodity Exchange in New
York.
   The continuing strength of the U.S. dollar, crude oil prices
backing off and no definitive statement from Thursday's OPEC meeting
all weighed on gold and silver prices, said William O'Neill,
director of research in New York for Elders Futures Inc.
   Gold settled $2.60 to $3.60 lower, with the contract for delivery
in January at $403 a troy ounce; and silver was 6.6 cents to 7.2
cents lower, with January at $6.104 a troy ounce.
   Coffee prices moved higher on the Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa
Exchange in New York.
   ``We were a little stronger today _ mainly over fears of a
general strike in Brazil over the new economic program would halt
shipments of coffee,'' said New York analyst Kim Badenhop of Merrill
Lynch Capital Markets Inc. ``The market has been very volatile and
it remains very volatile,''
   Coffee settled 1.68 cents to 3.48 cents higher, with the contract
for delivery in March at $1.37.72 a pound.
   Energy futures prices tumbled on the New York Mercantile Exchange
as traders were disappointed over the outcome of a meeting between
OPEC and independent oil-producing nations.
   Crude oil settled 36 cents to 45 cents lower, with the contract
for delivery in March at $17.72 a barrel; and hearing oil was 1.34
cents to 1.66 cents lower, with February at 50.87 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
