<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Mead     01-26 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Mead,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mead Reports Higher Quarterly, Annual Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mead Corp. on Thursday reported its fourth
quarter income rose 31 percent, partly due to the sale of its
Brunswick Pulp &amp; Paper Company.
   Mead, a paper products and electronic publishing company, also
attributed its financial performance last year to strong demand for
its products in the United States and abroad, high production and
improved margins.
   The company said fourth quarter earnings were $43.4 million or 68
cents a share, compared to $33.2 million or 53 cents a share, during
the corresponding 1987 period.
   For all of last year, earnings were up about 63 percent to $352.7
million, or $5.37 a share, from $216.7 million, or $3.45 a share, in
1987.
   Excluding one-time gains from the sale of assets in both 1988 and
1987, earnings came to $240.8 million or $3.70 per share, compared
with $175.5 million or $2.79 per share for 1987.
   During the fourth quarter, the company made $11.2 million after
completing final arrangements for the sale of Brunswick to
Georgia-Pacific Corp.
   Sales for 1988 climbed 6 percent to $4.5 billion, compared to
$4.2 billion in 1987. Fourth quarter sales, however, were down 2
percent to $1 billion from $1.1 billion a year ago.
   ``Paper and paperboard markets were strong all year,'' said Mead
Chairman Burnell Roberts. ``We operated at near-capacity levels,
backlogs were sizeable and net selling prices improved across our
grade lines.''
   On Dec. 30, Mead acquired the Michie Company, a legal publishing
company with sales of $34 million. The acquisition is expected to
decrease 1989 earnings per share by approximately 25 cents.
</TEXT>
