<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Brokerage     01-26 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Brokerage,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>PaineWebber Group Profit Drops Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investment giant PaineWebber Group Inc. said
Thursday its profit plunged 93 percent in the fourth quarter and
fell 41 percent for all of 1988, reflecting a slowdown in the
financial market and onetime costs.
   Donald B. Marron, chairman and chief executive, said sharp
declines in retail and institutional volume in the wake of the
October 1987 crash more than offset improvement in merchant banking
and asset mangement activities.
   He said the firm took steps to improve productivity by cutting
support staff, consolidating offices and shrinking marginal
businesses, and said it would ``continue to rigorously pursue'' that
program.
   PaineWebber said its profit fell to $512,000 in the three months
ended Dec. 31 compared with $7.0 million, or 16 cents a share, a
year earlier.
   Payment of preferred stock dividends left the company with a loss
of 20 cents per share in the latest quarter.
   Fourth-quarter revenue rose 28.7 percent to $696 million from
$541 million a year earlier.
   The latest results included non-recurring expenses of $13
million, including $8 million from a previously-disclosed legal
settlement involving Washington Public Power Supply System
securities and $5 million related to the relocation of the firm's
systems and operations functions to New Jersey.
   For the year, PaineWebber earned $42.4 million, or 58 cents per
share, compared with $72 million, or $2.17 per share, in 1987.
   Revenue for the year edged up to $2.51 billion from $2.44 billion
in 1987.
   The full-year results reflected $20 million in costs due to the
back-office relocation and $20 million due to the WPPSS settlement.
</TEXT>
