<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 2048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ComputerViruses 1stLd-Writethru f0243 01-26 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Computer Viruses, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0243,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warn About Global Computer Disaster</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 8th graf bgng, It didn't ... and 10th graf bgng ``The virus
apparently ... '' to CORRECT name to McLoughlin, sted McLaughlin. Also
moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world may be heading toward a catastrophic
computer failure unless more effective measures are taken to combat
computer viruses, a leading U.S. computer security specialist said
Thursday.
   Professor Lance J. Hoffman of George Washington University said
the virus which affected the Pentagon's ARPANET computer network
last November ``could have had very disastrous consequences for our
society.''
   ``It wasn't Chernobyl yet, it was the Three Mile Island _ it woke
a lot of people up,'' Hoffman told a delegation of Japanese computer
specialists touring this country to assess the virus problem.
   He was alluding to the catastrophic explosion and fire that
wracked a nuclear power plant in the Soviet Ukraine in April 1986,
along with the much less severe partial meltdown which occurred at
the TMI atomic power station near Harrisburg, Pa., in March 1979.
   Hoffman added: ``Unfortunately, I think the Chernobyl may well
happen. We are not out of the woods.''
   Viruses are generally small strings of computer codes that can be
stealthily inserted into software programs, causing a variety of
problems including destruction of computer data and sudden clogging
of a computer's memory with thousands of copies of the virus.
   At the same George Washington University meeting, a staff member
from the Library of Congress disclosed that a virus had been found
last fall within the massive institution's main catalog computer
system.
   ``It didn't cause any damage. It was identified before it could
spread or permanently erase any data,'' said Glenn McLoughlin, a
computer science specialist with the Science Policy Research
Division of the library's Congressional Research Service.
   He said the virus was found after personnel logging onto
computers at the library noticed they had substantially less
computer memory space to work with than they had expected.
   The virus apparently got into the Library of Congress system,
McLoughlin said, through a piece of software obtained from the
University of Maryland.
   ``We don't know whether it was a student at Maryland, or whether
Maryland had gotten it from somebody else. That was simply the
latest point of departure for the software,'' he said.
   The six-man Japanese delegation attending Thursday's briefing was
winding up a 10-day tour of the United States. Their itinerary also
included visits to the San Francisco area, Los Angeles, New York
City, International Business Machines Corp. offices in Purchase,
N.Y., and Lehigh University, Bethlehem, Pa.
   The group's head, Tomihisa Naito, president of S.G. Engineering
Company Ltd., a Tokyo-based firm dealing with factory automation,
commented that many people in both the United States and Japan still
``do not recognize the importance of protecting computer systems.''
   ``Information in computers has a lot of power nowadays, so people
should be aware of the possibility that that information can be
contaminated,'' he said.
   Edwin B. Heinlein, a computer security consultant from San
Rafael, Calif., who helped arrange the Japanese visit, said he
agreed with Hoffman's assessment that the chances are ``very good''
for a disastrous computer virus incident.
   ``You can make all the laws you want, but only ethical behavior
will keep people from doing bad things,'' Heinlein said. Despite
safeguards now being introduced in many computer systems, he said,
``there's always going to be a loophole, or somebody being able to
take advantage of things.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890126-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 2055EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Airlines     01-26 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Airlines,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAL's Profit Drops in Fourth Quarter; Delta's Down Slightly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The parent of United Airlines reported Thursday that its net
income dropped sharply in the fourth quarter from a year earlier,
mainly as a result of accounting changes. Delta Air Lines blamed
rising operating expenses for a 4 percent decline in its profit for
its latest quarter.
   Chicago-based UAL Corp. said its net income for the three months
ended Dec. 31 fell to $20.87 million, or 97 cents a share, from
$209.9 million, or $3.68 a share, a year earlier.
   The company said the per-share comparison isn't meaningful
because of a substantial reduction in the number of shares
outstanding due to a self-tender offer in the first quarter of 1988.
The average number of shares used to compute per-share earnings
dropped to 21,570 in the fourth quarter from 57,100 a year earlier.
   Fourth-quarter revenue rose to $2.22 billion from $2.10 billion
in the year-earlier quarter.
   UAL said the drop in net income for the quarter was mainly due to
a downward adjustment to a previously reported gain on the sale of
the company's non-airline subsidiaries.
   UAL, formerly named Allegis Corp., decided in 1987 to reverse its
travel conglomerate strategy and focus on its core airline business.
The subsidiaries _Hilton International Co., Hertz Corp. and Westin
Hotel Co. _ were sold to fulfill that goal. United Airlines is the
nation's largest carrier.
   The company said additional costs related to the sales of the
units led to a reduction of $24.5 million in the previously reported
gain of $548.5 million.
   For 1988 as a whole, UAL's net income tripled to $1.12 billion,
or $37.87 a share, from $335.1 million, or $6.02 a share, in 1987.
   Again, the per-share comparison isn't considered meaningful.
   Revenue for the year increased 8.2 percent to $8.98 billion from
$8.30 billion the previous year.
   ``Our goal is to position United as qualitatively best, which
will enable us to produce the earnings necessary to fund a prudent
capital spending plan and to provide the security and work
environment our employees so justly deserve,'' said Stephen M. Wolf,
UAL's chairman, president and chief executive officer.
   Atlanta-based Delta said its net income for the second quarter of
its fiscal year slipped to $85.1 million, or $1.73 a share, from
$88.3 million, or $1.82 a share, in the year-earlier quarter.
   Delta, the nation's third-largest carrier, blamed the decline on
a 12 percent rise in operating expenses in the quarter ended Dec. 31.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 9 percent, to $1.86 billion from
$1.70 billion a year earlier.
   ``While revenues continued to show good growth at over 9 percent
for the quarter, operating expenses rose 12 percent, resulting in
the lower earnings,'' said Thomas J. Roeck, Delta's senior vice
president of finance and chief financial officer.
   ``Increases in salaries and related costs, maintenance expenses
and commissions were the primary factors in this increase in
expenses,'' Roeck said.
   For the first six months of its fiscal year, Delta's net income
increased 26 percent to $185.1 million, or $3.76 a share, from
$147.4 million, or $3.03 a share, in the same 1987 period.
   Six-month revenue was up 12 percent, to $3.74 billion from $3.29
billion.
</TEXT>
