<HEAD>Northwest Airlines Cuts Memphis Flights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines will cut back on its
flights from Memphis on May 1 and lay off or transfer as many as 400
workers, an airline spokesman said Thursday.
   ``We are going to make Memphis a more marketable hub and a much
more efficient hub,'' said Northwest spokesman Alan Muncaster.
   The number of Northwest's round-trip flights from Memphis will be
reduced from 165 to about 150, the airline said.
   Muncaster said the carrier will have exact figures on flights and
job cuts by mid-February. Some 2,600 workers are employed in Memphis
by Northwest, which is based in Eagan, Minn.
   Most of the laid-off employees will be ground service workers and
mechanics. Some employees will be allowed to transfer to other
cities, Muncaster said.
