<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 2350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-McDonald's     01-26 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-McDonald's,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profit Up 17 Percent in 4th Qtr, 18 Percent for Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAK BROOK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonald's Corp., which operates the
nation's largest fast-food restaurant chain, said Thursday its
profit climbed 17 percent in the fourth quarter and was up 18
percent for all of 1988.
   ``McDonald's performance in 1988 reflects several milestones,''
Chairman Fred L. Turner said. ``Systemwide sales exceeded $16
billion, pretax income surpassed $1 billion and we sold our 70
billionth hamburger.''
   For the three months ended Dec. 31, McDonald's said it earned
$151.5 million, or 81 cents per share, compared with $129.6 million,
or 68 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Revenue rose 15 percent in the quarter to $1.45 billion from
$1.27 billion a year earlier. Systemwide sales, which include sales
at franchised restaurants as well as those that McDonald's owns and
operates itself, were up 13 percent in the quarter to $4.14 billon
from $3.68 billion a year earlier.
   Net income for the year rose to $645.9 million, or $3.43 a share,
from $549 million, or $2.89 a share, a year earlier.
   Revenue rose 14 percent for the year to $5.57 billion from $4.89
billion in 1987. Systemwide sales increased 12 percent for the year
to $16.06 bllion from $14.33 bllion in 1987.
   For the year, average sales for McDonald's restuarants open at
least one year, a key measurement of fast-food industry performance,
rose to $1.596 million from $1.502 million in 1987.
   U.S. sales benefitted from the introduction of salads in 1987,
growth in breakfast sales and the successful marketing of such
promotions as Monopoly II and games tied to the Olympics, the
company said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890126-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 2310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AlleghenyInternational     01-26 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Allegheny International,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Files Revised Plan Of Reorganization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. on Thursday filed
a revised reorganization plan, saying it may sell its flagship Oster
and Sunbeam home appliance divisions to help bring the company out
of Chapter 11 bankruptcy.
   The consumer products concern said it has signed a letter of
intent to sell the Milwaukee-based appliance unit, as previously
disclosed, for $260 million to Black &amp; Decker Corp., a maker of
household appliances based in Towson, Md.
   But Allegheny International did not say how the rest of its
estimated $700 million debt would be paid.
   The plan would leave the company in the possession of its own
stockholders. But preferred and preference shareholders would own 82
percent of the stock in the reorganized company, while current
owners of common stock would emerge owning only 18 percent.
   Allegheny International said all creditors will be paid all they
were owed on the day the company filed for protection under federal
bankruptcy laws 11 months ago. Many of those creditors have been
demanding interest and attorney fees.
   A consortium of banks, whose $200 million in Allegheny
International loans are secured by the company's assets, would get
their money back plus $17 million, the company said. But they would
lose much interest that has accumulated since the company declared
bankrupcty.
   In exchange, shareholders would drop a suit charging unfair
pressure from the banks helped speed Allegheny International into
bankruptcy, the company said.
   Under a bankruptcy court ruling, Allegheny International has
until March 31 to convince shareholders and creditors to support the
plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890126-0298 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 0046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-IllinoisCentral-ADM     01-26 0116</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Illinois Central-ADM,0122</SECOND>
<HEAD>ADM To Take 15 Percent Stake In Illinois Central</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archer Daniels Midland Co. plans to increase its
stake in Illinois Central Transportation Co. to at least 15 percent,
Illinois Central disclosed Wednesday.
   Illinois Central issued a two-sentence statement that said ADM,
the huge commodity processor based in Decatur in central Illinois,
planned to buy more shares on top of the 1.6 million recently
acquired.
   Last week, ADM told Illinois Central that it had acquired 1.6
million shares, or 8 percent of all outstanding stock, for
``investment purposes.''
   Richard E. Burket, an ADM vice president, would not come to
telephone late Wednesday for questions about the new stock purchase.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
